    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Today we are announcing the discovery of the star-planet system we are calling Brezur. This Star-planet system is very special because it provides a planet that is a condidate for being habitable meaning it is potentially capable of being home to alien life. The planet that orbits this star is much like our own planet Earth. It is 1.30 Re which means that it has a radius 30% larger than that of our earth meaning it is slightly bigger. It has a density of 3.5 g/cm3 meaning that every cubic centimeter weighs an average of 3.5 grams, so basically has a rock type density much like earth. Other similarities include the planet's atmosphere which has a strong greenhouse effect meaning it retains heat in the atmosphere and ends of heating the planet, just like our atmosphere does. 
Now there are also some differences between the Brezur system and outr own sun-earth system. First of all Brezur the sun is significantly smaller than our sun, and emit less energy. When it comes to mass Brezur is 62% lighter than our sun, we can tell this by the luinosity which is .0338 Ls. This would be like cuting the sun into threes. When it comes to the energy it emits since this star is smaller it emits less energy. Its like if we had two light bulbs one 100 W normal lightbulb be the sun and a 40W small lamp lightbulb. If the bigger lightbulb brightly lights up a whole room the smaller bulb will still light up the room but it will be dimmer. The other difference between the Brezur system and our own is the the distance between the star and the planet. The planet is about a fifth of the distance from Brezur than earth is from the sun. The exact numbers is .219 AU, hat is closer than mercury is to our sun. This numebr would equal about 20,428,150 miles, which to put into perspective is about 360 million footbal fields. 
This star is 4.4 light years away ( a light year is how much distance light covers in a year) meaning it would take over 150,000 year to reach this star at our current space travels speed. Although it will be a long time before we could develop the technology to reach this planet, it is important to search for signs of life to see if this planet is habitabe,these signs of life are what we call biosignitures. These are any type of substances that provide evidence of past or present life. Some of the things we might be looking out for materials in these planets are were created by life and not by anything else, so this could include any waste, chemical compunds or even things with disticnt shape and sizes that could only be explanied as being created by life. Ofcourse in order to find these type of evidence we will need advanced technology that can look for this type of evidence from here on our own planet. 
Who knows maybe one day we could find life on this planet that orbits Brezur.</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The star-planet system I discovered is a little different from our own. The star’s name is Babu and it has a temperature of 8244 K. It is 74.10 lightyears away from us and is approximately twice the size and mass of our Sun. It is expected to live for a billion and a half years. The habitable planet found in this system is also roughly twice the size and mass of the Earth. It is about 36% closer to its star compared to where the Earth is from the Sun and orbits around its star every 130 days. Water can be found in this planet and although its surface temperature is really high at 554.6 K, the atmospheric pressure allows the planet to have liquid water. One of the biosignatures to look for is methane but this does not necessarily indicate life by itself but a possibility for it. Another is oxygen which shows us that there are living creatures that conducts oxygenic photo phototrophy. H2O or water is present in this planet which tells us that oxygen making organisms can be found.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The system that this planet (Cudegan) is in is not extremely different from our system including the earth and the sun. The star's luminosity is about 11 times larger than that of our sun and will live about 10% as long as the sun. The planet itself lies about 4.3 times the distance from the earth to the sun from its host star. This planet has a mass of about 5.6 times that of the earth, 2.1 times its radius, and a density of 3.27g/cm3. This density value allows us to infer that the planet is a rocky, terrestrial world. Considering its surface pressure is 10 times that of earth and it's atmosphere contains essential greenhouse gases (including water) it has a strong greenhouse effect. This means that even though the planet's effective temperature is about 232k, on the surface it would likely be something like 332k which is very habitable. The way that we know the atmosphere contains numerous greenhouse gases is from its gas emission spectrum, which shows us all (most) of the elements present in the atmosphere.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Daphion is an Earth-like star-planet system residing just 4.4 light years away. It's star is about 33 times dimmer than the Sun but the planet orbits it's star about 5 times closer than the Earth does the Sun. Along with it's close proximity to it's star, Daphion's planet contains a strong atmospheric greenhouse effect, which allows it to maintain a consistent temperature. Daphion's star is over 100 billion times the age of the Sun, which means that life on the planet orbiting the star has had that much more time to evolve compared to life on Earth. The planet orbiting the Daphion star system is about 1/3 more massive than the Earth and has the capacity to retain liquid water. The planet's atmosphere contains the same gases found in Earth's atmosphere and the presence of oxygen in the form of ozone suggests that photosynthetic life forms exist at the planet's surface. Because of the planet's strong greenhouse effect, the surface temperature of the planet averages about 170 degrees farenheit. Coupled with the presence of Methane in the atmosphere, scientists might primarily look for biosignatures of methanogens and bacteria that prefer higher temperatures.  </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Crabiltia

My best candidate for a habitable planet is Crabiltia. Crabiltia is 60.4 lightyears away. Lightyear is the distance that light can travel in a year. Astronomers use lightyears to measure the large distances in space. 
1 light year (ly) = 5.87849981 × 10^12 miles
Crabiltia is therefore 3.55061389 × 10^14 miles away.

Host Star Characteristics

Habitable planets need a host star which fuels the planet with energy for life.
In Earth, the Sun is our host star which has a luminosity of 1. Luminosity is the amount of energy emitted by a star. It shouldn't be confused with brightness which is the reflection of light. 
1 luminosity (Ls)= 3.846×10^26 W
 The luminosity of the host star of Crabiltia is 21 and has a projected lifetime of 1.13 x 10^9 years.

Planet Characteristics

The distance of our planet from its host star is measure in astronomical unit(AU). AU is a unit of length reflecting the distance from the Earth to the Sun. The distance between our planet and host star is also about 1 AU.
1 Astronomical Unit = 92 955 807.3 mile
Comparing our planet's mass to Earth, we find that it is about 6 times Earth's mass(6Me). 1 earth mass = 1.31664252 × 10^25 pounds
Crabiltia also has a radius of 2 compared to Earth (Re).
1 Re = 3 963.1676 miles
The density of Crabiltia is 3.411 g/cm³ compared to Earth which has 5.51 g/cm³.
The surface pressure of Crabiltia is 22.5 atm. and it has an effective temperature of 339 K. The effective temperature of a body such as a star or planet is the temperature of a black body that would emit the same total amount of electromagnetic radiation. Kelvin is the unit of temperature used for planets and stars. 1 K= -457.87 F.
In this case, our planet has a temperature of 399 K or 258.53 F.
This effective temperature tells us how much energy is received without counting what is reflected or absorbed by the atmosphere. The real temperature depends on the greenhouse effect as well. Greenhouse effect  accounts for the temperature that is absorbed and radiated back to space.
A  weak effect is from 0-40%; this adds 10K
A  moderate effect is 40-60%; this add 30K
A strong effect is from 60-100%; this adds 100K

The elements in our planet are critical for its habitability. Carbon, Hydrogen, Nitrogen, Oxygen, Phosphorus, and Sulfur are among the most important elements that we need to survive. Methane, bacteria, climate,water and an atmosphere are also essential elements we need to look for if we want to find organisms and life.

</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>A potentially habitable planet, Conyan, has been discovered orbiting a host star that is approximately 40 times less luminous than our sun; that is it emits 40 times less energy. As a result, the planet must orbit the star much closer than the Earth orbits the sun in order to have temperatures that would support liquid water. Conyan orbits its host star at about 0.23 astronomical units, this is4.4 times closer than Earth orbits the sun. At this distance, the surface temperature of the planet is predicted to be approximately -40°C. How can a planet this cold possibly support liquid water and possibly life? The greenhouse effect! Much like how carbon dioxide in the atmosphere makes Earth hotter, the presence of greenhouse gasses on Cayman raises the predicted temperature to a cozy 60°C.

So what is this planet like? Its density suggests it is a mixture of ice/water and rock. This is different than our home planet which, even though it has vast oceans, is mostly made up of rock and metal. With a radius of 1.5 times that of Earth, and a mass 2.2 times that of Earth, this planet is not so different from our own. It is still a rocky world that can host liquid water. And with an atmospheric pressure greater than one would experience at the top Mt. Everest, Conyan is a promising looking planet.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We believe we have found a habitable planet!  This habitable planet is about 95.9 light years away which is quite far, but is certainly a magnificent discovery, and this is why.  We believe there to be many planets in the galaxy that are habitable, but we have most recently settled on the planet, "Carkatrass", which portrays many Earth-like features that are capable of producing life.  Firstly, this planet surrounds a star that has a luminosity that is much smaller than that of our own sun. This means that the output of energy of radiation emitted by this star is smaller which therefore creates a smaller flux of energy.  With that, the overall effective temperature is much lower than it could be on this planet if it were closer to it's sun.  An effective temperature is based overall from the radiated energy emitted from the star it surrounds without the other variables that come into play (this may include pressure, greenhouse effect, and distance from the sun).  With the distance being about 90 billion meters further away, it needs to be completely capable of holding radiated heat from the sun or it will not survive.  In this instance, it does.  The effective temperature of this planet is approximately 183.2 Kelvin or about -129 degrees Fahrenheit, which is an exceptionally freezing temperature.  This is due to the distance Carkatrass is away from its sun as well as it's albedo (The amount of reflected light or radiation).  Consequently, the Greenhouse Effect is strong on this planet which adds approximately 100 Kelvin to the effective temperature, therefore making it about 50 degree Fahrenehit.  This is definitely a habitable temperature to be in.  The Greenhouse Effect is able to create a more habitable environment because there is a higher absorption rate in the gases, which proposes a higher temperature because the radiation of heat and energy trying to leave the atmosphere to get back to space is less.  More maintained energy in Carkatrass' atmosphere makes the temperatures exceedingly warmer.  With the proposed surface temperature, this would likely lead to a drier, desert-like climate.  It is definitely evident that Carkatrass is planet at which there is capability of sustaining life.  There are numerous elements that play into the effects of being able to produce life, and with the current information at hand, we believe this to be so.  Though there is no way of knowing in advance which organisms are universal to other planets or just peculiar to Earth, there is certainly a chance that there is a DNA compound to be found there.  The conditions of this planet are all pointing to the life-like structures that are present on our own Earth.  With much research and extensive data, we have found a likely habitable world outside of our own. This means that there could possibly be other intelligent life in our galaxy! </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Today it was announced that  world-renowned astrophysicist Joseph Picarella has discovered what could possibly be an Earth-like planet on which life may exist! 

The planet, which orbits a star named Deri which was also discovered by Picarella, is a rocky one just like our own. While Deri is relatively dim in comaprison to our Sun (it is only about 3 percent as luminous as the Sun), the planet in question is still beleived to be in the "goldilocks" zone due to the fact that it is much closer to Deri than we are to the Sun. To put it in perspective, the newly found planet is roughly only 22 percent of the distance from its star as we are from our Sun. 

Because of this relatively close orbit to its star, it is likely to contain liquid water since it gets just the right amount of energy from Deri. 

Some other notable characteristics of this planet are the fact that it is just under 1.5 times as massive as Earth, it has roughly 1.3 times the radius of Earth, and its surface pressure is estimated to be 1.55 times that of Earth's.

At only 4.4 light years away (meaning that at the speed of light it would take 4.4 years to get there) this system is relaively close which is very exciting for the team that is researching it. 

The next step for Picarella will be to study the atmosphere of this planet (if there is one) to determine whether or not the planet has any biosignatures. Biosignatures are the existence of gasses like oxygen or carbon dioxide which usually are the waste products of different types of living beings like plants or mammals like us. In order to look for an atmosphere and any biosignatures that it may contain, the scientists will have to wait until the planet moves in front of its star in order to study the light that passes through the areas where an atmosphere would be. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The star we found with the best opportunities for a habitable world is named Ainiomnu on my star sheet. It is a staggering 4.4 light years away from us and comes in at around 3% as luminous as our own sun and 38% the size. It has an expected lifetime of about 112 billion years. Our mystery planet comes in with an orbit of about 1/5 the distance our earth is from the sun and an orbit that repeats six times as often as our own. The mass of the planet is almost 1.4 times that of our own and the radius is 1.3 times longer. This leaves us with a density of about 3.5 g/cm^3 which tells us our planet is terrestrial. Based on these numbers, we found the effective temperature of our planet to be about -11.47 degrees Fahrenheit, but luckily there are a lot of trace gasses present in the atmosphere to keep in our planet’s energy. This fortunately allowed us to predict that the surface temperature of our planet will have a range up to 160 degrees Fahrenheit on the surface. The pressure on our planet is a little higher than that of earth, but enough to keep our water Liquid and away from the threat of a runaway greenhouse which would kill our water. The combination of these factors (along with the knowledge that most of the other planets we found with liquid water would crush us or cause us to faint without pressure suits) has allowed us to select this planet as the prime candidate for a habitable world. Some biosignatures we can look for include readings of methane, oxygen and other gasses that would allow organisms to metabolize effectively, but we won’t be able to tell if we get false negatives or positives without some more extensive research into the planet because enough sinks for those gasses may exist in the environment on the ground, or the flux from our star could get in the way of our readings.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My candidate, Ethgarec, is an ideal habitable planet due to its many characteristics that I have observed. In order to explaing my planet though, I must first explain my star. My host star has a low mass from my calculations  and this allows it to have a longer projected lifetime. My  star had enough luminosity so that when it is combined with my planet's distance it provides the appropriate amount of brightness, energy, that my planet needs to be an ideal candidate for a habitable planet. Moving on to my planet Ethgarec we can see that  the distance from the star is close enough that when combined with the Greenhouse Effect from the planet's gasses we are given both the ideal temperature to maintain water in its liquid form on the planet. Without the greenhouse effect my planet would have been to cold and the water would have been in a solid state. The greenhouse effect was able to strengthen my absorbtion rate which allowed me to add the additional 100 degrees that was needed to bring it to the liquid state. With the density of my planet I was able to determine that it was composed of a Rock/Metal composite which helps make my planet a potential candidate for habitability. If were to have been a water of gas planet we would not have had the necessary conditions to produce a habitable planet. The radius of my planet shows that helps us to determine the necessary temperature needed to have a planet that provides the correct gasses, temperature, and state of water needed to survive. With all of these things to consider I believe Ethgarec is proven to be a viable solution to a habitable planet. If provides the correct temperatures, pressure, state of water, distance from the star, and has a star with the correct luminosity and lifetime to sustain it.</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>A new habitable planet has been discovered recently by one Katherine (Katie) Broyles, circling the Star, Datroddyn.  This planet, Eden Prime, is located .22 Astronomical units, and is about three tenths larger than the Earth, with two fifths greater mass.  Though the density is less than Earth's by about two cubic centimeters, which still allows for a terrestrial surface.  With an effective temperature of 249.55 Kelvin (approximately -23.6 degrees Celsius) and the combination of the strong greenhouse effect that has been calculated, surface temperatures reach a balmy 349.55 degrees kelvin, or 76.4 degrees celsius.  Much Warmer than the Earth, however, it does hold the potential to host life.  
Further research into the planet will include looking closer at the biosignatures and determining if some of the elements and chemicals present may permit life on the planet.  For Earth, that would mean traces of carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, phosphorus, and sulfur, and though it is considered unfavorable, it is possible to have alternative elements to assist in the development of life. Keeping in mind the description of what a living being is (grows, develops, reacts to the environment, reproduces, adapts, and evolves), a probe may be needed to be sent to Eden Prime to examine possible activity by a living being.  The probe will also determine if a redox reaction is utlized by the life forms, or if phototryphy, gaining sustanance from sunlight, is used.  Levels of methane will also be determined, which could help to determining if Eden Prime could develop an atmosphere composition more similar to Earth's.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>PRESS RELEASE
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
APRIL 22, 2015


ARE WE REALLY ALONE IN THE UNIVERSE?

The age old question gains clarity as we find planets with the tools that could sustain life!

Area 51, (outside Las Vegas, NV) - 

The age old question, “Are we alone in the universe?” gained new light today as Brian Cunningham, resident super genius at Area 51, NV announced that the planet Durnavesh has been discovered with traits comparable to earth and compatible to potentially sustaining life.   At a press conference held at the Palms Casino and Resort, Cunningham summarized details of the findings in a report to later be published in Lil’Alien Times that Durnavesh had been discovered in a joint exploration project with a team of scientist at Arizona State University School of Earth and Space Exploration (SESE) by looking at a series of bio signatures and planetary conditions that would be essential for life to exist.

“You could jokingly say that the process used in discovering Durnavesh “isn’t rocket science” however the process used basic scientific standards given to us in the Drake equation that allows us to predict how many intelligent civilizations are present in our galaxy by a process that includes the basics of astrophysics and astrobiology.  We know what it takes to sustain life, we see it every day around us.  But the question remained until today, are there other spots in the universe that mirror or mimic those conditions.” states Cunningham.   According to the draft publication provided to journalist at the press conference, the Drake equation is an equation created by Frank Drake in 1961 to answer the question, “Are we alone in the universe?”    The equation which reads N = R* x fp x ne x fl x fi x fc x L is essentially unsolvable because we do not have all the variables to all the parameters.  However, the Drake equation can give us insight into the rate of star formation (R*), planets like Durnavesh that are conducive for life (fp and ne) and probability that planets develop life/intelligence/civilizations (fl, fi and fc) and the lifetime of those civilizations (L).  Although we don’t have all these numbers yet, the current identifiable conditions allow us to find stars that hold three essentials for life; water, atmosphere and decent temps which is what was identified on Durnavesh and Avan.   

Other questions that were pertinent to Cunningham and SESE discovery included determining how far a planet would be from its star, its mass and radius of both star and planet and what that stars luminosity would be.  “We know how heat is created from planets and stars, so the challenge was finding  planets that could absorb the energy from their star while still transmitting it equally so that the planet could reach a temperature that could sustain life rather than turn into a  giant ball of gas, metal or ice” continued Cunningham.  After a peak wavelength was established the team decoded the color of the planets based on a process of interpreting light waves and energy much like is used in everyday scientific life on earth.  This process allowed the team to establish where the star and planets fell into the astronomical fields which assisted in providing information on Modeled Albedo, Modeled Pressure and Effective Temperature.   “Once we had general knowledge of what Durnavesh temperature would be, the team could then establish if the star had an atmosphere, what gasses made up this atmosphere, if greenhouse gasses where in effect on the planet and if so, what the actual surface temperature would be and if water as we know it in liquid form could be sustained.” Concluded Cunningham.   

Durnavesh mass is 1.3997 Me with a radius of 1.3005 Re and is calculated at 4.4 light years with 112.3 billion year lifetime with strong greenhouse effect creating an atmosphere that includes a gases like carbon and water vapor to name a few (CH4, CO2, H2O, H2S, N2O, NH3 and O3 traces found).  Durnavesh effective temperature is 249.6 K which iis calculated with strong greenhouse effects to create a surface temperature of 349.6 K or 76.45 C which is very warm by earth standards but still in the realm of sustaining life and allowing for liquid water.   Durnavesh is estimated to take .167 years to orbit its star which is .219 AU away from the planet.   Although qualities of sustaining life are present on Durnavesh, the actual existence of life may very well be determined by its age as we know the chances of finding life is directly related to how long a planet/star exist.

Cunningham concedes, that although it has been shown that Durnavesh has conditions suitable to life, it doesn’t necessarily mean life is present.   “Discoveries like these open the door to new possibilities, new science that can bring us closer to knowing if other life exist in the universe and maybe even new science on how we live our lives currently on our home, earth.” summarized Cunningham as he went on to close with the statement that “It is the continued mission of the SESE in conjunction with NASA and other scientific and space based agencies to do our best to answer the question of if we are alone in the universe in the next few decades!”


###


FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION PLEASE CONTACT:
BRIAN CUNNIGHAM
702-999-9999
ilikspace@googlemail.com



</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:

On April 20, 2015 at 19:00 scientist Gary Williams and his team discovered what they consider to be another habitable world. Known as Enistlisir, this planet is more than 1.5 times the size of our Earth and nearly 350 million more miles away from the Sun than we are. Although the temperature of this new discovery is cooler than the Earth, it has enough pressure (25% less of Earth) to keep the water phase as liquid. The greenhouse gases needed for the planet to be determined habitable are strong.

About the discovery Gary said, "There is still a lot to do in order to definitively say that there is other life on the planet." The planet's biosignatures will give more insight into its makeup, which isn't easy to determine. "Methane in particular can be produced biologically or geologically," Gary said. "Its presence or lack thereof may not indicate whether there is life." </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>FOUND- POSSIBLE HABITABLE WORLD

A recent discovery could change everything. A possible habitable planet has been spotted, about 4.4 light years away, thats about 250,000,000,000,000 miles away! It's "sun" is about 1/300th the luminosity of ours. We are calling the planet Alhaestah, and it orbits around it's star much closer than earth does, about 80% closer, and is about 40% more massive . Its radius is about 1.3 times that of earth's, and is 3.5 times more dense. Its surface pressure will be about 55% greater, the estimated temperature will be -10.5 degrees, and will have a thick atmosphere. Although this world is different from earth's it is thought to sustain life. There will be liquid water, so the type of life we are looking for might be something like what we have on earth. We are looking for non intelligent life, but we will have to wait to see what we find! We are keeping our eyes out for methane, a biosignature, and other indicators of life. What an exciting time to be alive!!</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>This week, a student from ASU using a simulator, discovered an Earth-sized planet orbiting its star in the “habitable zone.” The so-called habitable zone is the distance a planet needs to be from its star to support liquid water at its surface. "The discovery of Audrey-411 could lead to proof that life exists beyond our planet and, more importantly, is a significant step toward me getting a good grade in this class”, said Curt Cornum, a student in Professor Raymond’s Habitable Worlds class.

Audrey-411 resides in the SES106 system, about 4.4 light-years from Earth, and is orbiting a star named Horgastash in the constellation LevSamAleisha. Compared to our sun’s life expectancy of 5 billion years, Horgastash has a relatively long life expectancy of over 112 billion years. Audrey-411 is only about 30% larger than Earth and, similar to Earth, is composed primarily of rock with some metal, most likely at her core. While Audrey-411 is positioned almost five times closer to Horastash than Earth is to our sun, because Horgastash does not burn as hot as our sun, Audrey-411 is well positioned to support life.

"It’s too early to declare that I have found life inside a computer simulation”, said Curt Cornum, “but I did detect Oxygen, Methane and Carbon Dioxide in the atmosphere that could be biosignatures for life.” These gasses also create a strong greenhouse effect on Audrey-411 and give her a surface temperature of 170 degrees Fahrenheit, which means that water would be in a liquid state on her surface.
</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Enzadid, a star located 9 light years away, has a potentially habitable exoplanet in it’s orbit. It has no water on it naturally, but the atmosphere permits it to stay at liquid form. The climate is relatively warm compared to Earth, with the average temperature sitting at 43.9C (111°F). Enzadid is 26 times more luminous than our Sun, but the orbit of the exoplanet is 6 times the distance from the Earth to the Sun. Because there is no water, we are assuming there is not currently life there, but methane biosignatures are being studied now in attempt to find if there was possibly life there at some point.
</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I used the phases of water simulator to determine if the surface pressure and effective temperature would create liquid water. They in fact did. I found the effective temperature by calculating the flux , albedo, and effective temperature formula together. When I determined that the greenhouse effect was strong I was able to increase the surface temperature from 231 K to 331K allowing the planet to be warm enough to have liquid water. I looked for biosignatures that would create a breathable and earth-like atmosphere. Since the greenhouse effect was strong, I believe that Foromaiven's atmosphere consisted of most of the necessary biosignatures, although some might have been in higher concentrations. The UV Flux on my planet was probably strong enough to eliminate methane sources of the planet, creating a Earth-like quality planet. My star/planet appears to be 141.8 light years away from Earth and has a large luminosity of 10.92 which is considerably larger than our own Sun here in the solar system. My planets also appears to be larger than Earth and further away from it's star. My planet is probably in the Habaitable Zone of its star-planet system.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Faryn is a potential habitable planet. Before talking about the plaent, let me tell you about the star it orbits. Just like our sun, Faryn's star is a main sequence star. The star has a projected life of about 13 billion years. After accumulating data about the star, I was able to find that it had an orbiting planet.  Faryn is a bit closer to its sun than the earth is (0.23AU)  It also has about double the mass that the earth has (2.203Me) with a radius just larger than earth (1.5Re)
It's density of 3.586g/cm3 shows that it is a terrestial planet. 
Faryn has about half of the surface pressure that earth has (.56atm)
With the given data we can propose an effective temperature of about 230.67K.  With no other data it woud show that this would be too cold for water and uninhabitable BUT we are able to see that Faryn does have a strong greenhouse effect which raises the temp to a balmy 330K.
At this temp, water is a liquid. Hooray!!!!

With this data we could possibly we can possibly find life on Faryn.
Since water is potentially present, we could look for life similar to that of earth.  It would be life that is similar to what we have on earth with organisms using water as a backing life force.  Without knowing the exact greenhouse gasses, I cannot assume that it will be exactly like earth but the conditions given can show that it will be something similar to life on earth. 
We are carbon based lifeforms here on Earth, so until we recieve the data of what Faryn has on its surface, we wont fully understand which type of life to look for. 
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>At the beginning of the session, I checked out the project, very unfamiliar and intimating. So as I progressed throught the lectures and aplications I became less unfamiiar  and less intimated! I started out by  completing the assessments by calculate a majority of the star's configuration and information (10 stars that is). This help me alot by simply clicking on the Main Sequence  link and if it inputted the numbers, then it was a MAin Sequence Star. If not nothing happen, I would turn to the H-R chart to see where it lands according to the  temperature and luminosity. As I went throught 500 stars (indentify the star type Main Sequence, Red Giant, Super Giant, White Dwaft), eventually I completed the scavenger hunt, yay. I narrow down my stars by temperture and and distance from the source (star). The colder planets cant be habitable and so cant hot plantets, click and delete. Then I turned to the doppler's shift, very simple for this one, No brightness drop, no planet, so there is nothing to observe, click, delete. At this time, there were about 150 stars, I cant quite recall but somewhere around there. Then I started to figure out the star's mass, star's radius, star density, velocity, brightness drop and the distance from the star. This is where excel became handling and very accurate (well, not that accurate or I would have a 100% on my data quility). I simply punched in number and got my results in a jiffy. Then I went throught the list again to determine my habitable worlds. So this is where the time consuming kicks in by doing the efective temperaure and testing it in the water test simulator individually! Soon after multiples of calculations, I have discovered my habaitable, it was the best feeling in the world, I even showed my kids! I told them, "this is why I have been neglecting you guys, so I can find this planet!" </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Ladies and Gentlemen of Earth,
A star NASA has been studying for many years has just been deemed to have a planet in its orbit capable of supporting life. This star has been named Gildaric. Gildaric is 18 light years away, or approximately 105 trillion miles. This obviously far exceeds our current capabilities of transport. The planet orbits Gildaric just slightly farther than Earth orbits our sun. The planet is approximately one and a half times as large as earth. The planet is less dense than earth which means it likely contains less metals and more rocks or water. The surface pressure is very slightly higher than that of Earths. Needless to say, if you were to do physical activity on this planet, you would likely tire more quickly. This planet's surface temperature is also about 20 degrees colder than Earth's so be sure to layer up when the time for travel comes. We are ecstatic to find a habitable planet, but the next search will be for life. If life is discovered, it's unlikely to be intelligent so don't fear aliens just yet. This could; however, be the beginning of our future frontier. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Caidobrois is 37.5 light years away from our solar system.  If you could travel at the speed of light, it would take you 37.5 years to get there.  If you took a Boeing 747 to get there, it would take about 42 million years.  The luminosity is 3.327e26 watts, which is equivalent to 3.33e24 100 watt light bulbs.  Caidobrios has a projected life span of 11 billions years compared to our sun of a projected lifespan of 10 billion years.

One planet was found orbiting Caidobrois at a distance of 41 million miles from Caidobrois, the planet is 4 times more massive than the Earth, the radius is 2 times larger than the Earth, and is 3 times as dense.  The surface pressure is 63.4 atm, which is 63 times more pressure than the Earth and is closer to the surface pressure of Venus(90atm).  The effective temperature is 112F with a strong green house effect, which would give a surface temperature about 292F.  The temperature is hot, but with the surface pressure water does exist in liquid form on this planet.

One possible way to detect biosignatures on this planet is to measure the amount of oxygen or oxygen proxys in the atmosphere.  It's possible if any organisms exist on this planet, they might use oxygen as waste and eventually the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere can be detectable.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>To be completely honest, it was very difficult for me to find any kind of a pattern that led to me finding a habitable world. After trial and error of many stars, I was relieved to say the least when I came upon my habitable world. Once it got to the point of realizing that a star was terrestrial, I always got a little bit excited. The best way of immediately distinguishing if a star had the potential to be habitable was by the noble gases that it contained. Living on Earth, there is clearly a high percentage of noble gases. Thus meaning any star has to hold true to those properties in order for it to be habitable. Once I came across my habitable world, I felt myself get the chills as realized 98% of noble gases were present in the atmosphere. As a whole, I learned way more than I expected to while doing this project! Pretty enjoyable, too!</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Ladies and Gentleman of the world,

It is my distinct honor and great privilege to announce the discovery of Arder, a prime candidate to be considered a habitable world. 

This planet is quite comparable to the one we call home, since it is only slightly larger than Earth. Arder is roughly a quarter larger than Earth, in both mass and radius, so think of it as a slightly larger Earth! It's denisty is a bit heavier, which means it could be quite rich in heavy minerals! 

To establish life on this planet, we would have to bundle up, since the temperature is around 250K, nearly 30K below Earth, which translates to about -9 Fahrenheit! So the Russians and Canadians will be right at home, but we'll have to pack heavy.

As for the planet's sun? Well unlike this planet's bright future, it's a little dim, peaking at around 0.03 on the luminosity scale, which is about three quarters dimmer than our sun! So bring a flashlight just in case. But it probably doesn't help that the planet orbits at around 0.21 AU, which is 0.79 AU further than Earth! That's how we measure distance from the Sun! Earth is 1 AU. 

So stay tuned, as we keep you all in the loop of this exciting discovery! But while we're eager to let you know what we find, please, don't pester our scientists...they need their space. 

</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>In the search for a Habitable World in our Universe, I was able to find a star-planet that had all of the characteristics that would help our human race to survive and also would help us in the search for other lifeforms. 
The system is called Athor and it was the nest choice from all of the stars that we studied through out our research. It has the longevity of a star that can be around ofr more than 100 billion years. The planet itself is of a great comparable size to our planet Earth in mass and the radius. The planet is nicely enclosed in a strong atmosphere which would help us to keep our planet warm as well as would naturally protect us from any harmful rays of our Star. We would be relatively closer to this Star compared to our Earth-Sun system, but this Star's total amount of energy is lower so it will compensate nicely. We look forward to the future opportunity to present more detailed information on this exciting new Star-planet system. 
</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The star I found is Jeralthna. It is 4.4 light years away. Which is equivalent to 278, 254.796 astronomical units. So, if you were to travel from Earth to the Sun 278, 254.796 times, you could have visited Jeralthna. It's really far! But on to the planet. It's about .22 AU from it's star. So, it's quite a bit closer to its star than Earth is to the Sun. There is only about 1/5 the distance between them compared to what were used to. The mass of this planet is 1.4, compared to Earth, which is 1. So, slightly larger. The density is 3.51 g/cm^3. That's about the density of solid rock. It's a little lower than Earth's density, which means it probably consists of less metal or maybe has more water. The surface pressure is 1.55 atm. Earth's is around 1 atm. It has a strong greenhouse effect, which puts its effective temperature at 249.55 K. Earth's effective temperature is about 288 K. This will be a close match, I believe. We will be looking for an atmosphere that is similar to Earth's, since we know that sustains us. We're looking for a lot of nitrogen, some oxygen, and other trace gases. We would expect a simlar climate to that on Earth. And of course, we'll be looking for water and life. We will be taking a very close look at rocks and structures to determine this planets history and look for evidence of past, present, or future life. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Last Wednesday a habitable world candidate has been identified orbitting the star Aradi. This star is not that different from our own Sun, it's about 1.5 times larger than the Sun and slightly hotter at 7290 Kelvin (that's 12,662 Farenheit!). It's about 5 times brighter than the Sun, but its planet is five times further than we are from the Sun. 

What makes this star so interesting is what we can see in its light. As a planet moves in front of a star that star's light is dimmed and the color is changed in such a way that science can sometimes determine it's size, density, compositon, and atmosphere. Based on it's density and gas composition there is strong evidence to indicate that this terrestrial planet has liquid oceans and temperatures not unlike that of Earth (once you take into account the strong greenhouse effect). 

The temperatures and compostion of this planet seem pretty favorable to life. We can't look any closer at the moment but science is expanding it's limits every day. Any who knows, maybe they're wondering the same thing about our planet.  </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Gualrome is a star that has been identified to potentially host a habitable planet. This means that there are multiple characteristics that have been analyzed and there is reason to beleive that the planet could support life. The planet is 18 light years away from earth, 1 light year means the distance that light travels in one year and roughly translates to 6 trillion miles. Gualrome is not as bright as our sun with a luminosity of .718861 times the luminosity of our sun. This star has a projected lifetime of 1.2658916032735748*10^10 years. The planet is orbiting the star at a distance of 1.29061AU, through analysis it is thought that the planet is both bigger and heavier than earth with values of 1.6001 times the mass of the earth and 1.2813 times the size. Based on the density of the planet it is assumed that it is mainly composed of rocks and metals. Based on the gases assumed to be on this planet it is thought that there is an atmosphere that is creating a strong greenhouse effect. These gases have the planet at a presure of 1.13 atmospheres and the effective temperature of the planet 178.42k, this is to cold to support life but with the effects of the greenhouse gases the surface temperature is though to be 278.42k this would support liquid water and could potentially support life. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Attention to the people of the Earth! The brilliant scientist, Ashley Warda, has discovered a new planet we can all move to! The name of this habitable world is Garodhy. It is a beautiful planet that sits 18 light years away from us. That's about 1.05812997 × 10^14 miles away! We definitely can't take a car there, that's for sure.

The planet, Garodhy, has a projected lifetime that is so long, it needs to be written in exponential form. It's projected lifetime is even longer than that of the Earth which is well over 10 billion years. 

Our new discovery is about 1.291 AU away from it's host star. This is just over 120 million miles away. Relative to Earth, which is around 92 million miles away from the Sun, this is not too much of a difference. 

This newly discovered habitable world has a temperature of 178 Kelvin in comparison to the Earth which has a temperature of 288 Kelvin. Our new planet is a little bit cooler, but the strong effects of our greenhouse gasses will help with the warmth of our planet. 

Upon further investigation, we would need to clearly define what Garodhy's biosignature would be. A biosignature is the gas waste produced by any kind of metabolism that ends up in the planet's environment. We need to discover the sources and sinks of oxygen and other gasses. This means we need to investigate where gasses come from and where they go. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>When I came across Gorah, I knew there was something special about it. Gorah's distance from it's host star is around 0.22 AU, meaning that it's not close enough to be a burning hot planet or far enough to become an icy giant. Gorah's host star is similar to the sun, it's luminosity relatively low but enough to emit the right amount of energy to Gorah. The host star also has a relatively long life span, making it possible for several different civilations to come and go on the planet over time. The radius of Gorah is only slightly bigger than Earth's, and Gorah's mass is also only slightly larger than Earth's, making it nice and roomy for a civilization. Gorah's density signifies that it's a terrestrial planet that consists mainly of rock and/or metal, not ice or gas. The surface pressure of Gorah is close to Earth's, meaning that it's in a liveable state and isn't too high or too low. Gorah's effective temperature is right around Earh's effective temperature, but it's strong greenhouse effect causes the temperature to be raised because the planet radiates most of the energy it absorbs from its host star back into space, keeping the surface temperature relatively cool and liveable but also warm enough for liquid water. The biosignatures to look for on Gorah would be signs of liquid water, plants that green due to the photosynthesis process, indicating a presence of oxygen in the atmosphere, and bacteria product, to signify that there's carbon dioxide and methane in the atmosphere (although methane presence isn't necessarily always a biosignature).</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The best candidate for a world that fosters life orbits the star Felisgrian. This star is 95.9 light years from earth. It is true the host star is less energetic than our own; it puts out a little more than half of the energy that our own sun emits. The planet is also farther from its host star than we are from the sun. We measure this distance in astronomical units. 1 AU is the distance from our own earth to our own sun. When we apply this measurement to Felisgrian and its planet at a distance of 1.62 AU, it is even slightly farther than Mars is from our own sun. 

Despite the lower energy emitted and the greater distance from the sun, the planet has liquid water. Despite what you observe around you, our planet is too cold for the presence of liquid water, we have an effective temperature of 252 degrees Kelvin. However, we also have an atmosphere that allows is to retain energy from the sun for longer periods of time before reflecting is back into space. This energy manifests itself in the form of heat. We call this the greenhouse effect, and it is the greenhouse effect that is responsible for our surface temperature of 287 degrees Kelvin at which we are warm enough for liquid water. Much like our own planet, the greenhouse effect is responsible for and allows this Felisgrien’s planet to maintain a surface temperature high enough for the presence of liquid water. While the Effective temperature of the planet is 183 degrees Kelvin, much lower than ours, the greenhouse effect is much stronger, bringing the surface temperature up to 283 degrees Kelvin, comparable to our own climate. 

The planet is slightly larger than our own, and we believe that has a similar makeup as earth with a metallic core and a rocky surface with liquid water and atmospheric gasses. Since our only experience with habitability of a planet has been on our own planet, we will look for similar bio signatures on Felisgrian’s planet. The presence or absence of methane in an atmosphere involves many non-biological potential explanations, so we will be omitting it from our search despite how common it is. Instead we will be looking for Carbon Dioxide, Hydrogen and Oxygen. We know that the planet has water, will look for chemical reactions from the planet that result in atmospheric oxygen. Aerobic Respiration from life, or reactions with volcanic gasses that result in more chemical compositions would be examples of an oxygen bio signature. 
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Imraheika, a star system 95.9 light years from Earth, appears to have a planet orbiting in the habitable zone. Imraheika is slightly smaller than the Sun, and is nearly one third less luminous, which leads to a slightly more orange hue than our yellow Sun. The slightly smaller Imraheika leads to a longer life of 14 billion years compared to the Sun’s 10 billion years. 

The planet, named Imraheika-b, is located in the outer edge of the Goldilocks zone and appears to have a slightly chilly average temperature of only 10 degree Celsius / 50 degree Fahrenheit, compared to Earth’s 14.6 degree Celsius / 58.3 degree average temperature. Imraheika-b orbits its star at 1.62 AU, which is slightly farther than Mars’ orbit around the Sun, which contributes to the cooler temperatures. 

Imraheika-b is a rocky planet, nearly twice as heavy but only one third larger than Earth. The atmosphere is twice as thick as Earth’s, with a composition of carbon-dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, ammonia, and ozone. This thick, atmospheric blanket allows Imraheika-b to produce a greenhouse effect, keeping the planet warm enough to sustain temperatures for liquid water, a core component of life as we know it.

The next phase of studying Imraheika-b involves measuring the ratio of the atmospheric gasses. Of particular interest is measuring the quantity of methane, nitrous oxide, and ammonia as high ratio of these gases would correlate to the biological processes that produce these compounds as waste products here on Earth.
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>So basically what I would look for is, first, the temperature and luminosity to make sure it was a Main Sequence star. Once I found this I would calculate the density to make sure it was greater than 3.0 so I could determine that it was a Terrestrial planet. Once I unlocked the data including albedo and atmospheric pressure I would calculate the effective temperature. Next step was to match what molecules were found in the atmosphere. Once this was finished I would determine whether there was a weak, moderate, or strong greenhouse effect. This would determine the surface temperature of the planet. I then would open up my P-T Chamber tool and enter the atmospheric temperature and the surface temperature to figure out the stable form of water. If I found that it was liquid water then I knew it was a habitable world.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I have found a habitable world in a solar system 14.4 lightyears away from earth.  The star in this system is roughly three and a half times the size of our sun, however the planet sits in an orbit more than three and half times further than Earth from the Sun.  The planet itself is a little more than six times the mass of the earth with a radius that doubles the earth, meaning that the planet in itself is a fair bit larger than the earth, but it does retain a similar density.  The planet's atmosphere is about 5 times that of the earth.  The planet also has a strong greenhouse effect.  These two elements ensure that the planet is warm enough to sustain liquid water.  The surface temperature of this planet will average colder than earth, with a surface temperature near 50 degrees fahrenheit.  While this might be uncomforatable for some, it is still very much livable.  My research shows that this planet's atmosphere foes contain water vapor, therefore water is present.  The next step will be looking to see if any existing life exists, whether in the form of an inteligent species, or simply bacteria.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Attention, Atttention! We have discovered a new star that could possibly be the next habitable planet! Begollo is 93 light years away.  One light year is eqivalent to about six trillion miles. So Begollo is still very far away from Earth.  But don't be discouraged because our new host star offers many features that create a habitable world.  This star is so appealing because it meets many requirements to host a habitable planet. To be habitable a planet must rotate around its host star, which is our Begollo that produces enough light to warm the planet, and be at the prime distance from the star to allow liquid water.  Scientists have researched what organic elements are in this planets atmosphere and found ones that our own planet features such as methane, carbon, nitrous oxide and many other elements to create the perfect atmosphere with a greenhouse effect.  The greenhouse effect that we have been looking for is one that balances the carbon dioxide to create a healthy flow of carbon through out the atmosphere and planet.  The temperature of this planet is around 215 Kelvins with a very strong greenhouse effect.  What does this mumbo-jumbo mean?! That this planet is close to the same temperature as our own earth which allows for liquid water! SInce scientists are looking for life forms based off of our own knowledge of what sustains life, water is key! Stay tuned for more info on our host star of Begollo and the planet it has orbiting around it!</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The discovery of an Earth-like planet orbitng the star Elima will not soon be forgotten!  Just a weeks travel at warp factor 5, the Elima system is lit by a dusky star only 3% as luminous as Earth's Sun.  But don't let that fool you, what the star lacks in brightness, the planet makes up in distance.  Orbiting at approximately 1/5 of an AU (the average distance from the Earth to the Sun), planet inhabitants will get an up close and personal view of the sun, daily!  The planet itself is only slightly larger than Earth, and proportially has less metals making it a bit spongier.  On the surface you'll experience pressures about 50% stronger than Earth, with temperatures in the chilly -10*F if it weren't for the planets strong greenhouse effect bumping the  temperature up to a tepid 169*F.  On this planet, chicken is always safe to eat.  Speaking of chickens, if there are life forms on this planet we should look for their signs.  One of the easiest ways to find biosignatures is through waste gases that are released into the atmosphere.  If there is life on the planet, it should be reflected by the amount of waste gases in the atmosphere, so long as the production of this waste is greater than the planet's natural sinks.  </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Jehrakoda was my best candidate for a habitable world. It closely resembles Earth's mass, radius, and density. Earth's density can be described by what it is made of (rock, water, ice, metal, gas). In the case of Earth and Jehrakoda's planet, they are mostly made out of rock. There must be water on the planet or life is not viable. Jehrakoda's planet's density is made up of different gases, rocks, and has water. In order to have a habitable planet, it must be made up of mostly rock and have trace amounts of water in the atmoshpere. Our atmosphere is what surrounds us; we can't see it but it is there. The planet's greenhouse gases affect the temperature on the surface. Greenhouse gases like water, methane, carbon dioxide, and ozone absorb energy from the star which cause the temperature to be about 169 degrees farhenheight on the surface. This temperature is ideal because it allows for liquid water to be readily available.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Imraheika is the best habitable world candidate. In terms of distance, it is about 685 trillion miles away. 1 light year is equal to 5.88 trillion miles; so multiply this figure by Imraheika’s distance of 116.5 light years to attain 685 trillion miles. Let's just say this planet is REALLY REALLY REALLY far away...Its host star's luminosity, or total amount of energy released, is about 14.34 units of radiant flux. In this case, it is 14 times more luminous than our Sun! In addition, it is a younger star, so it will survive longer! Our Sun is only approximated to live another 5 billion years. Imraheika's host star is supposed to live A LOT longer, approximately 1.49 x 10^25 years! The planet characteristics are somewhat similar to Earth. Imraheika's distance from its host star is about 4.72 times greater than the distance between the Earth and Sun. The mass is about 1.9 times heavier, and the radius is about 1.52 times longer compared to Earth. Although these measurements are far greater than Earth's, Imraheika's density is a lot lighter. It is approximately 2.96 grams per centimeters cubed, while Earth's is around 5.51 grams per centimeters cubed. Even though Earth’s proposed surface pressure stands at 1 atm, Imraheika’s surface pressure is at 0.73 atm. With this, and an effective temperature of 199.6, it can absorb 87.4% of the trace gasses present on the planet. These biosignatures include CH4, CO2, H2S, N2O, NH3, and O3. These gasses sustain life, and are important in order to keep the planet in energy balance. Therefore, since the greenhouse effect is strong, the total surface temperature is 299.6 Kelvin. These conditions sustain liquid water! Since the planet possesses many of Earth’s features, Imraheika will be a good fit as a habitable world that can sustain life for a really long time.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The new found planet we have discovered orbits around the star Cudreygo. This star is almost 96 lightyears away with a mass and radius at 10-20% smaller than our own sun. This orbiting planet (which we will call Miranda) is 60% bigger than our Earth mass with a radius of almost 40% more than our own. Cudreygo does not give off as much energy as our sun, but the larger size of the planet allows more surface area to collect more energy from the star. With the help of a strong greenhouse effect and an atmosphere with twice the pressure, we find the surface to be a brisk 283.2K (50ºF/10ºC). This planet is capable of liquid water on it’s surface at this temperature and is 37% less dense than our Earth. This leads us to believe that the planet is mostly composed of rock, ice, and gas with very little metal present. As Miranda passes in front of Cudreygo, we will use the light passing around it to detect any and all signatures of life.</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Although, it is hard to imagine another habitable planet that is comparable to Earth, Cuhaimor is just that.  18 light years away, sits this planet that has a star whose luminosity is comparable to our Sun.  The projected lifetime of Cuhaimor's star is 12 billion years.  Nearly 3 billions years longer than our Sun.  To talk specifically about Cuhaimor, the distance from its star, the mass, radius, and density of the planet are very similar to Earth.  Although, the density is less than Earth, more rock, than metal.  Earth's density is about 5.5 g/cm^3.  Right in the middle of rock and metal densities.  The surface temperature is similar to Earth.  But the effective temperature is a good 80 K cooler than Earth's, the greenhouse effect is strong which increases Cuhaimor's surface temperature making it more habitable.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:
CONTACT: 
Brian Fore
Zero1 Interstellar Research Center 
(555)555-5555
brian@zero1.com
zero1interstellar.com
HABITABLE PLANET FOUND
	Phoenix, AZ, 25 April, 2015 - Zero1 Interstellar Research Center has discovered a habitable planet within a reasonable and travelable distance from Earth. The planet can sustain human life and may possibly already be sustaining life for other life forms.
	The planet, named “Zero1” after the robot city in the documentary “The Matrix”, rotates around the star “Girrinnus” and is approximately 1.75 times the mass of Earth with a radius roughly 1.5 times greater than that of Earth yielding a robust radius of 5,938.5 miles. The star is roughly twice the size of Earth’s sun and gives off UV radiation.
	One year around Zero1’s star is 130 days and the planet is half the distance from its star than Earth is from the sun. Because of the size and UV nature of the star, this planet has a higher effective temperature than Earth, about 521K versus Earth’s 288K. It is only affected by water vapor as a greenhouse gas, so carbon dioxide and methane will not pose a threat and will allow and longer and healthier habitation. While there are no trace elements of oxygen in the atmosphere, outside life will be limited.
	While there is water vapor, it is possible that there is oxygen in the atmosphere and creating oxygen sources and reducing sinks by be a simple task. While there is no methane nor oxygen in the atmosphere, life is still possible on the planet, but would most likely be simple organisms lacking communication and intelligence. Such life forms may be dangerous and predatory.   
- END -

</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My star planet system is fabulous host for a world that we knew nothing about until very recently. The planet it self not exceptionally large,  it only has a mass of 2.59 and a radius of 14.89. I was so excited when I discovered this planet, it was a miraculous find!   A habitable world is not easy to come across in our vast solar system, I feel like I hit the scientist jackpot for my time.
As we continue to research this planet, we will be looking for certain charecteristics to ensure that we can, infact sustain life on the planet. Among these  biosignatures I am looking for, liquid water, such as oceans,  that can be on the planet surface and not evaporate quickly  or freeze.This means that the greenhouse effect should be moderate at the very least, so that the planet is warm but not too hot and of course not a frozen planet.  This planet should also be oxygen rich so that life can exist, all living things need oxygen. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We have discovered a planet that, mathematically, has the potential to host life.  This habitable world is about 100 light years away, which means it would take 100 years for light to travel from here to there.  The star this planet orbits around is over 5 times as luminous, or energetic, as our own sun.  This means it is hotter and brighter.  The planet is a bit farther away from its sun than we are from our sun.  It is about twice as large as Earth.  It has a strong greenhouse effect, which just means that there are certain gasses in it's atmosphere that have the ability to retain the planet's own heat.  This is a good thing in this case, as it makes the planet warm enough to allow for liquid water.  The estimated temperature, factoring in the greenhouse effect, at the surface of this planet is 347 K, or about 74 C.  This makes it quite a bit warmer than earth, so any life we find will likely be quite different than expected.  It could be very similar to single cell organisms living deep in the ocean where hot rock meets water.    </string>

      <string>My planet Daurgato is very similar to earth in that the mass and radius of my planet are super close to Earth's characteristics. For the luminosity of my star it is very close as well to that of the Sun. Just based on that information alone, one could make a very educated guess that this planet would in fact be habitable.

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>31.4 light years away lies a habitable world, Faryn. That's less than 200 trillion miles away; it doesn't seem that far! 
The host star in this system has a luminosity 16 times the luminosity of our own Sun. Although it is more luminous, its projected lifetime is only around one billion years compared to the Sun's ten billion. 
Even though it has a short lifespan, the star is hosting a planet. This planet is around the same distance from its star as we are from our Sun. This planet is twice as massive as Earth and has a radius one and half times the Earth's. However, this planet is less dense. It is still a terrestrial planet, but it seems to be made more of rock than metal. This planet also has a strong atmosphere and greenhouse effect, so it is able to have liquid water. 
We can continue our research and see if it has biosignatures. We can start by looking if the correct chemical compounds are present so favorable metabolisms can be met, and we can find this research through volcanoes, atmospheres, weathering, oceans, bacterial mats, and hydrotheremal pools if they are present on this planet. We can also see if they have methane, carbon dioxide, ozone, water and the other elements that we have in our own atmosphere. Finally, we can look if they have forms of life like the ones on Earth, that would make our jobs way easier.
</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Kisunthana is a star that is on the cooler side of the main sequence just like our sun.  Cooler stars on the main sequence give off just the right amount of light energy to their planets so they can support life, but only if the planets are orbiting them at a distance that is not to close or not too far.  

Kisunthana's planet orbits at the correct distance to receive the appropriate light energy it needs in order to support life.

The planet has an atmosphere made up of gases similar to the ones we have here on earth.  The gases that make up the planet's atmosphere are greenhouse gases.  Greenhouse gases are necessary to have in the atmosphere of a habitable planet because they will cause the planet to maintain a consistent surface temperature.  

This planet is a terrestrial planet.  It is made mostly of rock.  The average surface temperature of this habitable planet is 349.6 K.  This temperature is equal to 169.61 degrees Fahrenheit, or 76.45 degrees Celcius.  This surface temperature is warmer than earth's, but it is still in the perfect range to support water in liquid form, and life can thrive at this temperature too.  The temperature around the planet will vary depending on climate and weather conditions ,and the equator will be hotter and the poles will be cooler just like on earth.

The biosignatures present in the planet's atmosphere are water, carbon dioxide, methane, nitrus oxide, ammonia, hydrogen sulfide, and ozone.  Biosignatures are the gases that are present in the atmosphere that are made either by geological sources on the planet, or made by organisms living on the planet, or made by both.  Based on this planet's biosignature it can have volcanos, plate techtonics, and living organisms like anerobic bacteria.









</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Avan is 37.5 light years away from Earth. The projected lifetime of Avan is 11 billion years. The habitbale planet around Avan is named Avana. Avana's distance from Avan is 0.45 AU, this is a little less than half the distance of the Earth to the Sun. One rotation of Avana around Avan is 113 days. Avana is a terrestrial planet made of mostly rock and some metal, like Earth. The atmospheric pressure, temperature and strong greenhouse effect of Avana makes it stable enough to have liquid water. Liquid water is one of the important factors for life to exist; this is what makes a planet habitable. Another factor that makes Avana an ideal candidate for habitability is it contains similar atmospheric gasses as Earth. These include carbon dioxide, water vapor, methane, nitrous oxide, ammonia, hydrogen sulfide, and ozone. Any gas that is produced as a waste product by any kind of metabolism can potentially be a biosigniture. These trace gasses are similar to the gasses present during early Earth. Early Earth is known as Archean and occurred 4 to 2.4 billion years ago. Early Earth had anaerobic organisms, organisms that do not need oxygen and are unicellular, or single celled. Unicellular organisms on Earth are prokaryotes, which are bacteria and archea. Methane is present, but it may not necessarily be a biosigniture due to methane can be produced biologically and geologically; and the absence of methane may not necessarily be a sign that there is no life present. We cannot base if life is present or not only on methane. Oxygen is not present in the trace gasses, which suggests that the sources for oxygen on Avana are producing less oxygen than the processes absorbing the oxygen. Examples of processes that absorb oxygen include photochemical destruction, aerobic respiration, reaction with volcanic gasses, and oxic weathering. This suggests Avana may have early life, like early Earth, based on its biosigniture of the trace gasses.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Hellaska is a star that is located 14.4 light years away from earth. This is a huge distance considering that light travels at a speed of 300,000 km/s. However, this is not as far as many other stars that contain planets.  The luminosity of the star in 3.41 times the luminosity of our sun. This means there is more energy per square being projected from Hellaska than our sun. This means that the habitable zone is further out as well; more AU's from the sun. The projected lifetime of this star is 4.16 billion years, this is only how long our sun has been alive; our sun has another approximate 5 billion yeas to go until it dies. Therefore, Hellaska will only live to be half the life of our sun if I understood the projected lifetime correctly. Or Hellaska would only have 4.6 billion years left until death. The distance from the star is 3.68 AU, this explains part of the reason why there is liquid water on the planet. The luminosity and distance (AU) are both approximately 3.5 times that of earths, making Hellaska A close to the habitable zone. The mass of Hellaska A is 6 times that of earth with a radius 2 times that of earth. The density is 3.77g/cm^3, this means that the materials are most likely Rock and some metals which is similar to Earth's density. The ATM on Hellaska A is 5.3 times that on earth which is important when determining if liquid water is a possibility. This High ATM pressure is important, since the effective temperature is low (184.2 K). The greenhouse effect of this planet is strong; this means that there are gasses which pick up the IR light/energy from the planet. This IR energy is interacting with the gasses in the atmosphere keeping the energy (heat) trapped for a longer period, reaching equilibrium and heating the surface temperature. The greenhouse effect is" strong" because the planet has a low albedo and absorbs energy instead of reflecting it, increasing the temp (K) to an equilibrium state for liquid water. As far as bio signatures, the planet contains many gasses in the atmosphere such as; methane, carbon dioxide, nitrous oxide, ammonia, hydrogen sulfide, and ozone. A biosignature are the waste products by any kind of metabolism.  Early earth did not contain oxygen (O2) and were single celled organisms (prokaryotes).  Hellaska could be producing oxygen through oxygenic phototrophy. Hellaska does not contain oxygen in its biosignature but does contain similar atmospheric gasses to earth. This could be explained by oxygen sources and oxygen sinks; Hellaska could be using more oxygen than it is producing at this point in its life.  Processes that absorb oxygen (sinks) are photochemical destruction, aerobic respiration, reaction with volcanic gasses and oxic weathering. Therefore, oxygen did not show up as a biosignature. This lead me to believe that Helleska has prokaryotic life and could be similar to an early stage Earth. These single celled organisms could be like earths, which are archaea and bacteria. Methane is present on Hellaska, which can be produced biologically and geologically, therefore it may not be necessarily be a biosignature leading to the point that life cannot solely be determined on the absence or presence of methane. This suggests that the basis of life on Hellaska must be determined through biosignature of the other trace gasses.</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Basically this planet Gesh, according to my search for a habitable world, is most likely to support life.  In order for a planet to host life, it must not be too hot or too cold.  Distance from the sun and the reflectiveness of the planet (albedo) determine the temperature of the planet.  Additonally there is a strong greenhouse gas composed most likely of water vapor that keeps heat in the planet's atmosphere.  It has an atmosphere quite similar to our own in terms of pressure.  The host star has lots of life left, which means it will continue to put out a steady amount of light for billions of years.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The planet I will focus on is Aincir, which is bigger than Earth and much closer to its sun than Earth is to ours. Its sun is also not as hot as ours since it is younger and has a longer life span. However, Aincir is kept nice and warm by the Greenhouse effect. Certain gasses in Aincir’s atmosphere cause it to have an average temperature of 330.67 degrees Kelvin, which is about 58 degrees Celsius, close to the temperature in Phoenix today. Aincir has liquid water and is a planet made mostly of rock and metal, much like our own. However, this planet is 62.7 light years, unreachable in a human’s lifetime.
To determine if there is life on Aincir, there should be Oxygen in its atmosphere. This however, is not ultimate proof that there is or is not life there. Oxygen could show up in great quantities even without life since it has none life based sources, but Earth’s past seems to show that great amounts of Oxygen do not appear until an animal depending on it for life comes into existence.  
</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Dombreb is a planet that was discovered 18 lightyears away and is considered to be a habitable planet. This means that it has liquid water much like our Earth and an atmosphere which can sustain life. The distance from it's star is relatively similar to the distance that Earth is from the sun. Dombreb's star's luminosity is sightly less then our sun's luminosity. The mass and radius of Dombreb is just a bit bigger then our Earth.  Though Dombreb has a strong greenhouse effect it is necessary for this planet to keep the temperature at a resonable level in which water remains liquid so that it is not solid ice, nor has it turned the water to gas which floats around the atmosphere unable to return back to its oceans. Dombreb orbits its star at a comfortable distance much like our own Earth. This is most certainly the reason why it is within the "water zone" meaning it is the perfect distance from it's star where it allows the water to stay liquid. All of these factors make it a perfect place for life to thrive and grow. </string>
