    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>            My planet-star system, Gamor, is the best candidate to have a habitable planet. To begin, the luminosity (brightness of the star) is about 11 Ls, or around ten times as bright as the star in out solar system (1 Ls). If my planet was at the same distance as Earth is from its star this luminosity would be a problem, but my planet is about 4 times further from its star than Earth (1 AU), with a distance of 4.322 AU.                                                     

            To continue, the density of my planet, 3.275 g/cm3, is in the proper range to be considered a terrestrial planet. In order for a planet to be considered habitable, it has to be terrestrial. The type of a planet that exists is determined by its density. A terrestrial planet falls between the density of pure rock (3 g/cm3), and metal (8 g/cm3). With a density of 3.275 g/cm3, my planet falls within that range, so it can be considered terrestrial, like Earth (~ 5 g/cm3).                                                                                  

            Another important aspect in the habitability of a planet is the surface pressure of said planet. Surface pressure determines, based on temperature, which form H2O will take on the planet. Earth has a surface pressure of 1 atm. The planet that I have discovered has a surface pressure of 10 atm, which is not a huge jump from the surface pressure of Earth. Furthermore, surface pressure and temperature are directly related. Depending on the pressure of a planet, the temperature at which water can remain in the liquid state varies, which is vitally important for a habitable planet. With 10 atm being close to 1 atm, it is important for my planet to have a temperature similar to that of Earth. Calculating the Effective Temperature is the first step.                                                                            

            The Effective Temperature is what the temperature of a planet would be if no gasses were present in the atmosphere. In this case, my planet has an effective temperature of 231.768 K. However, effective temperature does not represent the actual temperature of the planet. The actual temperature of a planet is called its surface temperature. Surface temperature is based on the effect gasses in the atmosphere have on the temperature. By calculating the amount of gasses in the atmosphere and the percent of energy that is absorbed, the surface temperature of the planet can be found. This is called the Greenhouse Effect.                                                       

            The Greenhouse Effect on my planet is strong, meaning between 60-100% of the gasses (most notably Carbon, Hydrogen, and Oxygen) are absorbed by the planet. A strong greenhouse effect results in a 100 K increase in temperature of the planet. Thus, instead of my planet having a temperature of 231.768 K, the actual temperature, or surface temperature, of my planet is 331.768 K. While 231.768 K may be too cold for water to be in its liquid state, because of the greenhouse effect, the 100 K increase in temperature to 331.768 K allows water to exist as a liquid, meaning it is a habitable planet.                                                                                                            

            In conclusion, based on all of these reasons, I believe my star-planet system Gamor has a planet that could be considered suitable for life. The planet is the proper distance from the star, the star's luminosity is not too bright or too dim, the density of the planet falls in the terrestrial range, the surface pressure of the planet is not too high or too low, and the effective temperature combined with the greenhouse effect allows water to exist in its liquid state. More tests have to be done, but Gamor has all the necessary components for harboring a planet that can be deemed habitable. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I discovered a planet that sits 18 light years away from us here on Earth, a distance too far for us to currenty go with our technology. This isn't to say that we could survive on the planet if we made it, but it could definitely harbor a different style of life because it can have liquid water at it's surface, although there isn't any water vapor in the atmosphere.  There is an extreme greenhouse effect that increases the effective temperature, which alone would be too cold to harbor life, but results in a 278 K surface temperature. The type of life to exist on this planet would be exotic, but definitely can exist. It is about the same distance from it's star that we are from ours, has almost the same radius, and has about 1.5 times as much mass.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I have discovered an Earth-like planet in the universe.  This planet is about 18 light years away, or in other words, it is over 105 trillion miles away.  This planet has many similar characteristics as our planet.  It orbits around a star that is much like our sun.  It is just barely farther away from its star than we our to the sun, so it takes a little bit longer for it to orbit around its star.  The planet I have discovered has weight and size dimensions very similar to Earth. This planet is capable of life and has liquid water at the surface.  Its atmosphere is also very similar to ours.  This planet is expected to be older than Earth but we are in the process of looking for certain substances that would show signs of life there such as water, methane, and carbon dioxide.  This is a huge discovery and we are excited to look further into this planet to see if indeed there is or was life there.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The habitable planet that has been identified orbits a star named Atir. This solar system is around four light years away. The star is smaller than our sun, but the planet is also much closer, actually closer than Mercury is to our sun. Our sun has a lifetime of around ten billion years, but Atir is smaller and releases a lower amount of energy, so its lifetime is over one hundred billion years. The planet is about 30% percent larger than earth and has a surface pressure of about 50% more than earth. With the higher pressue, thicker atmosphere, and strong greenhouse effect the approximate surface temperature is around 165 degrees fahrenheit, or 75 degrees celsius. This is obviously very hot compared to average temperatures on earth, but just as on earth we have hotter and cooler regions, so the circulation will transfer the hotter air from the equatorial region and the colder air from the poles around the planet creating some pleasant regions with more realistic earth like temperatures. The planet is made of some of the same materials earth is made of, but is slightly less dense, meaning it is likely to have quite a bit more water. We should see some of the same types of volcanism and plate tectonics creating a potential inorganic carbon cycle similar to what we have on earth. Basically what that means is there will be water evaporation and rain showers, active volcanic eruptions, and quakes similar to what we experience on earth. With these different activities going on there is a possibility that life could already exists on this planet. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The first candidate that I found which proved to be habitable orbits a star named Chierebdin. The distance of this star is approximately 37.5 lightyears from Earth, which equates to the amount of time it would take light to travel to this star-planet system. 37.5 light years may not seem like a large distance but when we take into account that the speed of light is just over 670,000 miles per hour, it really puts this number into perspective. For instance, if you were to drive a car at 65 mph it would take you 220 billion years to get there. 

The luminosity of this star system is .867 compared to our sun's luminosity of 1, this is actually fairly similar. The projected lifetime of the star is over 11 billion years, which is actually older than the entire universe itself. The projected lifetime of our star is approximately 10 billion years. The difference in projected lifespan can be linked to the luminosity of the two stars. The Chierebdin system's star is slightly less luminous which translates into the star itself being slightly smaller. The smaller the star the longer its lifespan will be, with the opposite being the larger the star the shorter its lifespan. We can see this in stars like supergiants where lifespans may be so short they are calculated in the millions of years only. 

The planet characteristics are vastly different from Earth, which make you scratch your head and wonder how and why this planet would be considered habitable. The main reason this planet is habitable is because it has an effective temperature that allows for liquid water to remain on its surface, not as a solid or gas but liquid. In my opinion the surface pressure on this planet would be ridiculously too strong for life as we know it to exist, but perhaps very small organisms or bacteria etc could thrive. We know on Earth that the surface pressure is approximately 1 atm, which is 14.7 pounds per square inch. This means that for every square inch of our body, there are 14.7 lbs pushing down against you. On this planet if we do the math, 14.7*63.4 there would be 931.98 lbs per square inch pushing down against you. 

The mass and radius of our planet are larger than Earth. Mass and radius are calculated and then converted into terms equivalent for Earth, so a planet twice as heavy as Earth would have a mass of 2. A planet twice as large would have a radius of 2, 4 times as large a radius of 4 etc. Our planet has a mass of 4.5 which is 4.5 times more massive than Earth, it's radius is approximately 2 times larger. This planet would be labeled as a Super Earth. The Density of our planet is approximately 3.1 meaning that it is a terrestrial planet composed of metal, rock, ice and gas, with metal and rock being the most prevalent. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Today a revolutionary discovery was made, after decades of research and timeless efforts a habitable planet was discovered tugging at its mother star Elima only 18 light-years away. The star Elima is technically not as luminous as our big bright beautiful Sun but it does not deter it from trying by only being off by about 3/10th's, maybe when its older. Thats a very small difference, I guess the Sun has some competition who can shine brighter? That leaves room for a lot of promise, because of this and some other factors pertaining to its size our star should live a relatively long happy life residing in the night sky we've come to know and love. As for our planet it is similar to the beloved Earth in the sense that it roughly lives about 120,000,000 miles away  from it, that is quite the distance. I guess the Sun and Elima like their personal space huh? It is not as big as our Earth but they are definitely made out of the same materials like rock and metal! The biosignatures, which is essentially a gas, you would look for on the extraterrestrial planet on Elima would be methane, our high esteemed Carbon dioxide, ozone and many more! You would be able to detects these gaseous gasses in our atmosphere if they are made in abundance such as the every day waste product of carbon dioxide on our very own Earth, which we have been seeing way more than we'd like to lately, who would have thought they'd be so close, sharing the same "gasses." The future is bright for our star Elima and its fellow planet, but since it is so far away from us we may never get to see it grow into the wise ripe old age as we did our Earth. Nevertheless, we are in good company.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The planet orbiting the star Celeder, which rests about 18 light years away, is a planet quite similar to our own Earth. The star around which it orbits is roughly the same as our sun, and the planet has almost the same distance from it. It is also similar in mass, size, and pressure. The biggest difference is in the planet's temperature. It is about 10 degrees cooler there than it is on our own planet. Because of its similarities to our Earth and sun system, the biosignatures we would look for would be similar to those we experience on our own planet. Increased levels of CO2 in the atmosphere, as well as H20. Radio waves are a possibility, if life on that planet is able to communicate. In order for life to be detectable on that planet however, it would have to be well populated and capable of sending signals out into the universe.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The planet Horgatash, which has many of the characteristics of a habitable planet, is 62.7 light years from Earth. The mass of this planet is about twice the mass of Earth, and the radius is 50% bigger than the radius of Earth. The density of the planet is 3.5 grams per centimeter cubed, which means that the primary material of the planet is rock, but that it also has metal in its composition. The temperature of the planet, without the influence of any atmosphere, is 230.7 Kelvins, which is equal to -44.41 degrees Fahrenheit or -42.45 degrees celsius, but there is a strong greenhouse effect, so that increases the temperature enough that there is liquid water on the surface. We cannot use methane as a biosignature -- which is an indicator of life -- because there are too many non-living things that create methane for us to assume that source of any methane found is life. However, it may be possible to use oxygen to search for life, since there are fewer non-living things that produce oxygen. The presence of oxygen in the atmosphere may mean that there are living bacteria on the planet.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We have just discovered a new habitable world candidate which orbits the star Jaydraca, which is approximately 4.4 light years away from us. This host star, through observations, was found to be quite dim compared to our own star. This star also has an estimated lifetime of about 11 billion years!

Because Jaydraca is so dim compared to our own star, this planet is much closer to it's host star than the Earth is to the Sun. This allows the planet to be in the so-called "Habitable" zone of the host star, allowing for the right conditions of life and liquid water. It was through observations that the orbit of this planet was found to be about one-fifth of that of the Earth and the Sun. This is even closer than the distance between Mercury and the Sun! This new planet is also about 1.4 times the mass of the Earth, and about 2.2 times the size of the Earth. It's overall density is approximately 3.5g/cm^3. This is significantly less than the density of Earth, which is about 5.5g/cm^3. This planet is more comparable to Mars when it comes to density, where Mars has a density of about 3.9g/cm^3. However, this density indicates that this planet is not a gas giant nor an ice/water planet. It is terrestrial, just like our own. The pressure on this planet is approximately 1.55atm, unlike our planet's pressure of 1atm. With a temperature of 249K (-11 degrees Fahrenheit) and a strong presense of Greenhouse gases, this planet is the best bet for finding extraterrestrial life! </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Deep in space, lerks a planet waiting to be inhabitied. Recent reports point to a possible, habitable location located deep in space. Idartus, an earth-like planet lives only 18 light years away, or 105 trillion 812 billion 997 million miles! Idartus orbits a star very similar to our sun! Its not quite as bright, but it will be around for over 12 billion years! Idartus itself is very similar to earth, but differs in some of its characteristics. It's a quarter of the distance to earth, longer! Its also a quarter larger in size! Boy, this just keeps getting better! BIgger and better?! With it being bigger, it brings some hotter temperatures, and you might weigh a bit more on this planet! 


We intend to conduct further studies to make sure this planet could be an option for life. Normally, we conduct Methane studies to find something called a biosignature. A biosignature is an element that provides scientific evidence that life does, or did exist! it can be produced in a lot of different cases, such as through life or geological changes. Methane doesn't always appear, but it doesn't mean we've lost more hope! In some situations, life might be present without methane. Only time will tell, especially since it took 2.3 Billion years for the earth just to be habitable! </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I am please to announce a viable candidate for a habitable world. Irwombar is located 4.4 light years away, or about 25 trillion miles! Seems like a lot, but it is only a little further, .1 ly, then our closest discovered stellar system. It's luminosity, a factor of brightness, is only about 3% of our sun, making it considerably less bright, leading to a lower temperature, 3480K, compared to the 5800K or 10,000F of our sun. However, this low luminosity is a quality of long lived stars, meaning the life expectancy of Irwombar is 100 billion years, about ten times the life expectancy of our sun. This means, if we are looking for intelligent communicating life, this star has plentiful time for it to have developed or be developing. You might worry that it'd be far to cold on the planet of a star that's 3% the luminosity, and a little over half the temperature of our sun, but Irwomvbar's planet revolves considerably closer to it's star then earth does, 80% percent closer that is, at a distance of .22 AU, compared to earth 1 AU. This means the heat from Irwombar has less time to radiate out, and more comes in contact with its planet. Also, working to keep this planet warmer, are the facts that it is 1 and 1/3 times the size of the earth, which gives it more surface area to grab the stars rays, as well as a bigger mass, by 1 and 1/4 compared to earth, which helps it maintain the gases that give it a strong atmosphere. These gases temporarily trap more radiation in, making the planet even warmer then earth. Both this planet and earth have a temperature, before considering their atmospheres, that shouldn't allow for liquid water, earth's at 257 K and this planet at 249.5 K. Earth's atmosphere keeps enough heat in the form of energy in to raise it's temperature 30 degrees K, making it able to have liquid water. This planet has a thicker atmosphere then earth, so thick that it adds 100 degrees K to it's temperature, making it even hotter then earth, well still able to retain liquid water. Which brings me to an important point, this planet has water vapor in it atmosphere, a quality that other habitable world with temperatures even more similar to that of earth's didn't have, meaning that even though it's much hotter then earth, it's also more humid, that is to say, there water in the atmosphere, and the right temperature that water can be liquid at too, meaning there will be some on the ground! This is very important, because water is very important to the possibility of life. Water works well in chemical reactions to produce energy. Well energy can be produced through other means too; water leads to reactions that produce much more energy, and are a lot more commonly occurring. Life, especially intelligent life, requires a lot of energy to sustain. Think of how malnutrition effects a growing body, if energy isn't taken in, or isn't enough, growth is stunted, like the runt in a litter of puppies that didn't get enough nutrients, energy, in the womb. More energy results in more growth. Brains that process the way ours do, require a lot of energy to develop, and water can produce a lot of energy in it chemical reactions. Therefore, when looking for intelligent life the presence of water is a great sign, especially when that life is given time to develop, which is provided by Irwombar's extended lifetime. Water also means Oxygen, the O in H2O, which can produce a lot of energy as well.  So, what's the next step in determining if our predictions are true and Irwombar may have intelligent life on it's planet? We will have to look for signs of this life, or bio signatures. If intelligent life exists, it could be in many forms, so it's hard to know what effect this life would have on it atmosphere that we could observe from a distance, so it's common to look for bio signatures similar to those of earth's as a starting point. Methane can be produced non-biologically so it isn't a good indicator of life. Oxygen might be a better indicator, considering it has grown considerably in our atmosphere since the advent of life on earth, and since more oxygen means better energy producing chemistry, which means more probability of life, excessive and growing amounts of oxygen in an atmosphere are great indicators of the possibility of intelligent life of Irwombar's planet. Whether this is the case, and whether oxygen is growing will be left to the years to see. But since Irwombar is quite a way away, we have much time to study it. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We here at Hablabs believe that we have discovered an excellent candidate for a habitable world that may well have life present upon it. The planet is called Aryn, and it is approximately 14.4 light years away from us, which is more than 70 trillion miles.

The planet Aryn orbits its star at 3.6 AU, which is about three and half times the distance that the Earth orbits the Sun. It is about 6 times as massive as Earth, and about twice as wide. It is slightly less dense than Earth, and has 5 times the atmospheric pressure at the surface. It's average surface temperature is several degrees cooler than Earth, and it has a similar total greenhouse effect.

An analysis of the light Aryn is emitting indicates the presense of several notable gases including Ozone, Methane, and Nitrogen. These gases were present on Earth during the rise of the first lifeforms, as may be conducive to life on Aryn as well.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Here at Hablabs we have found a new habital world in the Firrist Star system. This star system is 14.4 light years from our solar system. To put this in terms that we can easily understand, if we were to fly there in the worlds fastest commercial jet, the Concord, it would approximately 7.3 million calender years to arrive at this planet.

The host star of this planet has a luminosity of 3.4, that means it is 3.4 times as luminous as our own star. The means the star in this system is hotter than our own sun.

The planet we have found is 3.7 times the distance from the sun as the earth is from the sun. Despite the distance from the star the strong greenhouse effect on this planet keeps in warm enough enough to support liquid water, something that is extremely important to life on Earth, and we believe is essential for life on another planet. The expected average temperature on this planet is 51.53 degrees fahrenheit. In comparison Earth is 61 degrees.

It is a larger planet, twice the radius of earth, yet is density is 3.8 grams per cm cubed, while Earth is 5.5 gram per cm cubed. This leads us to believe that this planet will primarily be rocky, with some ice and very little metals. 

The planet seem to be fit for habitation, our next step is look for biosignatures, that might give us a reason to believe their is life on the planet. From what we know of our own planets we believe that an oxygen rich environment is necessary for advanced life, while it may appear in a Methane dominated environment, we believe oxygen is most important. For this reason we want to look at both the oxygen and methane levels in the atmosphere. Methane is not a good biosignature in terms of determining life on a planet. there are just too many non biological sources. However, if advanced life needs a oxygen rich environment we could rule out advanced life, in a methane rich environment. This is because methance will not last long in an oxygen rich atmoshpere. The major gas we want to look for in a foriegn atmoshpere is oxygen. 

We believe that the oxidation event in our atmoshpere is due to oxygenic photrophy by cyonbacteria, which would explain the shift from a methane rich atmopshpere to an oxygen rich atmoshpere. To determine this we need to look at the absorption spectrum of a planet.</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The star that I have found is 15% less in luminosity to the Sun. The host stars mass is 5% less and will live longer than the Suns projected lifetime. I was looking for a host star that was similar in radius, luminosity, mass, color and had similar wavelengths spectrums to the Sun. The planet that I discovered is a large planet, twice the size of Earth. The planet has close to 100% greenhouse effect, and has all the necessary gasses to make this planet habitable. This planet has an atmosphere and the pressure is with in normal range. The effective temperature, proposed surface pressure, and gasses all create a liquid state on this planet. I looked for planets that had a density of 3.0g/cm3 to 5.0g/cm3 so that the planet was similar to earth. I also looked at the gasses present, if the gasses did not have H20 it was less likely to be habitable.   </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Breaking news! A new planet that could potentially support life has just been discovered! The planet is about 18 light years (approximately 106 trillion miles) from our solar system. The planet orbits a star that is about 30% less bright than the Sun and has a projected lifetime of about 12.7 billion years, which is comparable to the Sun’s lifetime of about 10 billion years. The planet orbits the star at about 1.3 times the distance that the Earth orbits the Sun, creating perfect conditions for life to exist on its surface.
The planet is a terrestrial planet, which means that it is composed mostly of rock and metal just like Earth. It has about 1.6 time the mass Earth has and is about 1.3 times as large. This means that it has a density 4 times that of water (as opposed to Earth which has a density of about 5.5 times that of water). Given all of these conditions the projected surface temperature of the planet is about -138 °F. However, because of the strong greenhouse effect that scientists have detected, the actual temperature is predicted to be around 41.5 °F. While that may seem rather cold, we have to keep in mind that the average surface temperature of Earth is only 57.2 °F, so this really isn’t too far off from what we would call ideal. The planet also has a surface pressure 1.13 times that of Earth, meaning that we would feel a little heavier on this planet, but it would definitely be bearable. The combination of this pressure and temperature means that there is almost certainly liquid water on the surface of this planet, and therefore a great potential for life.
To continue the search for life scientists will look for certain biosignatures, which is basically anything that provides scientific proof of past or present life. These scientists will likely look for methane or oxygen. Methane can be a biosignature because many microorganisms produce methane as a waste product just like we produce carbon dioxide when we exhale. However there are many reasons why methane isn’t always reliable as an indicator of life. For example there are abiotic—meaning not having to do with biology—processes through which methane can be produced and can therefore create a false biosignature. Also, even if there are microorganisms producing methane, if the star is too bright the methane will be destroyed before scientists can detect it. Any biosignature will only be detectable if there are more sources (producers) than there are sinks (consumers). 
The discovery of a planet that has the potential to hold life is exciting enough, and despite the challenges still to come, scientists remain optimistic that this newly discovered planet will host some form of life.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My best candidate for a habitable world is 4.4 light years away. A light year is a measure of distance from here on earth. Light travels at about 186,000 miles per second. If you take all the seconds that tick by every single day in 4.4 years and multiply it by 186,000, that's how far my planet would be from earth. This planet has a star, just like ours has the sun. This planet and its star revolve around each other because of gravitational pull. Gravitational pull causes this planet and its star to circle each other at a certain distance apart without actually hitting each other. Once again, just like earth and the sun do. My planet's star has a luminosity of about .034 Ls, meaning its only about 3.4% as bright as our star. Since brightness or luminosity means more heat energy leaving that star, that means the planet I found needs to be much closer to this star then we are to our sun. Which it is. It has a distance of .22 AU which means this certain planet is about 88% closer to its star then we are to the sun. Both of the units I have referred to , AU and Ls, are in comparison our sun. This planet is slightly larger than earth, and seems to be made up of much rock because rocks have a density about 3. Because of a strong greenhouse effect, or a heating of a planet due to gases trapped in its atmospher, this planet has a temperature of over 100 degrees fahrenheit.  </string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The best canidate I found in my discovery is a star called Fintan. This star is 14.4 light years away from our earth, which is 84652205373843.95 in miles as an easier way to look at it. The luminosity of this particuar star, which means the intrinsic brightness of a celestial object, is 3.412001437. The luminosity of a star depends on both its temperature and it's radius. A hotter star is more luminous than a cooler one of the same radius. A bigger star is more luminous than a smaller one of the same temperature. The projected lifetime of this star is 4.1617801934658637E9 years. My planets distance from the star is 3.681903282481253 AU. AU stands for astronomical unit which is a unit of length. When I would look for biosignatures, I would look for an atmosphere cloe to that of the earths composition. </string>

      <string>Extra, Extra read all about it! I have found the missing link!! Oh wait, wrong head line, but I have found a potential planet that could be our next Earth! Also to mention, that this planet is quite a bit warmer the Earth is now, sun tanning for everyone, or just a lot of sun screen. It is a rocky planet, which is similar to Earth now, which is good for lots of hiking and what have you. I find this lovely planet to be a great new host planet for humanity to grow and evolve.     <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>If we were to travel to this habitable star system by car traveling at 60mph, it would take 1,042,383,386 years to get there. So we would most certainly need to create more advanced spaceships to get there in a timely manner.
The star itself is quite similar to our own regarding it's lifetime of approximately 10 billion years. The only difference is that it will look more red than our sun and is not as bright. However, the planet's atmosphere in this star system produces the right qualities to support liquid water, which means life; just like our own planet Earth does! It is also considerably closer to the star than Earth is to the Sun, which is necessary in order to recieve the right amount of energy from the Sun to make the planet livable. The pressure that out atmosphere exerts here on Earth is rather higher than on this new planet, so the air may seem a bit thin; just like when climbing higher in elevation. This planet is considerably larger than our own planet as well, so expect gravity to be stronger!</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Jhalromer is the best candidate to be a habitable world for multiple reasons. It orbits a small dim star which has a projected lifetime of more than 120 billion years. Because this star is so small the planet, Jhalromer needs to be much closer to it, about a quarter of this distance of earth to the sun. Jhalromer is only about thirty percent larger than earth and has a composition that is mostly rock and some metal. The planet has a strong atmosphere composed of many gasses creating a slightly higher pressure than the one here on earth. This is necessary however to create the greenhouse effect, keeping the planet at a warm and stable temperature suitable for life.</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Based on pressure and temperature, we can see that my star Jena is suitable to hold liquid water. This is made possible due to greenhouse gases that get absorbed and cause the temperature to rise, making it in the perfect range for water. This is one of the most important factors. The density of my planet falls near the 3g/cm^3 range. This means that it has the consistency of a rocky/terrestrial planet, which is what Earth is made up of. The other options can be gas or ice but these are not suitable for life. Earth has been around for around 4.6 billion years; so putting that into perspective with Jena's lifetime allows us to see the similarities between the two. All of these characteristics help create a planet that is habitable. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Breaking News:  Another Potentially Habitable Planet, Has Been Discovered!
A mere 14.4 light years from Earth is Brollod, a star which is nearly 3.5 times brighter than our Sun and whose projected life time is approximately 4.2 billion years. Orbiting Brollod is a planet that is about 6 times the mass of Earth, twice Earth's circumfrence, and about as dense as our Moon. This planet just so happens to be within the Brollod's Habitable Zone, or the region around a star within which planets with sufficient atmospheric pressures, which this new planets has, can support liquid water at their surfaces. The Effective Temperature of this planet, a frigid 184.2 K, indicates that it would be a frozen wasteland, but the presence of a Strong Greenhouse Effect, which is created by the presence of  numerous greenhouses gases in its atmosphere, increases this planet's temperature about about 100 K and therefore allows Brollod to heat the planet to a livable temperature, melting the ice into usable, liquid water. The presence of water, which is comprised of Hydrogen and Oxygen, along with many other necessary greehouse gases, on Brollod's planet gives a strong positive correlation that life as we are most familiar with it and it's requirements on Earth would be sustainable there as well. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The star system that I have discovered revolves around the star, Jurgol. Jurgol hosts a planet that is able to sustain life if need be. There may be life already on the planet, but as of now that is unknown. This planet is projected to live for about 600 billion years. 

Though the planet is very far from its star, the star is bright enough to warm the planet to livable temperatures. This planet has an effective temperature of about 208 degrees Kelvin; that's about -85 degrees Fahrenheit. Although the planet is below freezing, the greenhouse gasses in this planets atmosphere allow sunlight in, but trap the heat that the planet emits back into space. Therefore, the planet will actually be about 308 degrees Kelvin, or 94 degrees Fahrenheit. As well as trapping in heat, the gasses in the atmosphere are ones that organisms can live off of.
</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The star-planet system, with its host star known as Abrios, is located 4.4 light years away from Earth which is approximately 26,400,000,000,000 miles.  When speaking about luminosity - which is the total amount of energy emitted from a star, compared to the Sun, we can say that if a start is 2Ls then it is 2 times more lumnious than the Sun.  So the luminosity from Abrios, is slightly less luminous at .033825373 and has a projected lifetime of approximately 112,341,703,238 years. The distance from a star to a planet can be measured in astonimcal units (AU) and can be compared to the distance between the Earth and Sun which is 1AU approximately 93 milion miles.  So the distance between Abrios and the planet is less than 1AU at approximately 22 million miles apart.  The density of the planet is at 3.5, a level on a density chart where it is considered to be made/composed of mostly rock making this planet a “terrestrial planet” which has “earth-like” features.  By observing the rocks and soil of the planet I hope to discover different biosignatures such as nucleic acids, lipids, proteins that are produced by life processes.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>     After doing thorough research and diligent searching, I have found a great candidate for a habitable world, called Chadranan. The planet is approximately 83.6 light years away from us. A light year is an astronomical unit that is used for distances that are substantially large. 1 light year is equal to about 9.4605284 × 10^15 meters. 
     When searching for a habitable planet, the planet itself is not the only important factor to take into consideration. The planet's host star also plays an important role in the system. The habitable zone describes an area around the star where the conditions are just right for an Earth-like planet. Each star has different luminosities, which is the total amount of energy released by an object in all directions. The host star I examined had the luminosity of 0.0308 Ls and projected lifetime of  approximately120 billion years. Luminosity is calculated by taking into consideration the absolute magnitude, while the projected lifetime takes into consideration the mass of the star. 
     The planet needs to be an appropriate distance away from the host star. If it is too far, then the planet might be too cold and if it is too close, it might be too hot to be considered habitable. The planet's distance from the star is .19077AU (Astronomical Units), which equates to about 28,539,350.2 kilometers. Mass and Radius are measured in reference to Earth (ME and RE). Planets densities can be calculated to classify what type of planet composition it posses. Chadranan's density calculated out to about 4.79g/cm3, which puts it in the category of mostly rock with some metal. 
     In order for a planet to be considered "habitable", we also need to take into consideration the surface pressure, effective temperature and the greenhouse effect. The surface pressure calculated to be 6.88atm, which is composed from the specific gases present in the atmosphere. The effective temperature is only 224.67K  (-55.2F), but with the greenhouse effect being strong, it makes the overall temperature about 324.67K (124.7F). The atmosphere causes natural warming (greenhouse effect). Sunlight warms the planet giving it the effective temperature. Then the planet emits the energy back and the gases temporarily absorb the energy. This results in more energy in the atmosphere and makes the actual temperature higher depending on how strong the greenhouse effect is. 
     Lastly, bio signatures are important when looking for life on a planet. Any gas that is produced by a waste product by any kind of metabolism, can potentially be bio signature. There are many metabolisms that exist and evolve over time. Attributes of life include its complex physical and chemical structures and also utilizes free energy. Possible bio signatures that we should look for life are cellular substances, microfossils, stromatolites, isotopic compositions of carbon, nitrogen,hydrogen and oxygen. 
     In conclusion, even though finding life on this planet may be a long shot, Chadranan posses many characteristics that would make it a strong candidate. 

     
     
</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: 

Marisa Hicks
Arizona State University
(805) 312 1268
marisa.anne.nora@gmail.com

Watch Out Earthlings, Here Comes Gorthlros
Tempe, AZ. April 29, 2015-A habitable planet was discovered early this morning by an Arizona State University student, Marisa Hicks. "Defining a habitable world may be harder than pronouncing the name of the planet," Marisa joked, "It takes more than just a powerful sun and water to make a planet habitable." Based on her calculations, Gorthlros has just the right 'ingredients' to make this happen. 

What are those ingredients, and if life can survive on Gorthlros, does that mean it already exists? To make a planet habitable, which is to say that a planet has the potential to hose life, a sun with a specific amount of light close enough to the planet to provide energy in the form of heat, an atmosphere with the winning combination of gasses that contributes a positive Greenhouse effect, similar to Earth, be made up of a combination of rock and metal, with just the right surface temperature to maintain liquid water. Phew! 

"Gorthlros is about three times the size of our Earth, but it's about seven times the distance from its host star as Earth is to the sun. The luminosity, or brightness of the sun makes up for the distance. The planet's density is ehavy, meaning it's made up primarily of metal and rock, but could also have a bit of ice and/or gas too" stated Marisa. 

"Unless we can find a way to travel at the speed of light, or go into deep sleep for years, like the characters in 'Interstellar,' we won't be traveling to Gorthlros in our lifetime." Marisa continues: "Gorthlros is about nine light-years away from us, or about 53 trillion miles away. Yes, trillions. That's a whole lot of zeroes behind that 53!"

Enen though we cannot travel to Gorthlros right now, further research can be made to determine if there is life on the planet. "When people think of life, they often think of humans. But when we say 'life' in scientific terminology, we mean any type of organism, even single-celled bacteria," Marisa clarified. "In order to determine if life is present, we will start looking at the biosignatures of the planet, such as the atmospheric changes of methane and oxygen. While this alone cannot successfully determine if there is life on a planet*, it's certainly a start in the right direction." 
     *Methane changes can be caused by geography, thus yielding a false positive. Additionally, organisms exist that do not require oxygen to breathe such as cyanobacteria, which uses the sun as fuel and releases oxygen into the atmosphere, which does not conclusively prove one way or another life exists with or without an abundant amount of oxygen in the atmosphere. 

ARIZONA STATE UNIVERSITY
Arizona State University is a public university located in Tempe, Arizona. It has additional campus locations and hosts a number od degree-seeking students online. For more information, please refer to the Arizona State University website. 

- END - 
</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>After an examination of 500 stars, and finding over 100 planets, I am pleased to announce that has been a discovery of an Earthlike planet.  It is located in the Jubriboru system, located approximately 4.4 light years away from our own system.  (Light years is the distance light can travel in a year; it is approximately 9.5 trillion kilometers or 5.88 trillion miles per year).

The Jubriboru system consists of a low-luminousity star, (meaning that it is not as bright as our own Sun), with a projected lifetime of over 1.12 hundred billion years.  The planet itself has a very tight orbit around Jubriboru; the orbit is about 8/10ths closer than the Earth is from the Sun.  The planet it slighty larger and heavier than our Earth, but not by much.  While the atmospheric pressure may be a little more than Earth's, that helps to give the newly discovered planet a hospitable temperature for life as we might know it.

Further examination of this planet is needed to see what kinds of life is on it.  The examinations will include scanning for 'biosignatures', chemical signs that life exists that are produced as waste products by living creatures.  These chemical traces can include methane, carbon dioxide and oxygen.  While methane and carbon dioxide can be produced by geological means as well as by organic means, oxygen is a waste product of life using carbon dioxide to produce energy.    

These developments are very exciting and I am looking forward to reporting more advancements on the Jubriboru system.  </string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Out of all the planets in my sample, this planet resulted to be the best cadidate for life. The first aspect of this system that makes it a good candidate for life was it's star, Foromaiven. It is very similar to the sun in our solar system in size and luminosity, which means it will give off a similar amount of energy, creating a suitable place for a planet to host habitable conditions. Now, looking at the planet itself, there are many aspects that give the possiblity of life forming on it's surface or below. First and formost, it's temperature and presence of the greenhouse effect are crucial, since having an atmosphere is essential to hosting life. It fulfils both of these criteria. Another crucial component this planet contains is the presence of elements. This planet is very element rich, and is neccessary to give the molecular platform for unicellular life to form.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The star Kama is located at about 14.42 light years from earth. This is relatively close considering the vastness of space. Although this is still 84.8 trillion miles. That’s a long distance, if we drove a car at 200 mph consistently it would take 48.4 million years to reach. Matter of fact, it still takes light 14.42 years for it to travel from earth to this star, and light travels at 671 million miles per hour. So yes this star is relatively close to other stars that are out there. Now Kama is about three times more luminous than the sun. This means it gives off more energy than the sun. This means that it burns its fuel faster than the sun as well, but its expected life time is only slightly less than of our sun. This indicates it should have plenty of time to host the formation of life on the orbiting planet. The planet that orbits Kama is located at 3.671 AU, which is about 341 million miles. Comparatively earth is located about 93 million miles from the sun. But since Kama burns much brighter and hotter than the sun, being further from the star benefits the planet so that it isn't scorched or incinerated by the star. The effective temperature is only calculated to be about 183.1 K but due to the observed chemical composition of the atmosphere we can estimate the temperature to be around 283.1 K which is a reasonable temperature for liquid water to exist. Due to the calculated denisty it is determined that  this planet is has a rocky and metallic make up, so there is a solid surface to walk on, with an atmospher above it. The atmosphere is actually fairly thick, 5 times heavier than earths, and the mass of the planet is also about 5 times larger than earth. This would suggest any life forms that live on this planet would have to be much stronger to over come the force of gravity and more arrow dynamic in order to manuever on the surface. If humans ever traveled to this planet they would need a space suit that would support their bodily structure so that they can easily move with less gravitational resistance.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We are pleased to announce the discovery of Bisperon Prime, nicknamed Starbug since it is a little green thing connected to a Red Dwarf. 

The planetary system of Bisperon is almost one hundred light years from us, making visitation basically impossible at this time. After all space is big, like really big. I mean you may think it's a long way down to the chemists but that's just peanuts to space. At any rate the star is small and dim, much cooler than our sun, a Red Dwarf Star in fact. 

At first glance Starbug is not in fact warm enough to support life. It is far closer to Bisperon than Earth is to the sun but again the star itself is much weaker. However early observations indicate that Starbug has a relatively thick atmosphere that contains carbon dioxide and water vapor, which would warm it up considerably. However it's air pressure is only about 44% that of Earth normal. So in theory the air is breathable but thin, not unlike living in Utah really. It is much warmer than Utah however, on average, so it is somewhat like being in the Andes Mountains in the Raiinforest. 

We have not yet found concrete evidence of life on Starbug but we are hopeful. If the planetary atmosphere changes over time as we observe this could be the effect of plant and animal analogues, or even bacteria. In particular a shift in CO2 levels would indicate probably life. We will continue to observe the planet closely for any such changes. In addition, just in case it already has intelligent life we have sent a coded signal to the planet to arrive in just under a century. And of course we are listening in as well. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Gisesius is interesting because it is so very different than our system. For one, the star is very low in luminosity but due to the very short orbital distance it allows the planet to collect relitively  ample heat (energy). This energy alone is not what makes the planet habitable though. The very low albedo(reflectivity), suggests a world with a good amount of rock and water. This allows the planet to have a decent effective temperature ( baseline temperature before greenhouse effect). Additionally, the plethora of greenhouse gasses present in the atmosphere allow it to retain enough energy to ssutain that liquid water. There are interesting gasses involved, like Nitrogen Dioxide. While these gasses can be easily explained naturally, nitrogen dioxide is a pollutant that can occur from industrialization. It could be possible that intelligent life is the cause.... or not. 

I have high expectation as to the amount of single cellular life that will be found on this planet, and optimistic expectations for multi-cellular life forms. Possibly even a homonoid species</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Dortrolan, believed to be a habitable world, was discovered orbiting a star with 0.00292 luminosity. This does not necessarily mean that the star looks that bright but rather than it is intrinsically that bright relative to our sun. Since our sun has a luminosity of 1, that means this star has a much weaker luminosity. Scientists project this star has a lifetime of about 643.9 billion years. The planet, Dortrolan, was discovered orbiting this star at a distance of 0.0713 astronomical units. One astronomical unit is equal to about 150 million kilometers, which means Dortrolan is located about 10.7 million kilometers away from its host star. This planet has five times the mass of Earth and two times the radius of Earth. Its density is about 3, which means that it is a terrestrial planet, having rocks and metal much like Earth. 

Careful estimates propose a surface pressure of about 0.28 atmospheric pressure. This is lower than the atmospheric pressure we experience on Earth, which has an average pressure of 1. We also found the planet has an effective temperature of 207.88 Kelvin, which is about -87.07 degrees fahrenheit. Effective temperature is the amount of heat coming from the host star that is projected to hit the planets surface; this is not the same as the temperature of the planet. If it were, the planet would be far to cold to be habitable. However, many other factors, such as pressure and the greenhouse effect, greatly influence the temperature of the planet. Increased pressure actually increases the freezing point of water and decreases the boiling point of water, increasing the chances that water will remain liquid on the planet longer--an essential aspect of habitability. Also, a stronger greenhouse effect means the planet will be warmer. To put it simply, an atmosphere with a strong greenhouse effect contains gasses that interact with this energy, holding the warmth within the atmosphere for a while before leasing it into space. This warms the planet over time. Thus, a strong atmospheric greenhouse combined with the pressure of the atmosphere warms the planet enough to make it a potential habitable world. 

How can we tell if there is life there however? We find this by looking at the planet’s biosignature, a complicated term that essentially means looking at any gas in the atmosphere that is produced as a waste product by any kind of metabolism. While some scientists would look for the presence of the gas methane in the atmosphere, I would not trust this gas because there are too many potential nonbiological explanations. Instead, I would look for the presence of oxygen since it is essential for people, animals, and multicellular life to breathe. Oxygen would be detectable if more oxygen was being released into the atmosphere than was being taken away. Nonetheless, I would keep my mind open to new possibilities. There could, no doubt, exist different sources of life out there, and we simply don’t have the ability to imagine it because the Earth is all we have known. Therefore, while I would focus on searching for oxygen and other stable gasses present on Earth, I would be excited to discover another way of life on a new habitable world. </string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Today, we have discovered a planet orbiting Jeralthna, a star just over 31 lightyears away from Earth, that we believe has the potential to support life. Jeralthna is a star that is roughly 16 times as bright as the Sun. The planet orbits the star at about the same distance that Earth orbits the Sun and is about 1.5 times as large as Earth. Normally, when planets orbit so closely to stars so bright, they end up looking more like Mercury, however, the planets rich and thick atmosphere help the planet retain its liquid water, as opposed to burning up or freezing over, which is key for determining whether or not we believe a planet can support life.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>  Most stars, about 90 percent, belong to what is referred to as main sequence. Stars spend most of their lives in this category before evolving up the scale of what is called the Hertzsprung Russell Diagram. However, some are in different phases of their life cycles, some of which are referred to as Red Giants (this is dying star). In fact, in about 5 billion years from now, our own sun will become just such and life as we now know it will cease to exist. However, that time is not yet here, and I have discovered what I believe to be a habitable planet, Ethraziel.

  This planet appears to have the characteristics needed to sustain life. What would make me think this planet might be habitable? Well, I looked for certain trace gasses such as CO2 and H2O. Also, how strong the greenhouse effect might be, and what might be the water phase; that is, could it be liquid? Liquid water being very important, after all, water vapor is our most abundant greenhouse gas. That said, only after observing such things as a Doppler shift and conducting a careful study of the transit spectrum can we determine the possible chemical composition and the extent of the atmosphere of a transiting exoplanet.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>               Kalis is a cool red red star that lies 4.4 light years from our Earth.  What makes it so exciting is the fact that we know from studying the light emitted by Kalis that the planet orbiting this star contains water in the liquid form. 
           Kalis, along with being cool is a lot smaller and longer lived than our sun.  Kalis is estmated to live 112 billion years, which is over 11 times longer than the time our own sun will remain alive.  This cool small star emits about 3.4 % of the amount of radiation that our sun emits.  This means that any planet that has the ability to support liquid water must be much closer to this star than we are to our sun.  In fact we find that the planet orbiting Kalis is about .22 AU's away, where 1 AU is about 93 million miles.  This means that our candidate for life is merely 20.46 million miles away from it's star.    This is much closer mercury is to our own sun.  Mercury is a desolate wasteland, pockmarked by craters with no atmosphere to speak of.  Because Kalis is so much less luminous it's host planet can maintain temperate conditions at a very close distance by astronomical standards.
            Our candidate has a size that is slightly larger than earth, but a composition that is very similar.  The atmosphere is proposed to have a pressure of 1.55 earth atmospheres, and is composed of gases like oxygen, methane, carbon dioxide, ammonia, and ozone.  All of these gases, essential to life and our interactive ecosystem provide evidence that there may be life on this planet.  Oxygen is an important byproduct of plant respiration and this could be a clue that there is some form of biological life releasing large amounts of oxygen into the atmosphere.  Liquid water, methane, carbon, ammonia, and nitrogen with temperate conditions provide a breeding ground for the formation of organic molecules.</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Alternative home for humanity has been found! A star-planet system that is being referred to as Fikikia has recently been discovered to have the potential to harbor life if Earth were to become no longer sufficient to our needs. This new system is 4.4 light years away from us so travel there is still unrealistic for everyone on Earth today. However a mission spanning generations could be theoretically possible. The new system has a sun much different from our own however. The sun in the Fikikia system is much less bright but would also appear much larger in the sky. This is due to the fact the the planet in the system is extremely close to the star compared to Earth. Another interesting fact about this newly discovered system is that the planet is actually larger and more massive than Earth. Like Earth though is a very strong greenhouse effect on the new planet. However, it is believed to be similar to Earth on the surface making it the ideal candidate for a new home if one was ever needed.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My planet is habitable for a number of reasons. The distance of the planet to its star is important.  Too close and it will burn up, or too far and it may be too cold. My planet is the proper distance, where water can exist on the surface. The star's luminosity, or brightness, is appropriate. If it were too bright, the planet could be too hot, and the planet may absord too much energy.  The mass plays an important roll. The mass effects the internal temperature. The greater the temperature, the more energy there is, and it will burn faster. Therefore, too much mass would mean a shorer-lived planet. Secondly, if a planet has too low of mass, the lesser gravity could affect its atmosphere, which isneeded to help retain energy and control the temperature of the planet.   The projected lifetime of my planet is vast. The radius and density are very important. The density  of my planet is such that it it mostly made of rock. Similar to Earth, we look for rocky-terrestrial-like plamets for the potential for similar characeteristis as ours.The effective temperature is such, so when there are temperature flucations or present gases, it will not affect its surface temperature, which would ultimately affect the planet's habilitablity. The greenhouse effect is basically in which the atmosphere warms up because it absorbs more energy than it transmits. The atmosphere warms up until it emits the same amount it is absorbing. As a result of this, the surface temperature is raised, which ultimately warms the planet above its effective temperate. I found a planet in which the greenhouse effect is strong, but not so much as to throw off the temperature or affect the planet and make it unhabilitable. Biosignatures you can expect to find on my  planet are water vapor, nitrogren and carbon dioxide, and molecules, all of which will indicate present life.</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Conditions on Dagolath are are suitable to accommodate life.  This is an exciting discovery in the search for Earth-like planets.  

Fun Facts:
>491 TRILLION Miles away from us
>3.6 times more massive than Earth
>Average Temperature:  -55.2705 degrees fahrenheit 

The star in this solar system is not very bright (our sun puts out about 33 times more energy).  This is okay, since Dagolath is very close to the star.  It also has a very strong greenhouse effect, which means it is able to retain much of the energy it produces.  Greenhouse gasses include carbon dioxide, methane, and water, and are produced naturally, perhaps by volcanoes.  The atmospheric pressure on this planet is 6.88 times what we have on Earth.  This allows it to have liquid water despite the low average temperature.  

</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>In the star sytem of 70 stars there was one planet that was found as possibly being habitiable. This planet, that we could possibly find life on, is found orbiting a star named Heldim. Heldim is about 14.4 light years away, that's very very very far, we mostly likely could not actually travel to this planet. The star that is about 3 and a half times brighter than our own sun and is projected to live 4.16 billions years. That is a couple million years less than our sun. This planet is about 3.5 times farther away from it's star than we are from our sun and its mass is about 6.1 times more than ours. It's radius is also about 2 times larger than ours and it's density is 3.7 g per cm cubed which is about 2 g per cm cubed less than ours. The estimated surface pressure is 5.3 atm while ours is 1. The effective temp, which is the projected temp to keep the planet stable is 184.2 K however, it's greenhouse effect is strong causing the temp to rise to 284.2 K. You could look for all biosignatures in this planet but the most helpful would be H2O.</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Jomer was my best canidate from my habitable planets. With the combination of necessary characteristics of the host star and planet characteristics it is made habitable for life. The effective temperature of Jomer is aronud 178 K, with the green house effect which pushes up the surface temperature about 100 K making the surface temperature 278 K(keeping the temp. between the boiling point and freezing point of H20). Also creating an atmosphere for the planet making it habitable with most likely necessary elemements such as carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphourus, or sulfur-which are necessary for life (life including metabolism, reproduction, and adaptations). The density of the planet (calculated by its mass and radis)is approximately 4 g/cm^3 meaning that the planet is mostly made up of terrestrial components such as liquid water, rocks, etc. which is necessary for life on a planet. Since the luminosity of the star is around .7 that directly affects the surface temperature of the planet, aiding in habitability.  
</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I have discovered that the star Akin hosts a habitable planet. This particular star is approximately 500 trillion miles away. The planet that it hosts has many similarities to Earth. This planet is about 40% bigger than Earth. The surface temperature of this planet is also close to that of Earth. Earth has an average surface temperature of 59 degrees fahrenheit and the planet I discovered is close to 50 degrees fahrenheit at its surface. Another important part to this planet's habitability is the biosignatures present in the atmosphere. Some biosignatures I would look for on this planet would be water, carbon dioxide, methane, and nitrous oxide. I would look for these particular biosignatures because these are the same ones that are most prominent in Earth's atmosphere. These biosignatures are what will keep the planet warm and habitable but also keep the water on the planet liquid rather than turning into vapor or ice. Things I would look for on the planet's surface would be liquid water, volcanoes, and mountains to show proof of these biosignatures being present. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My star-planet system is full of main sequence stars most of which are Red Dwarfs. It is also abundant in Sun-like stars, Blue Giants, and a few White Dwarfs. I had the biggest difficulty finding Red Giants and Super Giants. I could only find four of the first and three of the later. Out of the 38 Main Sequence stars I analyzed, 16 of them had planets orbiting them. Out of these 16 planets, four were Ice Giants, eight were Gas Giants, and the remaining four were Terrestrial.  Celeder’s planet was too cold to harbor life as the star had a luminosity or brightness of 9.454 Ls (1 Ls is equal to the brightness of the sun) and an orbital radius of 0.876 astronomical units or AU (1 AU is equal to the distance from the Earth to the sun). Cuhaimor’s planet was too hot with its luminosity of 16.05 Ls and an orbital radius of 0.69 astronomical units. The stars Barcyn and Arsiri had metal Terrestrial planets orbiting them that were capable of harboring life. These two Habitable planets had many similarities and differences. Both planets had the same gasses present in their atmospheres, that being methane, carbon dioxide, water vapor, hydrogen sulfide, nitrous oxide, ammonia, and ozone. This resulted in both planets having high absorption percentages and strong Greenhouse effects. The best candidate was Barcyn's planet with the star's luminosity of 21.11 Ls and the planet's orbital radius of 0.86 astronomical units. It's surface temperature is about 462.1 Kelvin (371 Farenheit) but with a surface pressure of 22.5 atm (atmospheric pressure) it is able to sustain liquid water and is therefore habitable. Since the planet is very warm and it's star is rather old (higher luminosity equals an older star) there should be organisms similar to what we find on earth on Barcyn's planet. The life on Barcyn's planet may even be intelligent life. We would need to look for oxygen (air) and chlorophyll (plant life) to ensure that even the smallest form of life really does exist on this planet. We would need to assess the planet's spectra to determine whether these elements exist on the planet.  </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string> I found a habitable planet that orbited the star Iyu'nivean. Its distance is measured in light-years because any other form of measurement wouldn't be large enough to calculate the distance. It is 62.7 light-years away. The star that this planet orbits is bright, giving off a luminosity of approximately 0.0254. The luminosity is the total amount of energy that a star gives off. This new habitable planet is expected to live 137 billion years. This planet is just a little over twice the size of Earth with a radius similar to Earth's. Its surface pressure is half that of Earth. Effective Temperature is expected to be -44.464 Fahrenheit but because the greenhouse effect is strong, which means more gases will be in movement inside the atmosphere, its surface temperature will be anywhere from 81degrees to 130 degrees in Fahrenheit. This planet will be considerably warmer than Earth, as you can see.	
This planet will be in another galaxy since it is so far from Earth but that doesn’t mean that life can’t —or hasn’t— thrived on this planet. In order to know if life has been on this planet, researchers need to be aware of the biosignatures, which are substances that are proof for past or current life on a planet. Proof of plant life, things that plant life produces (such as oxygen), substance for life (such as water), waste products (such as carbon dioxide ), and bacteria (such as nitrous oxide). Conditions that these could survive in are called the “habitable zone.” This is where planets can support liquid water, so long as the atmospheric pressure is compatible. 
Carbon dioxide (CO2) can survive in atmospheres (and in the planet) with the temperatures of -99F to 260F. In the higher degrees, CO2 only exists in the atmosphere. At 78F, there can be precipitation in the atmosphere where atmospheric CO2 and oxygen (O2) combine to make carbonic acid (H2CO3). When it goes through weathering, H2CO3 loses some of the molecules and turns into bicarbonate (HCO3). HCO3 will travel through rivers and underground into the ocean where it will combine with calcium to become calcium carbonate (CaCO3). And so on. This is only the cycle life of CO2, but as you can see, it is very important in an atmosphere. Because it can be detected in many conditions, it can be found.
Oxygen (O2) was emitted into our atmosphere 2.9 billion years ago by cyanobacteria, so those could be proof on other planets that there is possible life there. 
Earth may not be the only inhabited planet in our sky if the biosignatures of life having existed or currently existing is discovered on other planets, such as the one I have found.
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Ladies and gentlemen of the press,

We come to you today with cautious optimism about our mission to discover a new Earth!  After careful measurements and diligent patience, we have discovered a strong candidate.

It is orbiting around the star Glos, which is about 96 lightyears away.  That is incredibly far.  One lightyear alone, converted to miles, is 5.88 trillion miles!  The speed of light travels just under 670 million miles an hour.  To put that into perspective, if you were running around the equator at the speed of light, you would lap the Earth 7.5 times!

Until we get to interstellar travel, we can talk about the other characteristics of our discovery.  The star itself is not much like our Sun.  When we measure stars, we measure the perceived brightness.  From that measurement, we can find the true magnitude of the star, what we call luminosity.  As an example, we could measure two candles wich are at different distances from us, and still get the same magnitude from both.  The luminosity of Glos is a fraction of our Sun, about 1/1000th.  What this means is that the temperature of this star is lower than the sun.  While our sun is yellow, Glos is a deep red; Glos is a red dwarf.  This means it is much cooler than our sun, but that it will live for a much longer time.

You may be asking yourselves how we can live around a star that is so much smaller than our sun.  Well, that is because our new Earth is a little different as well!  The planet itself is bigger than Earth; about three times as massive, and about 50% spatially bigger.  Hoever, what makes this planet habitable is the distance it orbits Glos.  New Earth is at an orbital distance of 0.0303, while our Earth is at 1.  To put this into perspective, let's say Tucson is 100 miles away.  That is the distance from the Earth to the Sun.  By that standard, New Earth is only three miles from Tucson, while we're 100 miles.  If Earth was a foot from the sun, New Earth is a third of one inch from Glos!  

So what will it be like there?  The pressure on New Earth is about half of hat we experience here on Earth.  What that means is it will be a little harder to breathe, if there is oxygen.  But your rice will cook faster, so that's good!  The atmosphere is pretty similar to ours, and has a strong greenhouse effect.  What that means is the energy emitted by the Earth, which includes absorbed starlight, warms the planet an extra 180 degrees F.  Without that effect, the planet would b a cool -40 degrees F.  What the actual average temperature will be is close to 142 degrees F.  That is hot, but not unhabitable!  I imagine, if we are able to colonize, we will live at the poles mostly, until our future generations evolve well enough to live comfortably.

Our next step is to figure out if there is life already there.  There are a couple ways we propose to do that.  Firstly, we are going to see if there is Methane in the atmosphere.  What that means is carbon dioxide and hydrogen are present, which are important for life.  Methane is not a reliable indicator for life, but it's a start.  The next step is we will look for oxygen buildup in the atmosphere.  That may mean there is plenty to go around, or there is some process on the planet that is not allowing it to live at the surface.  By using these two measurements, we can see if there is any dynamism on New Earth, which is a good indicator that the planet may go through similar changes as the Earth, allowing single-celled organism to live.  

Ladies and gentlement, thank you very much for your time, and for sharing our excitement at this wonderful prospect!       
       </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>This star-planet system is a potential habitable world because it is just the right distance from its star to be considered an Earth-like planet. This means that the planet’s mass, radius, and density are relatively similar to our home planet and could contain organic life forms like what we see on Earth (i.e., plants, animals, water, oxygen). The temperature of the planet, surface pressure, and greenhouse effect are also reflective of Earth-like characteristics. The planet is not too hot like Venus, and not frozen over like  a planet stuck in the Ice Age. This is because of the host star, or “Sun.” The star’s luminosity plays a part in warming the planet, as well as the greenhouse effect, which causes natural warming to the planet. Sunlight warms the planet’s surface until it reaches it’s effective temperature, and gases in the planet’s atmosphere can absorb energy that the planet itself emits. The major greenhouse gases that are emitted by the planet are very common on Earth: water vapor, carbon dioxide, methane, and nitrous oxide. These are biosignatures that can help scientists discover if there has been life on this planet or if life currently exists. Certain minerals and elements can be found on planets and rocks that can also give us this information.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>In the long search of the galaxy for a habitable world, the best candidate to host a habitable world is the star system Drine.  This star system is 4.4 light years from Earth, which is the same distance as another well known nearby star, Alpha Centauri.  With our current technology it would take approximately 80,000 years to travel this distance.  However, through our observations we have deemed it an excellent candidate to host a habitable world.  Through observation of the passing light, we noticed that an orbiting world is present.  This world is slightly larger than Earth in both mass and radius.  It's density is much lower than our own, meaning that it is made of a larger composition of rock than Earth, and has a lot less metal.  The planet is much closer to its star than we are to our own, it is actually even closer to its star than Mercury is to ours.  However, Drine is much more dim than our star, about 3 percent of the brightness or our Sun.  The planet's pressure would be greater than on earth, like going about 35 feet under water, and would therefor be more difficult to walk.  The surface temperature would be about 169.5 degrees farenheit, which is obviously much warmer than Earth, but with the greater pressure and larger greenhouse effect it would still be very warm, but not as warm as that temperature would seem on Earth.  While life would most likely be harsh on this alien world, the fact that it has the ability to host liquid water is immensely valuable to the creation of life and make it a prime candidate in our search for a habitable world. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>This newly identified star-planet is habitable. As you can see from the planets characteristics like its distance from stars, mass, radius, density, proposed surface pressure, effective temperature, and greenhouse effect the numbers are relatively similiar to those of earth. As far as we knew Earth was the only habitable planet, with this discovery we see there are other forms of possible signs of life out there. In order for life to occur on this star-planet it would have to contain certain biosignatureswhich provide scientific evidence of past or present life. For this planet to be habitable for plants and animals some things it would need are oxygen, nitrogen, carbon dioxide, and water to name a few. Indo contains these elements in its atmosphere. Also for plant life carrying out photosynthesis is necessary and can only be done by having a certain amount of carbon in the atmosphere in the form of carbon dioxide. Effective Temperature on habitable planets is extremely necessary because plants and animals cannot survive if the temperatures are too extreme. For sustaining a stable habitable temperature, the mixture of greenhouse gases is critical. If a planet loses the balance of greenhouse gases it can lead to a heating or cooling of the planet in dire ways. The longevity of this planet is important as well, because it means the planet will be able to survive for over 10 billion years giving plenty of time for plants and animals to develop and evolve into a fully functioning society that could replicate Earth's present society in terms of government, healthcare, and languages. </string>
