      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Finding a habitable planet was very challenging. I knew this would be the case, because of all the lessons we have gone over in class, and how exact all the calculations had to be for everything to align and for a habitable world. When looking for a habitable world, I first looked at the distance from the star and the luminosity. Because Earth is only 1 AU from the Sun, I wanted to find a planet that wasn't too far away from the its star. I also was interesed in the lifetime of the star. Because it takes a long time for life to develop on a planet with the perfect conditions, I wanted to find a star that could last long enough to support this growth of life. The most important part of the planet is that it did have water and it was at the right temperature to be liquid based.  </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Could there be life outside of the Earth? A planet was recently discovered with characteristics that may support life! This planet is being referred to as Crabiltia. Just like Earth, Crabiltia has water! Crabiltia's temperature is supportive of liquid water. Water is essential to the formation of life, when the H2O disappears, so will any signs of life.
What else is needed on a planet to support life? Energy! Energy is vital to the exsistance of life. Crabiltia orbits around a bright luminous star, predicted to live for billions of years to support life. Just like the sun, stars have a predicted lifespan based on their composition and most importantly the mass of the star. Large stars give off more luminosity which in turn shortens their lifespan, the star surrounding Crabiltia is right on point to provide enough energy to heat the planet to a significant temperature for water and life but not too much that it will die "quickly". 
With a mass like that of the Earth, Crabiltia is predicted to have similar gasses and mimic the greenhouse effect strength of the earth giving the organism oxygen, nitrogen. CO2, methane, hydrogen, and of course water vapor! 
All of the data supports life on Crabiltia! What do you think we will find when we visit? </string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We have found a Habitable World outside of Earth! Her name is Issai. She is  83.6 light years away, that's 5.87849981x10^12 miles. The tempurature on Issai is a chilly 55 degrees fahrenheit. It will be cold but livable. This planet was found when a student was searching through hundreds of stars. This one was found within the Main Sequence with the right tempurature and just the right amount of surface pressure and greenhouse effect. The biosignatures to look for on this planet are CO2, N20, CH4 and H20. You can H20 in liquid form on the planet!! The planet has a host star of it's own and a very long projected lifetime of 1.2 trillion years. Help us welcome this new planet into the Habitable Club. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My team and I have discovered a habitable planet! We started our search by examining the stars and figuring out which, if any, had exoplanets. Many stars have orbiting planets, but whether these planets are habitable or not is where things get tricky. The star hosting the planet we just discovered has a luminosity of .639. The luminosity of the star is the TOTAL amount of energy emitted. Earth's host star, the Sun, has a luminosity of 1. Based on this information we know that this host star gives off about 36% less energy than our sun. Since it took Earth 4.6 billion years to generate intelligent life, it's important we look for a star that is just as old. The host star we found has a projected life of 13 billion years. This is similar enough to our Sun. The relative ratio of the new planet's characetrists, relative to Earth, are all approximately 1.5 times larger. The effective temperature is 183 Kelvin. However, the greenhouse gass effect adds 100 Kelvin. Therefore, the surface temperature of the new planet is 283 Kelvin. The Earth's surface temperature is 287 Kelvin. The planet doesn't currently have H20, but it may have in the past. I would look for any signs of unicellular or multicellular life. I would examine rocks for fossils. Depending on what the atmosphere is made of, certain biosignatures may or may not be detectable. </string>
    </entry>

      <string>In order for a planet to be habitable, it has to be dense enough to support life. If a planet is dense enough, and a terestial planet instead of a water/ice planet, it is habitable. For a planet to habitable, it also has to have some sort of greenhouse effect. When there is a greenhouse effect, the planet traps gases that it emitts and that helps it stay at a temperature that can support life. The surface temperature and pressure of a planet determine if it is habitable or not too. If your planet's star is a man sequence, and the planet is dense enoiugh, then there is a decent chance it will be habitable.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My star-planet system called Andaidraia is roughly 368 trillion miles in distance compared to 5 trillion miles in distance from Earth to the Sun. The average home using roughly 6500 watts of energy, in contrast, Andaidraia's hot star emits roughly 631 watts per square meter. Andaidraia's density is 3.586 g/cm3 which is the amount of matter inside an object. It is close to Mars's density of 3.94 g/cm3 and the Earth is 5.51 g/cm3. In other words, the earth has more stuff inside of it like rock or iron that weighs more than both Andaidraia and Mars. The proposed surface pressure on Andaidraia, which is pressure caused by the weight of air in an atmosphere which affects the temperature excluding greenhouse gases is roughly 231 Kelvins or -43.87 degrees Fahrenheit. If we include greenhouse gases which is the absorption of invisible radiant energy from geological and biological forces like carbon dioxide, raises the planet's temperature. The surface temperature would then be roughly 53 degrees Fahrenheit. On Earth, the average surface temperature is 52.7 degrees Fahrenheit. Therefore, Andaidraia is pretty darn close in comfortable temperature for humans. On planet Andaidraia, you may find lifeforms consisting of fungi, plants, and possibly animals due to existing elements that contain organisms that can metabolize, reproduce, and adapt. These life essential elements include hydrogen, carbon, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorus and sulfur just like the Earth. Which in turn is absorbing light energy from the host star. Andaidraia's hot star emits (this about of energy) on the planet allowing for lifeforms.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>New Habitable Planet discovered!

It has been recently been discovered that a star Named Alganja is host to a Planet that possesses the necessary characteristics to host life! This Planet has an Effective temperature of 247.46 Kelvin, this is just 7.55 Kelvin cooler than earth! Don’t worry people if that sounds cold it is before each planets the Greenhouse Effect. 

This possible Colonies truly lives in a land of giants with a star that is close to six times more luminous than the sum (that’s the actual brightness not the brightness relative to the viewer if you don’t already know).  The Planet itself has twice the radius and about 4.5 times the mass of the earth. So it will probably take way longer for us to screw this one up.  It has about 20 atmospheres of pressure but hey at least you won’t need to bring your basement gym on the ship! Also she has a beauty of an atmosphere which comes in handy making sure you stay warm and don’t get fried by solar wind and what not. You would almost think this thing would  come with power windows and cruse control. 

Why Pack up and go?! Well liquid water for one and with it being 105.2 light-years away better to start the journey sooner than later.  I know this sounds like a bit of a haul but when you consider the closest star to us Proxima Centauri is 4.24 light-years it gives you a respect for the fact that we found such a premo planet within 20 times the distance.  Just remember that time is Relative! 

The ball is on your court explorers 

</string>
    </entry>

      <string>My best candidate for the Habitable worlds is Aquillix, being 83.6 light years away it wouldnt be impossible to relocate there if need be.     <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>One of the best planets I found to be habitable was orbitting the star Drezaira (I want to point out, I must have accidentally chosen this one over my best one, because the best one's surface temperature was much closer to Earth's and had a lot of feature's closer to Earth's). When I first noticed there is a planet orbitting this not very luminous star, I didn't think that it would have a good chance, let alone any chance of being habitable. Since the star's luminosity provides energy which warms the planet (like how our sun warms our Earth), and Drezaira isn't very luminous, I figured if there was a planet, it would be icy cold. But I found out that it does have a planet relatively close to it at about .219 AU for it's orbital radius. The Earth's orbital radius to the sun, or  how close it is located to the sun, is equal to 1 AU, so much further away. It also is larger than the Earth, yet less dense. The Earth has a density of about 5 grams per centimeters cubed, making it a mixture of rocky and metal material. While Drezaira's planet's density is about 3, it is just enough to be a rocky planet and not ice. It's atmospheric pressure on it's surface is a lot less than Earth, but has a strong greenhouse effect. It's atmosphere is made up of many atmospheric gasses and specifically Ammonia, CO2, Methane, Nitrous Oxide, Hydrogen Sulfate, and O3 (Ozone). These alone hold in the star's rays, which warms up the planet. And even though there isn't water present yet, these gasses alone can be sustainable, making it's planet habitable.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>	With the help of my collaborators, I was able to find five habitable planets. The best candidate for a habitable planet for humans would be a in the Doniven system. Traveling there may not occur any time soon, as Doniven is 18 light years away. Doniven is similar to Earth’s sun – it has approximately 90% of our sun’s radius and mass, with 70% of our sun’s luminosity. The planet that orbits Doniven is 20% further than the Earth is from its sun. As a result, the orbit is longer. The temperature on this planet is slightly cooler than Earth. The pressure is 13% more than what we have on Earth. A strong greenhouse effect is present on this planet as well. We could look for biosignatures of lifeforms that can utilize oxygen to survive.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The potentially habitable planet that was detected in the Gerrokoz star system is a location in the universe that will pique interests for possible alien life. The Gerrokoz star is much smaller than our Sun. The Gerrokoz star is approximately 40% the size, a little less than 50% of the radius and about 4% of the radiated energy of the Sun. However, Gerrokoz star will live approximately 10 times longer than the Sun. The planet that orbits the Gerrokoz star does so in about 60 days. Compared to the Earth's orbit around the Sun, it is much closer. In actuality, the planet is 78% closer to the Gerrokoz star than the Earth is to the Sun. Therefore, with the less amount of energy that radiates from the Gerrokoz star, the planet is in an ideal location for the possibility of alien life. The mass of this Earth like planet is 5 times that of Earth and the radius is a little more than two times that of the Earth's radius which makes it ideal to maintain an atmosphere and achieve balance. Gravity is about 20% greater than gravity on Earth. There a number of trace gases on the planet that could be the result of metobolic waste from the organisms on the planet. The trace gases present are that of methane,  ammonia, carbon dioxide, hydrogen sulfide, nitrogen dioxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone. These gases are also present on Earth and had previously dominated the Earth's atmosphere in its anoxic state during the Archean era approximately 2.4 to 4 billion years ago. We have detected Earth's life cycle in this particular planet. The surface temperature and the greenhouse effect with the atmospheric pressure allow for liquid water to exist on the surface of this planet. Further study of the atmosphere will determine the origin of the gases as biosignatures of alien life. Because of the planet's similarities to Earth, we believe that simple organisms will metabolize to and contribute to the evolution of the planet's atmosphere making it more and more Earth like. The study will look for biosignatures such as methane which is a direct result of methanogenisis or serpentinization as organisms metabolize hydrogen and carbon dioxide. After such time, we will try to determine the existence of more complex organisms that produce oxygen as waste. This is definitely an exciting time for science. We are just scratching the surface of detecting alien life. We believe there may be other life forms than ourselves.  </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Today, I have found a possible habitable world in our galaxy. We are calling it Dias, and it is 4.4 light years away from us. As it name implies, that is the number of years it would take if we could travel there in a craft that could travel at the speed of light. Otherwise, at current record interstellar craft speeds, it would take Voyager 1 approximately 77,512.8 years to get there.

Its "sun", or host star, is a Main Sequence star, wherein that we can predict its properties because it is not an outlier. If you took the distance between the Earth and the Sun, and used that as "1 AU" on a scale of orbital distance, this planet is extremely close to its star. It is even closer than Mercury to our Sun, at a distance of 0.22 AU. The reason why it still can be considered habitable is because its star is much less luminous than our own. Luminosity is the amount of energy emitted by a star; if we take our Sun to be "1 Ls", this star is 0.0338 Ls, or almost 0 comparatively. This star, we assume, will continue to exist for another 1.123e11 years.

Dias itself is close to Earth-like. Its mass and radius are one Earth plus some extra at 1.399 Earth Masses (ME) and 1.3004 Earth Radiuses (RE). Dias's mass indicates it is a primarily rocky planet at 3.509 g/cm^3. On the surface, we estimate the pressure to be 1.55 atmospheres (based upon Earth's atmosphere putting a pressure of 1 atmosphere unit upon us.) Its effective surface temperature is 249.55 Kelvin, or -23.6 degrees Celcius/-10.48 degrees Fahrenheit. However, with its strong greenhouse effect, its true surface temperature may be around 349.55 Kelvin, which is 76.4 degrees Celcius/169.52 degrees Fahrenheit, putting it within the range for having liquid water on its surface.

We have found water in its atmosphere, just like we have in our own. They also have methane and oxygen in their atmosphere. Whether these gasses are byproducts of an abiotic process or of a biological source, I do not know yet. These are gasses required for the processes of life, and are considered to be called biosignatures. If we can find evidence that these were caused by a non-geologic process, then they would be proclaimed positive biosignature and be considered as a viable habitat for intelligent life.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Ladies, gentlemen, and all other individuals, the rumors circulating around the field that a potential “habitable world” has been found are completely true.  We have found a planet out in our universe, only four and a half light years away, that may just support life!  (pause for applause)  “How do we know?”, you may ask.  Well, it’s simple.  Our calculations estimate that any water on the surface of said planet is liquid at the planet’s natural temperature.  This has the potential to mean rivers, lakes, or even oceans.  Which means there is a potential for life!  (pause for cheering)

At first glance, this may seem impossible.  The star this planet orbits, Aryssa, has only 3% of the energy and light of our own Sun, and most of that is in infrared light.  So how does the planet compensate for that drop in light and heat?  First of all, it orbits closer, with only 1/5 of the distance from its host star as the Earth is from our own Sun.  That certainly helps, but how does it retain that heat?  After all, Mercury is close to the Sun, yet it’s barren.  Well, this planet has in abundance what Mercury lacks entirely: a viable atmosphere and a strong greenhouse effect, with an atmospheric pressure about 1.5 times that of the Earth.  (pause for thoughtful nodding)  For those of you unaware, that means that very little of the heat this planet generates escapes out into the cold blackness of space, never to return.  This process can mean a potential temperature increase of 100 degrees Kelvin!  (pause for confused mumbling)  That’s about 100 degrees Celsius, or 180 degrees Fahrenheit for you Americans out there.  A big difference, the difference between liquid water and stone-cold ice.  (ohhhh)

The next step is to look for biosignatures, our first evidence of life!  (continue right on through cheering, we’re getting sick of pausing for every little thing)  At such a distance and through such a thick atmosphere with such an abundance of greenhouse gases, it may be difficult at first glance to determine who’s breathing what down there.  We as a scientific community suggest increasing funding for our space program (we’ve been suggesting that for a long time) and sending rovers to the surface of this planet to investigate the levels of oxygen, methane, nitrogen, and carbon in the air to find out what organisms might be having an effect on these levels, as well as search out signs of liquid water on the rocky surface.  The best way to peer through the thick atmosphere is to pierce it straight through!  Or, well, it certainly seems like the most exciting way to go about it.

This rock-and-metal planet is just slightly bigger than Earth, at 1.3 times the radius and 1.4 times the mass of our own home planet.  We have discovered a variety of facts about this potential habitable world, all that is left for you as citizens to do is help us name it!  Feel free to submit your naming ideas to the HabLabs Space Program, addressed to HAL INFINITY, our future overlord.  Note: names such as “Zoosmell Pooplord” will not be tolerated, and will lead to quick and painless execution.  Thank you!  (bow and leave stage amidst wild celebratory eruption) </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Today’s discovery of a potential vacation spot across the universe is exciting news for the scientists of SES 106 at Arizona State University! But don’t pack your bags just yet. Enzadid is over 62 light years away (so you probably won’t be able to use your airline miles). What is exciting is that this planet has the potential to host life. The conditions are very different from Earth, but there is the possibility that Enzadid has water on the surface. Given that we can’t see it from here, we will have to trust the science. Based on what the scientist could see, they have figured out that this planet is orbiting a much smaller Sun than our own…only about 2% of the amount of energy given off by our Sun. The planet itself is larger than Earth (about one and half times larger) and orbits much closer to its Sun than we do. It is even closer to its energy source than Mercury is to ours! With such a small energy source, the planet is naturally very cold (approximately -46 degrees Fahrenheit), but there is something at work that warms up the surface of the planet enough to keep the water from freezing. Greenhouse gases in the atmosphere are to thank for this sauna effect! We hear a lot about the negative effects of greenhouse gases from the media, but did you know that Earth would be frozen if not for our atmosphere saving some of our energy for us. So, if Enzadid has a similar atmosphere and water, could we find life soon? The scientists of SES 106 will continue to look for ordered biological constructs and also for disordered biological waste products. As molecules are destroyed by ultraviolet light, energy and new compounds are formed. It seems that any place where there is a source of energy and simple compounds, complex organic molecules can emerge. If given the right conditions and enough time, we could discover a very similar planet to Earth. Scientists are trying to solve all of the variables needed for us to meet those universal neighbors. Maybe whoever lives there is already on the way to Tempe for an extended vacation.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Dekeegwyn is a star over 40 trillion kilometers from Earth, which actually isn't very far away, relatively. It is only about 3 percent as luminous as our own sun and it's estimated to have a lifetime of around 100 billion years. The potentially habitable planet that orbits it is about 20 percent closer to its sun than Earth is. It's also about 30% bigger than earth, but is only about 2 thirds of the density. It has about 50% more pressure than Earth and its effective temperature is within 10 degrees Celsius of Earth's, and since like Earth, it has a strong greenhouse effect, it should have actual surface temperatures close to that of Earth. On Dekeegwyn's planet, I would look for biosignature gases such as methane, carbon, dioxide, ozone, and water vapor, which would be detectable if there was enough life on the planet at some point to produce a detectable amount of any of them, because biosignature gases are what is left after the metabolic process of some type of life.</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I have discovered a habitable planet it our universe that, although is 4.4 light years away, is very similar to our planet Earth. The effective temperature of Kanoba is at 250 K, just a 4 degree different from Earth's 254. Kanoba's combination of temperature at atsompheric pressure of 1.55 atm create a liquid state of water on the planet making capable of hosting life. Both have a strong Greenhouse Effect which means both planets' atmospheres absorb a lot of greenhouse gasses, thus increasing their temperatures. Kanoba is much closer to it's host star and bigger than Earth. Konoba 40% larger in mass and 30% larger in radius compared to Earth. Konoba is less dense than Earth which probably means it contains less metalic properties. The Biosignatures of planets are key to being habitable. The right amount of gases such as methan, carbon dioxide, ozone, and water are necessary to being a habitable planet. These gases stimulate activies like volcanism, methane and oxygen sinks which help sustain an atmosphere capabel to hosting a civilization. </string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I am proud to announce that  the John Watkins Research Group has found another habitable world. The planet , Jent, is about 93.2 light years away. For those of you who do not know, one light year is equivalent to 5.88 trillion miles. The planet is about five times larger than planet Earth however it is less dense. The trace gasses we were looking for are H2o, ch4, co2, h2s, n20, nh3, and o3. Based on the results of our testing we decided that this planet had a strong greenhouse effect becausde of all of the biosignatures present. These particular gasses are only present at the same time when temperature and pressure are within a certain limit. The abundance of biosignatures we received from this planet show us that it is indeed habitable. There is other life out there people!  </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The habitable planet was detected orbiting the host star, Arli. Arli's distance from Earth is approximately 62.7 light years away. 
The luminsoty of a star is the total amount of energy it is emitting. Arli gives off a luminosity of 0.025365192 Ls. This number is a measurement of the wattage being emitted by the sun. Our sun gives off exactly 1 Ls. In comparison, Arli is not as luminous as our sun, but it still maintains the characteristics needed for life. Arli's projected lifetime is a staggering 138 billion years.  In comparison, our Sun is only 4.5 billion years old. 
The habitable planet orbiting  Arli has a radius of approximately .230 astronomical units. The distance from Earth to the Sun is 1 astronomical unit, or about 149,597,871 kilometers.  The distance between Arli and its habitable planet is roughly 1/5 the distance between Earth and the Sun, but this is accounted for by Arli's lower luminosity. 
The radius of Arli's habitable planet is approximately 1.50 Re. This measurement, "Re", is a comparison of the planet's radius to the radius of Earth. Arli's host planet, therefore, is approximately 1.5 times bigger than Earth. The mass of the host planet is approximately 2.2 Me. This measurement, "Me" is a comparison of the planet's mass to the mass of the Earth. In this instance, Arli's planet is 2.2 times more massive than the Earth. Arli's planet has a desnity of approximately 3.59 grams per centimeter squared. In scientific terms, this means that the planet is composed primarily of a rock type material, making the planet conducive to being habitable like our rocky planet Earth.
The proposed surface pressure of Arli's planet is 0.56 atm. This is a less heavy atmospheric pressuure than we currently experience on Earth, which sits at a comforable 1 atm. On Arli's planet, we would find even more ease in our every day movements due to less pressure.
The effective temperature of Arli's planet is 230.7 degrees Kelvin. This is about -44.51 degrees Fahrenheit, or -42.5 degrees Celsius. This may seem a bit chilly, but this does not accounts for the greenhouse effect caused by atmospheric gasses present on Arli's planet!  A greenhouse effect occurs thermal radiation is absorbed by atmopheric greenhouse gases, and is radiated in all directions. The greenhouse effect found on Arli's planet is strong, meaning that we can safely add 100 degrees Kelvin to the number. This brings our surface temperature to a toast 330.7 degrees Kelvin, or  57.55 degress Celsius. This is an incredible discovery, because all of these conditions make Arli's planet habitable. We would search for biosignatures on Arli's planet such as methane: while this is not the most significant indication of a biosignature, methane can be produced both biologically and geologically. We would also seek out the main sources conducive to life, including hydrothermal systems, such as deep sea vents; as well as the presence of plate tectonics. We would also seek out signs of oxygen, such as sedimentary rocks similar to places like Australias's marble bar. Any place that has a source of energy (IE, the sun)  and simple compounds, is capable of having complex organic molecules emerging.
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>When I was searching for a habitable world I would make sure it had a relatively high effective temperature so that when you add gasses the surface temperature will be a little higher and be able to hold liquid.  At first, I thought you needed to have water for a planet to be habitable but as I learned it is all about the surface temperature. You just need to find the correct biosignature's in order to have life. The biosignature in our case is an element but it can also be other substances such as an, isotope, molecule, or somthing else. The biosignature provides scientific evidence of past or present life.  I was looking for a habitable world with a star and planet silimar to our sun and earth but I realized that a habitable world doesnt need to follow those qualifications. One thing it has to have is a strong greenhouse effect. It allows the planet to become warmer in order to support life. the dictionary definition of greenhouse effet reads " it is a process by which thermal radiation from a planetary surface is absorbed by atmospheric greenhouse gases, and is re-radiated in all directions. This is very important because without it the planet will be to hot or way to cold.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We have found a star system, Derdi, which about 9.13 light years away  that has a terrestrial planet that is a good candidate for harboring life. This star is almost 24 times more luminous than our sun and is projected to shine for another 1.04 billion years. In that stars planetary system there is a terrestrial planet that shows it is possible to contain life. Its surface temperature is projected to be about 312.7 degrees kelvin, which is around 103.1 degrees farenheit. This is a good sign for finding liquid water at the surface which can survive in a liquid state between the temperatures of about 273 to 373 Kelvin. This planet also contains a similar atmosphere to earth with gasses such as methane, carbon dioxide, ozone, ammonia, and nitrogen dioxide. These gasses create a similar greenhouse effect like the one we have on our planet and warm up the planet. These gasses are also a great sign for possibe biosignatures. Biosignatures are one way  that we are able to find out if there is possibly life on another planet. For example methane, nitrous oxide, and ammonia are produced on Earth mainly by bacteria. These same gasses were found on our planet in the Derdi system. This could be a sign that bacteria are present on this planet, which is a sign of life. However, there is also ozone in this system which on Earth is produced by photosynthetic life which shows that there is also a possibility of photosynthetic life on this planet, There is also a sign of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, this suggests that there also might be organic life as carbon dioxide is a waste that we produce. We can not know for sure whether these assumptions are accurate but we can hypothesize that there is a possibility of life on this planet. Conditions that these biosignatures would be detectable would have to a planet similar to our own planet.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I have narrowed the search down to the best choices for a habitable world, and the planet orbits the star known as Hornorard, we found this star at nearly 63 light years from here meaning traveling at the speed of light would take that long to make the trip. This planet is more than twice as "heavy" as earth, and 1 and a half times as wide, orbiting its sun 1/5th of the distance that we orbit ours. Don't be alarmed at the close distance though, the energy output of this star  is far smaller than our sun so this planet is at a good location for temperature. The intiial temperature was recorded at 230 K, but traces of greenhouse gass elements on the planet that increase overall temperature were detected, these include CO2, Nitrogen, Methane, and even liquid water. This planet will actually have a far warmer average temperature than our own, but as with any planet there will be areas of more mild temperatures and even fairly cold. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>When looking for a habitable world I would try to find wavelengths that closely matched our sun.  I would also make sure that if the luminosity was high that the planet would be a reasonable distance from the star.  This one did not match that and I accidentally stumbled upon this star.  The reason it worked out great is that the surface pressure was so high that the water would stray from being a gas.  Another thing I learned from class is that alot of the biosignatures in our atmosphere changed and lessened over time and now our biggest greenhouse gasses our CO2 and H2O. The reason I marked it habitable is that I could see alot of parallels in gas signatures that our planet shares with Issendrath.  Yes it may be close but if my memory serves well this was a red star and not a cyan star like our planet is so its luminosity does not play as big of a part as if our sun was that high in luminosity.  Seeing a large number of gases and the fact that water could be present on this planet are what give me hope that this planet could be potentially habitable.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Arsirryk is approximately 83.6 light years away. Light years is measured in the speed travels in a year which is approximately 300,000,000m/s. The distance is calulated by dividing 3.26 (ly)/ by the parralax angle. The parralax is the angle that is observed as we are moving, thus the light that we recieve from the star that Arsirryk is orbiting is likewise moving. 

The Star it orbits is not as luminous as our own star as it is 3.08% as  luminous as ours. However it orbits at a much closer rate than we do to our own star the sun. Arsirryk orbits at a distance that is about 1/5 of ours or more precisely .1908 astronomical units (AU). AU is the measurement used that derives from our distance relative to the sun. The projected lifetime is the amount of time it will take for the star to use up its fuel, starting from Hydrogen and condensing it in its core to produce heavier elements to the point where it cant any longer. At that point it will become a white dwarf becuase of its smaller size. 

As the planet is not as luminous, Arsirryk is able to stay at its closer orbit and still remain in the area where habitability is possible. This is known as when the planet orbits in front of the star (relative to us) the light spectra observed is marked by the chemicals that are in the planets atmosphere.  

We can calculate the mass of the planet by calculating the distance from the star and the stars mass and velocity. We calculate the radius by taking into account the stars radius and the % of light that is blocked off when the planet passes in front. With both the radius and the mass, we can then figure out that the density of Arsirryk is 4.79, which puts it into the terrestrial classification. 

Including the chemicals of CH4, CO2 N20, NH3, H2S, O3 that are present on the planet and the effective temperature we are able to calculate that the planet is in or close enough to the habitable zone that with the addition of temperature (green house) by the chimicals, any water possibly present in the planet would exist is liquid form. 
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Idaromorn, is a star that is 4.4 light years away from us, which is the same distance that the star Alpha Centauri is from the Earth. Idaromorn is only 3% as bright as the sun, but is going to last 100 times as long as the sun, which means life is going to have a very long time to form. Idaromorn has a terrestrial planet that is 80% closer than the Earth is to the Sun, which makes up for Idaromorn not being that luminous. The planet is a little more massive and a little wider than the Earth, and it has a little stronger atmosphere than the Earth. I was able to study the light waves that were emitted from the star and reflected back off the planet and based off of which light waves were blocked be able to tell what gasses were in the atmosphere. The goal was to make sure that the planet had both CO2 and H2O in the atmosphere because we know that we need those two gasses to survive. I was also looking for a planet with a strong greenhouse gas effect. When a planet has both CO2 and H2O it is able to regulate its temperature more efficiently and effectively, through processes like weathering, evaporation, volcanism, etc.  </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The planet that we have found, Argargash, is something quite similar to the world that we currently live on. The star that this planet revolves around is about 20% brighter than our sun and is nearly twice as old. Now we are also almost twice as far from this star as the Earth is from the sun. That probably makes you wonder how this planet could possibly be habitable if we're that far away from the star that gives us heat. Argargash has a very dense atmosphere that would allow the heat to be trapped more efficiently than it is here on Earth, therefore retaining the heat from the star better than Earth retains the heat from the sun. 

Now that we have found the planet, we will begin looking for biosignatures on the surface of the planet. Now if we were 140 light years away from our current location and looking back on ourselves, what would be be looking for in terms of biosignatures? Liquid water is the first thing that we would look for because we know that's what we need to survive on a planet such as this, so we can start there. Assuming intelligent life would have evolved on a similar timeline, we could look for man-made structures orbiting the planet much like our satellites. 

We have sincere faith that this could be a large step forward in finding civilization outside of our own solar system. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>While on a search for a habitable planet besides our own planet Earth, we have concluded our search and found one with success! The best candidate for a planet for all to live on is Aranda, being around 62.7 light years away!  Comparing Arandas host star to the sun, the brightness and distance is comparable to what we see here on Earth! Its host star is also projected to last just under one TRILLION years- giving us the light and energy we need on our new planet. While searching for this beautiful new home, we researched the biosignatures given off by the planet and its atmosphere. There are certain gasses within the planets atmosphere that are crucial to our survival on Aranda and we have discovered just that. After all, without the presence of liquid water, what kind of life could we live?! </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We have found a habitable planet. I planet were it can sustain life or life is already in progress. This means that we are no longer alone in the solar system. The planet's name is llkos located 18 light years away. Like Earth and the Sun, it also has a host star. Its luminosity is lower than our sun, but it is strong enough for a planet with life to form. The host star is also no very old, so there will be plenty of time for this planet to develop, making it possible for us to call it home as well in the future. The planets mass, radius, and density also make it perfect for life. Compared to Earth the distance to star, mass, radius and density are very similar.  However, Ilkos is farther than earth to the sun and also is bigger in mass, radius, and density. With this new planets surface pressure and effective temperature liquid water will be abundent. The greenhouse effect is very strong, meaning that this planets atmostphere has the necessary gases to sustain life, such as water, carbon, and oxygen. This is a very exciting discovery that may be once in a lifetime. I hope this allows us to expore and discover more in our solar system. My hope for Ilkos is that it will soon become our home away from home. </string>

      <string>After much time and calcuation new habiatable star-planet systen has been found. It is 14.4 light years away and its name is Derifanos. The planet is about 6 times larger than Earth.     <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My planet, Enzortrak, has a brightness drop and brightness drop days, which is where I start when I want to determine if a planet is habitable. Once I know that my host star has a planet, I move on to determine its lifetime and luminosity. If its lifetime (6.36E11 years) and luminosity (0.003 Ls) fall within the main sequence category, then it means that my planet could be habitable. After that, I move on to check my star's density. It's density is 3.08 which means it is neither a water or a gas planet (which are both inhabitable), it is terrestrial; just what we want. I proceed to check on its effective temperature and greenhouse effect. My greenhouse effect for Enzortrak is strong which means it adds 100k to my effective temperature (208.84k + 100k) which boosts the surface temperature to 308.84k. 308.84k is in the 273k-373k range which means the water phase is liquid. All of these characteristics combined tell us that my host star is in fact a habitable planet. 

The biosignatures I would look for on my planet are the molecules that, when they react together, give off waste products with virtually similar energy as that of water vapor. In other words, my planet does not necessarily have to have water vapor for it to be habitable, it just needs the right molecules to react together and give off similar energy as that of water vapor. On the same note, the absence of methane is not necessarily a sign that there is no life on a planet. Likewise, the presence of methane also doesn't mean that there is life. The habitability of a planet depends on various aspect of its host star; brightness drop, brightness drop days, luminosity, projected lifetime, density, surface temperature, water phase, etc.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The most important aspect of my habitable world is brightness drop and the brightness drop period, if both are 0 then there's no planet. If they are not then there is a planet and the density would determine if it is a tetestrial, ice/water giant or a gas giant. The planet is tetesrial with an above 3 g/cm^3. Between 3 and 8 g/cm^3 it is rock, anything with a g/cm^3 above 8 it is metal, both material densities are capable of being habitable. After that we look at the effective temperature the temperature and the green house effect, in this case the green house effect is strong meaning the surface temperature is going to go up 100+ K which makes the surface temperature 278 K which is effective for holding liquid. Important to note the temperature needs to be anywhere from 273 K to 373 K in order for liquid to be present, anything below 273 k  is in the ice water phase and anything above 373 k is in the gas phase, far too hot to be habitable.  Also important to note that the star needs to be in the main sequence in order to be habitable. About biosignature, the planet doesn't necessarily have to have water vapor in order to be habitable; some molecules when they react together can give off waste products with similar energy to that of water. I believe my planet had CO2 and methane, among other gasses. Although we know that methane absence may not be a sign that the planet isn't habitable, just like methane presence doesn't mean biosignature, it all comes down to how the greenhouse gasses act together to create an atmosphere that sustains life.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Greetings, fellow explorers! I am delighted to announce that I have discovered a star-planet system that is very much alike to ours. The star "Aranda" lies 37.5 light years away. It has a luminosity very alike to our sun - comparably, Aranda is 0.867 Ls, while our sun is considered to be 1 Ls. The lifetime of this sun is estimated to be over 11 billion years. Additionally, the detected planet is about twice the length of Earth and slightly less dense. While earth is about 5.5 grams per cubic centimeter, this planet is 3.1. This merely states that its composition is slightly different than Earth's. One of the most crucial factors about this planet is its effective temperature. It averages to be about 318 Kelvin (or 112 degrees Fahrenheit) while our Earth is currently 287 Kelvin (or 57 degrees Fahrenheit). Although this may seem to be a bit hot, it is an average of the entire planet and therefore there are less hot, more habitable areas of the planet. As far as the composition of its atmosphere, this planet contains all of the necessary gasses that we have on Earth. Before inhabiting a planet, however, we must find its biosignatures first. These are any type of gas that is produced as a waste product by any kind of metabolism, and are evidence of life forms. Methane gas is a prime example of a biosignature. It is one of the earliest metabolisms to have evolved on Earth. However; the presence or absence of methane in an atmosphere can also have non-biological explanations. Methane can be created through the metamorphic process "serpantization" and diminished through UV light processes. Another type of biosignature is the rock formation of "stromatolites," which are produced by microbes in shallow water. Rocks can also show evidence of oxygenic photosynthesis, which means that cyanobacteria once lived on the planet. Although there is much exploring of this planet to be done before we can be 100% sure it is safe for human life, I strongly believe that it is a reasonable candidate for a new human world.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I am pleased to announce that I have discovered a possibly habitable world - a world 4.4 lightyears away named Kanivermyr. How amazing is the possibility of life on another planet? Here are some interesting facts about this newly discovered planet:

- The projected lifetime for the star (a.k.a. "sun") that this planet orbits around is just over 112 billion years. To give a bit of a perspective, our sun is estimated to be around 4.5 billion years old, and will die in another 5.5 billion years. 
- The star this planet orbits around is also projected to have a luminosity (or brightness) of just under 13 septillion Watts.
- Kanivermyr orbits about 20.4 million miles away from it's "sun."
- Kanivermyr is about a third larger in it's radius than Earth is, has just over a third more mass than Earth, and is less dense than Earth by about 2 g/cm^3.
- The atmosphere pressure of Kanivermyr is about 1.5 times that of Earth's atmosphere, it has a slightly cooler average temperature compared to Earth, and it has a strong greenhouse effect - this allows the planet to trap some of it's star's warmth in it's lower atmosphere.

Some Biosignatures I looked for when determining whether or not this planet was habitable were gasses like methane and carbon dioxide, an ozone layer, water (H2O), and other elements necessary to life that may be found here on Earth.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>A new star with a planet that has the necessary characteristics to support life has been found! After extensive searching through space, and many stars that did not have suitable planets, we have found a planet with great potential for life. This planet is a little less than twice the size of earth, though it has many similar characteristics. It is a bit farther away from its star than the Earth is from the sun, but it has a thick atmosphere to make up for this difference. The atmosphere acts as a trap for all of the energy coming from the sun, warming up the planet to levels appropriate for life as we know it. This planet has liquid water on it, and is composed very similarly to Earth. This star and planet are located about 31 light years away from Earth; a light year being the measure of distance light travels in one year. We are all very excited to see what kind of life this earthlike planet may contain!</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Recently, a planet named Hangollyn has been discovered that has the capability to sustain life.  At 4.4 light years away, it would take the average car travelling at 85 miles per hour 34,737,307.55 years to travel there. The luminosity, or amount of energy emitted, of this planet's host star, is less than that of our own Sun.  For comparison purposes, our Sun's luminosity is 1.  This new host star's luminosity is about 0.03.  This is quite a difference.  This star is projected to last around 112 billion years. However this does not mean Hangollyn will be habitable throughout the star's entire lifespan.  This planet resides 0.22 Astronomical Units from its star.  This is equal to 20.4 million miles.  This planet's mass and radius are only slightly bigger than Earth's.  Where Earth's mass and a radius is equal to 1ME, Hangollyn's mass is 1.4ME and radius is 1.3ME.  The density composition, however, is about 56% of Earth's density.  Compared to Earth's who's surface pressure is equal to 1atm, Hangollyn's pressure is at about 1.55, leaving its effective temperature around 249.4K, or -11.47 degrees Fahrenheit, but because of its strong greenhouse effect, the average surface temperature of Hangollyn rises to a habitable temperature.  Hangollyn is the next best candidate, next to Earth, to sustain life as we know it.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Ara'in is a star system about 93 light years from our own. It's sun is only about 4% as hot as our own is which is good because the planet which I have discovered is very close to its star and is twice the size of Earth. The density of this planet suggests that there is land made of rock to be found there. The atmosphere is only a little more than 10% of our own planet, but this allows for liquid water to form on the planet as it is cooler than Earth. 

I would first start to look for biosignatures in the water. With an atmosphere this light and a very strong greenhouse effect I would not expect to find a planet very similar to what we are familiar with on Earth. But since we are using the presence of liquid water as the basis for habitabilty we should begin by looking there. </string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We May Not Be Alone! Habitable World Found So Far Away, We Will Pobably Never Meet Inhabitants! 

This new world, founded by the ever brilliant and amazing Kayla Brownlee, is kinda sorta similar to our own. Even tough Arli is tremendously far away, so far it would even take Thor forever to get there, the planet is still worth noting. Arli has a smaller orbital radius than Earth. This means that Arli orbits its sun much quicker than Earth. Arli has a smaller mass, radius, and density than Earth. So basically, Arli is the Victoria'sSecret model of the galaxy with it's lean weight and size while Earth is Gerry Gergich, fat, ugly, and farts a lot. With a higher surface temperature than Earth,  Arli is not not a planet for those who love to spend their time frolicking in the snow making grotesque looking snow angels. No, Arli is a planet where people who would rather bask in the sunshine and overheat would feel at home. Pale gingers beware, I'm looking at you Prince Harry!     <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>When I was looking through my star selections to find a habitable world, I tried to filter through my possibilities to find systems that somewhat resembled our planet and relationship to our sun. The most important characteristics I looked for were density to determine if the planet was terrestrial, and once I found those I checked for effective temperature. I knew that if I had a potential planet with an effective temperature of around 250K and above, the addition of enough greenhouse gas would give me the right temp for a habitable world. This process helped me find my habitable world fairly quickly. H2O was the greenhouse gas that seemed to give me the best chance at having a habitable world with liquid water. While the planet I found is smaller than earth, the density is very close, and it's star is fairly similar to our sun. So overall I would say that my process worked out very well.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The planet I have discovered is named Junnaenda, and I suggest to everyone to start associating this name with hope because once we destroy the planet this is most likely our new home-should we find a way to get there in a timely fashion. Junnaenda is 4.4 light years away; this basically means that at the current technology we are limited to, we have no chance of getting there, and even if we somehow managed to fit enough resources for the trip you and several generations down would live and die in your metal spaceship home before we even got close. Fortunately the planet is going to be around for roughly 112 billion years, so as long as we kept our journey underneath that lifespan we should be good. The surface temperature, thanks to its atmosphere and greenhouse effect, is able to sustain liquid water. Theoretically we would run into a similar situation to what we have here on Earth-decent temperatures, water, and an atmosphere looking out for us keeping the host star's harmful rays at bay. This planet will have more room than Earth seeing that it is slight bigger; let's try to share this extra space please. 

What I found was liquid water, which means this planet will operate in a similar way as Earth using the carbon cycle. This planet is most likely replicating what we have here, which means the carbon cycle is in effect. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Goril became my best habitalbe planet. This planet orbited a white dwarf star, which I found to be inteesting. The luminosity of the host star is intrinsic it does not change over time. It measures the total amount of energy emitted or put out by the star at any given time.  A stars luminosity falls between 0.00001 Ls and 100,000 Ls. Ls stands for luminosity. If the planet is to far it will recieve to little energy and be too cold, and if it is too close it will recieve too much energy and be to hot. Goril lies within the habitable zone, which is the area around the star where conditions are just right for an earthlike planet to be. The projected life time is the time the planet has till it is completely gone. The distance from the star is measured in astronomical units. the astronomical units dive us the orbital radius te distance the planet is as it rotates around the star. This the the measurement astrologists use. The further the planet is from the star the colder the planet becomes and the closer it is the hotter it becomes. The mass measures how much stuff the planet is made of.  Mass and luminosity share a relationship. The radius is the length of the line from the core or center of the planet to the perimetter of the planet. The density is the "weight" of the planet. This is used to determine if the planet is habitable. The density has to be over 3grams/cm3 for it to be habitable. A desser object will take up less volume. The denser object will be more massive. The atomic molecular masses are messured by the mass of the proton or neutron. This also depends on the temperature of the planet. Higher temperatures move molecules faster because they have more energy. The speed of the molecules depends on the temperature and the ability to escape depends on the speed of the molecule. The larger the object is the longer it holds the gases needed to sustain life. The effective temperature can be adjusted by adding the green house effect. By adding gasses the temperature of the planet can increase becuse the energy is now absorbed into the planet. The absorbtion retans the energy heating up the planet. All of these items had to be met before I could determine if the planet was habitable. This planet met all requirements of habability. Biosignatures are gasses that are produced as waste products by any kind of metabolism. Metabolism is the way molecules in gases interact with each other.  A methanogenisis metabolism was the first to evolve on earth. That would be one I looked for. The interaction of carbon is another biosignature I looked for. The most important is carbon and hydrogen interatction. Methanogens are mostly positive biosignatures. False positives are usuall methane geology and can mimic habitable biological explanations but have too many potential non-biological explanations. Alos, the ultra violet light they absorb can wipe out the signature. Methane is the waste product produced during these interactions. Signatures are generated biologically by methanogens. These are the signatures I looked for. They are found when there is a concentration of oxygen in the planets atmosphere which depends on its source of oxygen and its sinks. Sinks are photochemical destruction, aerobic respiration, reaction with volcanic gasses, and oxic weathering. Oxygen is only detectable when the sources are greater than the sinks. To balance this you would have to increase the source of oxygen or reduce the sinks for oxygen or both. All of this needs to occur to detect a biosignature.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>A planet has been identified 83.5 light years away. It was found orbiting Gilma'nai, a star smaller than Earths sun. The planet is approximately 1.6 times the size of Earth. The planet is composed of a combination of rock and metal. The atmosphere's greenhouse effect is strong enough to make the planet's temperature in the range for water to be found in a liquid state. The planet has the following trace gasses: methane, carbon dioxide, hydrogen sulfide, nitrous oxide, ammonia, and ozone. The presence of these gasses shows the potential of biological organisms such as bacteria, phytoplankton, and other organic materials which have the potential to evolve. The bio signatures sources on the planet exists however the sinks remain to be identified.
</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Of the 110 stars from the sample, 75 had planets. The types of planets found can be broken down as follows: 15 were gas giants, 25 were ice giants, and 35 were terrestrial. The surface temperatures of these terrestrial planets ranged from 12.59K to 832.9K (or roughly around -260C to 558C) with surface pressure ranging from 0.01atm to 63.4atm (1atm = atmospheric pressure on Earth). Of these 35 terrestrial planets only 4 had the right surface temperature and pressure to allow for liquid water. The composition of gasses found in these planets is as follows:

Two planets had 6 detected gasses:
CH4, CO2, N2O, NH3, H2S, O3

One had only O-Zone:
O3

And one planet, orbiting the star Arrkin (just a bit dimmer than our sun), had evidence for the gasses CH4, CO2, N2O, NH3, H2S, O3, and H2O (water vapor). 

Arrkin's planet, while having a highly favorable gas collection, is not similar to Earth in every way. The atmospheric pressure was high at 63 times that of earth's and the surface temperature was 418.1K close to 144C. Life found there would have to be able to withstand great pressure and intense heat. Although there is evidence of CH4 (Methane) in the atmosphere of this planet (which can be a biosignature for life), there are geological processes that also produce methane. However with the additional presence of water vapor in the atmosphere, there is still the possibility of life. 
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Almost 4.5 lightyears away lies a small red star with an orbiting planet capable of supporting life!
Enzadisha, the planet's sun, is much dimmer and smaller than our Sun. Since this star doesn't provide as much energy as our sun does to Earth, this planet orbits closer than Mercury does to our Sun. 
This planet is slightly larger than Earth, with a lower density, which implies the existence of less metal and more rock than Earth is made up of. 
Through observations of this system, we have determined the existence of an atmosphere a slightly heavier than Earth normal, with traces of methane, carbon dioxide, nitrogen, ozone, ammonia and, most exciting, water vapor. This thicker atmosphere full of these gases causes a strong greenhouse effect that produces surface temperatures of around 170 f. This may seem a little warm for us Earthlings, but is sure to mean a nice steamy home for many forms of life. 
The existence of ammonia and methane in the atmosphere of this planet, while not proof of life, is fortunate. Methane does occur naturally, but is often produced by living things here on Earth. If we can determine the existence of large amounts of oxygen in the atmosphere, it would be even more likely to be inhabited. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Our Best Candidate for a Habitable world is a planet off of the star Homorom. Traveling at the speed of light, it would take 37.5 years to reach our destination. It provides 87% as much energy to the habitable planet as our Sun with a projected lifetime of 11.3 billion years. The planet's distance from Homorom is similar to that of Mercury which is half the distance of the Earth to the Sun. It is 4 times the size of Earth and as dense as the Moon and the average rock on Earth. The effective temperature, which takes into account the strong greenhouse effect, is 318.6 K or 113.8 degrees farenheit (45.5 degrees Celsius). This temperature is comparable to what is experienced in Death Valley. Biosignatures that need to be investigated are gases that are produced as a waste product of metabolism such as oxygen, carbon, and hydrogen. Methane is also a biosignature of interest regardless of whether it is created biologically or geographically. These signatures can be measured and tracked through the con centrations in the atmosphere if the gases are present in significant amounts. Probes are another viable solution to take samples that would yield greater information on the planet's history and present state.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We have found a possible habitable world in the star system Aquashan. Aquashan has a slightly longer lifetime than our sun, so life on this planet will have plenty of time to evolve long before the star's death. Aquashan gives off half of our sun's energy, but it gives enough energy so that this planet has similiar temperatures to those of Earth, allowing for liquid water. Even though this planet is 50% farther out from its star than Earth is from the sun, it is 50% larger than Earth, so it is able to retain its heat longer. 

Within the next one hundred years, astrobiologists will seek out this new planet and look for signs of life, starting with oxygen. Observing this planet's geology will give tell-tale signs of oxygen. If the rocks found are red with iron, it shows that they have been oxidized and that is valid proof that the planet has oxygen in its atmopshere. The second clue will be its water. Since the planet's temperature allows for liquid water, it is very possible that there are lakes, rivers, and oceans present. A rich atmosphere and a sustainable temperature will produce the correct building blocks to creating a habitable world that will remind us of home. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The recently discovered planet, Bispeth, appears to be a great discovery amongst the HabLab University students. While it may appear to be just an ordinary planet, one student in particular believes it to be a potential habitable planet. Maureen Dorwin, the self-titled most amazing person in the world, discovered this planet while working on a project for her final project for her final semester at HabLab University. "It was an incredible experience," says Maureen. "I didn't think I would ever find a planet!" 

So what makes this planet habitable? First, Maureen assessed whether her star that the planet orbits was the perfect candidate for a habitable world. "Like, I just saw that it was about 3 times as luminous [bright] as our like, own sun and saw that the planet was in like, this habitable zone from the planet where it wouldn't be too hot or too cold," says Maureen. "It's dense enough that there wouldn't be too much gas or ice. Also, like, it models after our greenhouse effect, so like, the outgoing radiation from the planet is keeping it at the right temperature instead of keeping it really hot or cold." She then went on to explain how planets can have an effective temperature (the predicted temperature of a planet's surface that's calculated from the planet's distance, the host star's luminosity, and the planet albedo [absorbtion of light]) so hot without turning everything into lava or keeping it frozen. "A planet can have an effective temperature from 173 Kelvin to about 240 Kelvin and still be habitable. That's what makes this discovery so rad!"

So what is the future for planet Bispeth? Will we ever visit it in the near future? Maureen says she is highly doubtful. "1 Lightyear is super far away, and this planet is 14.4 lightyears away! Until we get a working Star Trek ship, we'll probably like, never see it."</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The host star Falcon, while lower in energy in comparison to the Sun, has a lifetime fairly equal to the Sun's. The planet that orbits this star is closer to the star than even our Mercury is to our Sun. While this may have some cause for concern in temperature, the low energy of the star provides much less heat to this planet, making the temperature of the planet low as well. In fact, the planet's temperature would be too cold to sustain liquid water, however, because of the greenhouse effect, in which gasses within the atmosphere retain energy emitted from the planet, the temperature of the planet is high enough to hold liquid water.  

With a sustainable temperature and a light atmosphere to retain this temperature, we could delve into biosignatures similiar to that of Earth's. Looking into the gasses most prominent in the atmosphere, we can determine some these biosignatures that create the probability of life on the planet. 

Our first step would be to look into traces of oxygen. With the right tools, we can examine the geology of the planet. The presence of red rocks reflects the process of iron becoming oxidized, providing evidence of oxygen. While we breath oxygen, the atom is an important component of what provides various forms of life, water. 

Detecting H2O, a gas molecule we understand based on our own experience on Earth, means a a high possibility for life. Examining the atmosphere, including the presence of clouds and precipitation, is a way in which we could detect the presence of water.

Methane would be worth looking into however the absence and presence of it is fairly ambigous in terms of its relationship to the presence of life.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>With an average surface temperature of 54 degrees fahrenheit Cedstlimo would be a very nice place to live.  Not a close place 5,349,348,300,000 miles away it would take about  534,954,924,253,600 years if we were traveling at 60 mph and even by space ship you would get there in your lifetime.  The of Cedstlimo is 1,022,119,402.28 years so compared to our sun at 11,000,000,000 it is dies pretty young.  The habitable world orbiting is 632,762,000 miles away from Cedstlimo which is a lot further away then we are from our sun which means that Cedstilmo is birghter and hotter then are sun which is why its lifetime is so much different then our own sun.  The planet is warm enough for liquid water which is a result of the greenhouse effects caused by the presence of Methane, Ozone, Carbon Dioxide, Nitrous Oxide, Hydrogen Sulfide and Ammonia in the atmosphere.  The only thing missing from its atmophere that separates it from our our in water vapor, however that does not mean that there couldnt be life on it, or life in its past.. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>A  habitable world has been found! It is 14.4 light years away from Earth, which means that if we were to travel to this planet at the speed of light it would only take us 14.4 years to reach it. The planet orbits a star, which we have named Alhaestah. The star, Alhaestah, is more luminous than our own sun, about 3.41 times more. That means that the star gives off more energy than our own sun does. The estimated lifetime of our habitable world is about 4 billion years-- which is a shorter estimated lifetime than Earths, but more than enough time for advanced life to evolve.

The planet orbiting Alhaestah is very similar to our planet Earth. Both have a similar density, which is about 3.77. That means that the planet is made of mostly rock, but it is likely that it has metal in its compostition as well just like our Earth does at the center. Interestingly enough, it is has about twice the radius of our planet, which makes it quite a big larger-- about six times as large as our Earth. 

The surface temperature of this planet is very similar to Earth's. We estimate its surface temperature to be 284.2 degrees Kelvin. Earth's is about 287 Kelvin. This is in part due to both planets having a strong presence of atmospheres, which help the planet retain heat. We have determined that due to the patters in the atmosphere, that this planet has many of the elements needed for life-- perhaps most importantly, water vapor. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Kail as a star-planet system that is very different from our own. The planet is larger than our own and about 1/4th the distance from it's sun as we are. The planet is kept warm by a much stronger Greenhouse effect that our own planet is, which maintains the planet at a much higher temperature than our own. The planet would be very warm and probably quite humid, as the much warmer air is capable of holding much more moisture. The atmospheric pressure on the planet would also be close to half of what Earth's is, which would take our bodies a long time to get used to. 

With less atmospheric pressure and warmer temperatures, I would imagine that many of the biosignatures found would have to have been buried rather quickly. On Earth, areas with a lot of heat and moisture are very well suited for the decay and decomposition process. I think that it would be safe to assume that the same would be true in the Kail system. Additionally, the lessened atmospheric pressure might lend to the lifeforms existing there having none or fewer actual bone or hardened structures, and the softer tissues would be much harder to preserve in the hot and moist environments. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Newly discovered Khel, a star emitting over 3 times more energy than our own Sun! Observing this star from a nearby 14 light years away, we have located a potentially habitable planet with a radius of twice our Earth, however its mass is about 6 times that of our Earth. This planet sits at over 342 thousand miles from its star. You would have to circle our Earth 13,745 times to travel that distance!

With an average surface temperature of 51.89 degrees F, only a few degrees cooler than Earth, but just fine if you don’t mind the chilly weather.

We are looking for traces of methane in the atmosphere, being that this may be an indicator of life. It is a product of one of the earliest ways organisms metabolize the available elements in the atmosphere. Of course this does not for sure say if there is life or note. We will also look for oxygen, which may indicate an organism such as our cyanobacteria from 2.9 billion years ago, whose main waste product was oxygen. 

</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Hello, I am excited to announce that I have discovered a potentially habitable world called Araveombam.  This planet is approximately 18 light years away from us.  This planet has a sun of it's own whose luminosity, which is how much energy this star is giving off, is 0.72.  To put this into perspective, our own sun's luminosity is equal to 1.  So this means that this alien sun and our own are very similar.  This exoplanet's sun has an estimated life of 12.6 billion years!  Although this seems like a lot, this is actually just a little more than our sun's life span.  Now onto the actual planet.  Araveomban is about 1.3 AU away from it's sun.  One AU is just a measurement of distance, 1 AU is equal to the distance from Earth to the Sun.  This means that Araveomban is a tad bit farther away from it's sun that we are from ours.  Araveomban has a mass of 1.6, a radius of 1.3, a density of 4.2 g/cm3.  Keep in mind that these mass and radius values are comparative to Earth.  Earth's mass and radius are set equal to one.  This means that Araveomban is about the same size as Earth and has a similar mass.  Density tells us what an object is made of.  If the density of a planet is high, it is likely to be made of rock and metal.  If the density is low, the planelt is likely made of gas or ice.  With a density of 4.2 g/cm3 we can say that Araveomban is made of rock and metal making it a terrestrial planet.  Now onto the surface of the planet.  It's surface pressure is 1 atm.  Atm stands for atmospheric pressure and it measures how much pressure the atmosphere is putting on the planet.  On Earth, we experience 1 atm.  Araveomban's effective temperature, or the temperature that we predicted using calculations, is 178 Kelvin.  178 Kelvin in fahrenheit is -139 degrees.  This may seem freezing and you maybe thinking, "How in the world could this planet be habitable!".  But when we take into account the greenhouse effect, this planet has an estimated temperature of 278 Kelvin or 40 degrees fahrenheit.  At this temperature and pressure, water here would be available in a liquid form.  After explaining Araveomban's characteristics you may notice that this planet and Earth are strikingly similar!  Now where to do we go from here?  Well we need to deterimine if there is life on the planet.  How do we do this when we are 18 light years away?  Well when there is life somewhere, that life will give off "clues" that it exists.  Essentially, life on a certain planet will inflluence and change that planet's atmosphere.  We look for these changes in the atmosphere, called biosignatures, to determine if there is life present.  On common biosignature we can look out for is methane.  But methane can be a little difficult to work with because there are non living sources that can create methane making it look life exists.  There are also sinks, or things that can destroy methane, making it look like methane is not present when, in fact, it is.  In order to detect methane the living organisms would have to create methane faster than the sinks can destroy them.  But even if we don't detect methane, it is possible for methane and life to exist on the planet, the sinks may just be destroying the methane too fast.  Also if we do detect methane, it's possible it was created by non living things and thus no life.  The possiblities are endless!  Thank you for your time and allowing me to display my findings to you.  We will be actively searching this planet for life and will report back in the future, hopefully with exciting news.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The most habitable planet I discovered was named Iseseth. It is a planet very similar to Earth in many ways but also very different. It is just slightly larger, about 1.5 times the size of Earth, and about 1/3 as dense. Its surface pressure is about 1.5 times the amount of Earth's as well so there would be slightly more gravity there. The atmosphere of Iseseth has a very strong Greenhouse Effect with water vapor, oxygen, carbon dioxide making up a good amount of the atmosphere very similar to our own atmosphere here on Earth, but there are many other prominent components that make it very different than our atmosphere such as nitrousoxide, ammonia, methane, and hydrogen sulfide. This raises the surface temperature Iseseth and makes it very hot, much warmer than Earth. The average day on Iseseth is approximately 349.5 degrees Kelvin or 169 degrees Fahrenheit compared to Earth days which are 287 degrees Kelvin or 57.2 degrees Fahrenheit. Even though, Iseseth is very warm though it is not too hot to maintain liquid water and is indeed very habitable. While Earth and Iseseth may have their differences they do have many similarities, but when it comes to their suns, the source of energy and potential life and habitability for a planet, these two could not be more different. 
Iseseth's host star (sun) is a little less than half as large as our own sun and only about 3% as bright. This causes Iseseth's sun to be much cooler than ours and so for Iseseth to be so hot, it has to be very close to its star. Iseseth is in fact 80% closer to it's sun than we are to our sun! That's almost 2 times as close to its sun than Mercury is to ours! Due to the smaller size and lower luminousity, Iseseth's sun also has a much longer projected lifetime than our own sun. Our sun is projected to live approximately  10-11 billion years while Iseseth has a projected lifetime over 10 times as long as our own sun at over 110 billion years old!</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Let me introduce you to the newest habitable planet found by the Hab Worlds project. I introduce Kaihano! Kaihano is a short 14.4 light years away and yeilds a parallax angle of .226389. Since one ly equals 5.878625 trillion miles, Kaihano is roughly 84.6522 trillion miles away. Its host star has a luminosity of 1.309867352(10^27) watts, similar to our own sun at 3.846(10^26) watts. Kaihano orbits a3.68 times further away from its host star than the earth does, thats roughly 5.50812688(10^11) meters away from its host star. It is six times the mass of our earth, its radius is double that of the Earths making it twice as big, and its density suggest that it is rocky in nature. We are all curious about temperature well Kaihano has an average temperature, after greenhouse gases introduce the greenhouse effect,  of 284 Kelvin. Thats a cool 51.5 Farenheight. So with the cool temps and the rocky terrain, the current residents of Kaihano should look like snowboarders. The challenge with Kaihano is the intense atmospheric pressue, it is at 77.88 psi while the earth rests at 14.695 psi. That is the equivalent of swimming at a depth of 780 meters. Yikes. It is likely that aquatic creature wouls occupy this planet. Anything terrestrial would probably be very short also.</string>
