    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Could There be Life?
May 3rd, 2015

Student researchers at Arizona State University announced today that they believe that have discovered a potentially Habitable planet. The students admit that this is still preliminary work, and were ultimately cut short by deadlines and commitments, but assert that there is a chance that there could be life on this planet. And interview with Oliver von Mizener, one of the students in charge of the research team, reveals that this is something worth being excited about. 

"After some careful analysis of the potential planet, we have decided that this is our best candidate out of the stars we had analyzed." When asked to clarify, Oliver stated, "Well, it's a little closer than our planet is from our Sun, but their star is a great deal less bright, so to speak". 

He continued, "I admit, that there is likely not life there now, but given the age of the star and it's distance, there is a chance that there used to be life there. We want to study this solar system more and see if we can identify anything else that might indicate that there was once life there."

We pressed for questions as to how they would examine this. "Well, we obviously can't fly out there. It's 15 light years away, it takes light itself 15 years to get out there. It just isn't possible. However we'll continue to look at this planet, gather information on it's environment and see how it has held up over the years."

We thought this all seemed a bit half baked, a dead planet we can't look at doesn't seem to indicate that life is possible outside of our own little bubble, but Oliver insisted that this could be significant. 

"Look, we missed the point." he admitted "We were tasked with finding something currently habitable but instead came up with something dead. However if we've learned anything during our research, any information is useful. This looks promising as a previous candidate, and if it had life, perhaps something in this quadrant could also support life. It allows us to narrow our focus."

"Not to mention the possibility for life that is beyond our comprehension. We have a set of parameters we understand to sustain life. However what if we are looking for something that is more alien than we expected? it doesn't hurt to look. I wish I could give you more at this time, but we rushed to get this out to press."

We look forward to hearing more about the labs progress in the future, perhaps with some confident students at the helm more progress can be made. This is ASU Times signing out. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The best candidate for a habitable planet was found orbiting the star called Horeyu which is located a distance of roughlt 31.4 light years away. This distance means that it would take light traveling at roughly 300,000,000 meters per second 31.4 years to reach us here on earth. The luminosity of this star, or measured brightness, is about 16 times that of our own sun with a lifetime of about 1.4 billion years. The planet that orbits Horeyu is about 1 astronomcal unit away from the star which is the same as the earth sun system. The planet has a mass of 2.8 times that of the earth and a radius of 1.5 times the earth. The density of this planet it roughly 4 g/cm^3 whereas the earth is about 5.5 g/cm^3. This means the composition of the discovered planet isterrestrial like our own planet. The pressure on the surface of the new planet is 12.5 times the pressure we find on our planet. The earth has a temperature of about 252 K while the temperature of the discovered planet is about 100 K greater due to a stronger greenhouse effect and hotter star. The combined pressure and temperature of the new planet allows for there to be liquid water on the surface which tells us that there may be life on this planet. This is exciting news for us, but the great distance of Horeyu means we need increased funding for research if we ever hope to reach this planet. Thank you for your time, I will now take questions.</string>
    </entry>

      <string>Arkin was the best possibnle candidate that I found for my system. It is 37.5 light years away which is equal to about 375,000,000,000,000 kilometers from us. It's host star has a luminosity of .867 which means it is .867 times as bright as our sun (so it's star is a little less bright than our sun). It has a projected lifetime of over 11 billion years, which is a little longer than the lifetime of our sun. It is .45 AU away from its host star meaning that it is a little less than half the distance that the earth is from our sun. It has a mass of about 4.5 times that of earth and a radius about twice as large as the earth's. It's density is 3.09 g/cm^2 which means it is primarily composed of rocky terrestrial material, with a surface pressure 63.4 times greater than the pressure found on earth. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Kjinson is a most fascinating star system. It is full of possibilities, including a planet revolving which has the possibility of life and even an atmosphere bearing a close resemblance to Earth! From what is seen, Kjinson is about 14.4 light years away! That is roughly 84,652,207,793,977 miles away! So, in retrospect, if a person traveled from Earth to Kjinson, it would be the rough equivalent of making 177,170,799 roundtrips to the moon! 

Kjinson, when compared to Earth’s sun, it much more luminous. It is about three times that of Earth’s sun’s luminosity. Kjinson age is a bit of a concern though, noting that its entire lifetime is projected to be the entire lifetime that the Earth has been in known existence (~4 billion+ years). That may not affect any of us, nor our future generations, but one day down the line, if humans populated the planet revolving this star, it cannot be a permanent home, and much like Earth is not. 

Which brings us to our next point, the planet revolving Kjinson. The planet revolving Kjinson is much different, yet very similar to Earth. I know, oxymoron, right? First off, the planet that was discovered revolves comfortable at 3.6819 AU away from its host star. That means it revolves at roughly 342,254,291 miles away from the star. Earth revolves comfortably around the sun at 1 AU, which is 92,955,807 miles from the sun. As you can see, the planet revolving Kjinson is quite a distance further than Earth is from the sun. Kjinson’s planet is also about six times the mass of Earth and about twice the radius of Earth, so needless to say it is much larger than Earth, which is not a bad thing by any means.

Now, for what really matters, can humans actually live on Kjinson’s planet? The effective temperature of the planet is 184.2 Kelvin, which is roughly -128.11 degrees Fahrenheit. A bit chilly, right? Well, that is not the end of this planet. There is a strong greenhouse effect occurring on Kjinson’s planet, and the surface has been warmed tremendously. The surface is a cool 284.2 Kelvin, 52 degree Fahrenheit. The planet has been warmed through the spreading of Carbon dioxide among other greenhouse gasses, just like Earth. The best thing is, this planet actually has liquid water with H2O present, just like Earth! There you have it folks, a planet that can possibly not only host life, but could possibly have a sprawling ecosystem, just waiting for us to discover!
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>-FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE-  May 3, 2015 Tempe, AZ.  Tired of living on a planet infested with people who think it's only 6000 years old? Well, there may be hope for those of you who are.  At a mere distance of 62.7 light years, in other words, 62.7 years traveling at the speed of light, lays the Emis star system.  After analyzing the intensity of the stars luminosity and noticing dips at specific periods, it was concluded that the Emis star was not without child.  This planet, named Batman, was lurking in the darkness of the universe before it was noticed transiting across the star.  This is where the dips or decine in the intensity of the star's luminosity came from.   Compared with our star, the Sun, Emis is only 2% of the luminosity, but fear not for the planet is only 22% of the distance that the Earth is from the Sun.  Using the doppler shift provided by the stars spectrum the mass of the planet could be determined.  Compared to Earth, planet Batman's mass is a little over double.  To find the radius of planet Batman, how big those dips in the luminosity from Emis had to be analyzed.  The radius was found to be 1.5 times bigger than Earth's.  Sweet, more elbow room! 
  Ok so we have a planet about twice the mass and size, but how do we know if it's habitable?  2% the luminosity of the Sun doesn't seem like it sounds like a warm place to live.  However, after analyzing the light from the corona of the planet as it transited across the star, it was found to have an atmosphere with greenhouse gasses in its composition.  Methane, oxygen, carbondioxide, water, ammonia, ozone, and other molecules were found when looking over the absoption lines in the spectrum.  The effective temperature, the temp provided by the star, with the addition of a strong greenhouse effect gives us surface temperatures of about 330K.  That's equivalent to the summers in Tempe, AZ.  Awesome! That means pool season all the time on planet Batman!  However, there is a downside.  At 56% of the pressure on Earth, the air is going to be kind of thin.  To get a better idea, that's like hanging out on top of a mountain that's about 15,000 feet tall, but with a 125 degree climate.  Still sounds better than having to deal with the ignorance that is running rampant on this planet.  Am I right or am I right ? 
   Now that is has been determined that humans can survive on planet Batman, the next step would be to make sure the planet isn't already occupied.  How do we do that? We look for certain biosignatures like oxygen or methane and determine if they were from natural causes or produced biologically.  We can also wait for the James Webb Space Telescope to be fully operational and perhaps get a glimpse of any exotic critters running around.  If found to be safe, the last step would be to really think about living on Earth with stupidity or start fresh on a new planet.  I'll leave that one up to the philosophisers.  
   On a final note, for us to be able to truly explore this planet, great leaps need to be made in technology.  I believe in our lifetime this is going to happen.  It all rests on whether Sonny White and the team at Eagleworks can get a working warpdrive and quantum communications become commonplace.  We're almost there and I can't wait. 


**Update Edit***  (5:20PM Tempe,AZ)
It has been found that the planet Batman is under the control of the Imperial Forces.  Our scouts have notified the SESE Rebel Alliance and a team has sent out cubesats to gather intel.  Any other updates will be posted as soon as they come in.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Greetings to all and thank you for taking interest in my latest discovery. Today i would like to present you with my star-planet system, Goril. It is about 18 light years away. That means it would take any light source 18  earth years to get there. Absolutely an incredible distance! The star's luminosity is about 7/10ths of that of our own star and is projected to live more than 12 billion years! This planet is slightly farther away than we are from our own star and has about 60% more mass that we do. It is about 30% larger in radius and has a very similar density as well. The pressure is slightly higher than Earth's and while the effective temperature is very cold, due to the greenhouse effect and atmospheric conditions, the temperatures will be very comparable to that of the Earth's. Due to all of these things, I would look to search for biosignatures like plant life and fauna similiar to our own. I am very excited to share this discovery with you all!</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The planet I found is located in the Drezaira star system, which is a little over 14 light years away. Though this sounds close, it would still take Voyager 1, our fastest traveling man-made space vessel, over 2 billion years to reach it, assuming it was traveling constantly at its max speed. The host star, Drezaira, has a lifespan of about 4 billion, meaning that the star would be dying or dead by the time we reached it.  The star itself is over 3.4 times as bright as our own sun, and the planet is about 3.7 times as far from the star as we are from the sun, so the amount of energy reaching the planet would be about the same as we get from the Sun, though slightly higher. The planet is twice as wide as the earth and 6 times more massive. However, the density estimates reveal the planet is mostly rock, with some traces of metal, water, and gas, making it structrually similar to Mars, but much larger and with a much denser atmosphere. The atmosphere creates 5 times as much pressure as there is here on Earth, and the gases within it cause surface temperatures to rise about 100 degrees Kelvin. This means that the air is much denser, heavier, and maybe even crushing to humans. The resulting temperatures are only 3 degrees Kelvin lower than our own. To put that in perspective, the Earth's average surface temperature is about 14 degrees Celsius (52 Fahrenheit), and the discovered planet has a surface temperature of about 11 degrees Celsius (51 Fahrenheit). This allows for liquid water to exist on the planet and produces surface conditions similar to ours on Earth (other than the massive air pressure). Because this planet has water vapor and oxygen in the atmosphere, it could be possible that life exists on it. As such, we could check for carbon compounds in the atmosphere like methane, but any that we find may be the result of geological rather than biological ones. If we do not find any methane, it does not rule out the possibility of life, as there may be enough carbon sinks (or carbon "absorbers") to "soak up" the carbon compounds in the atmosphere to the point where they are undetectible. However, it is still worth looking into the possibility. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Besirroma is the name of my star that was calculated to have a habitable planet. The distance of Besirroma from earth is measured in light years. This star is 62.7 light years away from earth. This is an important factor to concentrate on, because knowing the distance can help us determine the star's properties correctly. Besirroma has a luminosity of .025365192 Ls. Luminosity is the total amount of energy emitted by an object at any given time. It is an intrisic property, a property that doesn't depend on the distance the star is from the earth. For example, Luminosity is the height of a building; this property does not change no matter how far you are. On the other hand brightness is the amount of energy observed from an object at a distance. Let's say the apparent hieght of the distant building- it looks different at various distances. Besirroma has a life expectancy of 1.38 billion years, which gives the planet time to develop some type of lifeform. Now the planets characteristics, first off the mass and radius. The mass and radius are measured by being compared to the size of earth. One way to measure the size of the planets is by radius. Radius is the measurement from the center of an object to the edge of it. This newly discovered planet has a radius of 1.5038 compared to Earth and a mass of 2.175 compared to Earth.  A density of an object is calculated by the equation mass/volume. Bessirroma has a planet with a density that is between that of pure rock (3g/ cm3) and pure metal (8g/ cm3), which makes it a terrestrial planet, one of the key factors leading to a habitable planet. We now look into how far apart the palnet and star are from eachother- that is the distance measured in Astronomical units a units of length. 1 astronomical unit is roughly the distance from the Earth to the Sun. The discovered planet has a distance of .23 AU from Besirroma, closer than that of our sun and planet Earth. The thing that still can make this planet habitable is the energy balance between planet and star. In order for a planet to be energy balanced, the planet has to release 100% of light that was absorbed by its star. A higher luminosity star will make a planet hotter and a less luminous star will have a cooler planet. Even though the star is in the lower side of luminosity, other factors have a role that can make the planet right in temperature. These other factors are the reflectivity and distance of a planet. Mentioned above is the distance of the planet from Besirroma, .23 AU, since it is closer the planet will have more heat. The Reflectivity of a planet depends on its albedo, albedo being a measure of how dark an object is. For example, water has a low albedo .07-.10, so it reflects back little energy that makes it a factor that gives a planet warmth. If the found planet were to be too cold for liquid water, then the water would be in its solid stage- ice. Ice and snow have a very high albedo and therefore, reflect more energy that is kept, making an ice giant planet. This brings me to the effective temperature. The effective temperature of a planet is simply what the planet's temperature should be to sustain liquid water. Effective temperature depends on the flux it recieves, the flux depending on luminosity, distance and albedo, or how much energy it reflects back into space without keeping it. The effective temperature of my discovered planet is at 230.69 K. The proposed surface pressure also plays a role in  liquid water stability. The boundaries of the water zone are bigger when the atmospheric pressure is higher. With the temperature of 230.69 K and a surface pressure of .56 atm, it is safe to say that liquid water is not in a stable phase for this planet at this point.. it is too cold. This is fixed by the greenhouse effect. The greenhouse effect is the outgoing planet radiation that is absorbed by gasses that are present in a planets atmosphere. A planet warms up until it reaches its effective temp. and then starts to emit energy. Gasses that are present in the atmosphere of a planet then absorb this energy resulting in a warmer planet. This planet has enough gasses that absorb infared radiation and increases the overall surface temperature. The surface temperature being the planets effective temperature plus the atmospheres greenhouse effect. It has a strong greenhouse effect adding about 100 K to the temperature, resulting in 330.69 K. With a surface pressure at .56 atm and the effective temp. being at 330.69, we now have a habitable planet with a stable phase of liquid water. Some type of biosignatures I would look for on my planet are the abundant molecular oxygen, or the inorganic molecule ozone, because on Earth, molecular oxygen is produced mostly by the photosynthesis of plants. The surface of a planet also holds a good source of information. Certain properties of light reflected from green plants could provide a good biosignature. The simultaneous detection of water, carbon dioxide, and oxygen or ozone would be a strong indicator that biological processes are occurring on this planet. </string>

      <string>My planet is a bit cold, with the effective temperature being 249 K which is around -11 degrees F. It's density determines that it is made of mostly rock, which is what makes it a terrestrial planet. This planet is closer to its star then the Sun is to the Earth. This planet has a little more pressue then Earth, Earth's is around 1, while the pressure for this planet is 1.55. I would look for biosignatures of oxygen and possibily nitrgogen. The O3 on the planet helps to block harmful ultraviolet radiation, so that helps with the planet being a little closer to its star.The oxygen would be detectable in the atmosphere. If the greenhouse effect was a little stronger it would raise the effective temperature and make this planet a little more comfortable to live on, a moderate effect would be the best since a strong effect would make the planet too hot to be habitable. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>   My best candidate is a planet in the host star system Barlaira. This system is 95.9 light years away. This is equivelent to spending nearly 96 years moving at the speed of light to reach them. The host star is very dim, at a luminosity of only .0013, roughly 1000% dimmer than our star, though the star Barlaira has a projected lifetime of 1.1 trillion years, whereas our own star has a projected lifetime of about 10 billion years. Dimmer stars use less energy and so have much longer lifespans before their energy has been expended.
  The habitable planet found in this system is much closer to Barlaira than the Earth is to the sun. The distance is .0304 AU, or 3% of the distance from the earth to the sun. This Planet's mass is 2.92 times that of earths with a radius of 1.407 times that of earths. This planet has a density of 5.7859 g/cm^3. Comparing this in relation to Earths own density of ~5.5 g/cm^3, it is slightly more dense than earth. Most likely due to its larger radius and increased metallic matter in the planet. The atmospheric pressure of this planet is slightly less than half of earths, at .44atm or atmospheres. The Effective Temperature or temperature of the planet without any greenhouse gases, is 235.21 Kelvin, or -36.292 F. However this very cold planet is significantly warmed by the Strong Greenhouse Effect which can bring the temperature up to 143 F. This temperature in combination with the low surface pressure allows for this planet to have liquid water, and thus is potentially habitable. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Researchers have recently discovered a planet is a strong candidate for habitability. This planet orbits the star Jesesiphia, which is approximately four and a half light years from Earth. (A light year is the distance that light, the fastest-moving particle in the known universe, travels in a year - about 5,878,499,810,000 miles.) Jesesiphia emits about three percent of the energy that our Sun does (this is called the star's luminosity), and its expected lifetime is over 112 billion years, or about eight times the current age of the universe. 

The newly-discovered habitable world orbits Jesesiphia at 0.220 AU (astronomical units), or about one fifth of the distance at which Earth orbits the Sun. The planet's mass is 1.4 times Earth's mass, and the radius is 1.3 times Earth's radius. The density of this planet is about 3.5, which suggests that the majority of the planet is rock, with some metal present as well.

Before we consider the effect of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the planet's temperature is 249.6 Kelvin (-23.6 degrees Celsius and -10 degrees Fahrenheit). At this temperature, water is frozen solid, but greenhouse gases are present in this planet's atmosphere. These gases, like carbon dioxide, methane, and water vapor, prevent certain types of energy from leaving the atmosphere, which in turn warms the planet's surface by close to 100K. The new temperature, 349.6K, is about 170 degrees Fahrenheit (76 degrees Celsius) - hotter than any location on Earth, but still cool enough to allow water to exist in a liquid state, which is a necessity for life to exist. The surface pressure of this planet is about 1.5 times the Earth's, which will also allow for liquid water.

On this planet, we intend to search for biosignatures, or signs that life has or does exist there. Biosignatures can include the presence of living or dead organisms or certain types of rocks like cherts, which can contain fossils, and banded iron formations, which alternate between layers of iron oxide and cherts. Additionally, biosignatures can appear in the form of wastes - the leftovers of biochemical reactions. These wastes can come in the form of unnaturally occurring combinations of gases in the atmosphere (such as large amounts of oxygen produced by plants or large amounts of carbon dioxide produced by respirating organisms). They can also appear as radioactive waste, the isotopes produced by nuclear reactions. Finding biosignatures like these will be incredibly helpful to the scientists working to answer the ultimate question: are we alone in the universe?</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Kista is 4.4 light years away from Earth. That means that the light travelling from that planet to Earth takes nearly 4.5 years to arrive! Considering light travels at approximately 186,000 miles a second, that's a pretty staggering distance. Converting that to miles, Kista is 25,800,000,000,000 miles away from Earth! It's host star has a luminosity of .0338 compared to the luminosity of the sun we all know and love. Luminosity is a measurement of the brightness of stars, and if Kista's host star's luminosity is .0338 compared to our sun that means that it is .0338 times as bright as our sun (or not as bright in this case). This is an extremely dim star when compared to earth, and I wonder if you are able to look directly into the star in that solar system! It has a projected lifetime of 112,000,000,000 years, which is significantly longer than that of our sun (about 10,000,000,000 years). That makes sense considering it's luminosity. The lower the luminosity the less energy the star exerts and the longer the star lives. Kista is .219 AU from its star. AU stand for anatomical units and is a measurement of the distance from a planet to the star it is orbitting. AU is relative to earth, and 1 AU is the distance between the earth and the sun (92,960,000 miles). Its mass is 1.399 compared to earth, meaning Kista is 1.399 times more massive than the earth. It also has a radius of 1.3 compared to earth, meaning it's radius is 1.3 times larger than that of the earth. It's density is 3.509 g/cm^2, significantly less than the density here on earth (5.51 g/cm^2). Its surface pressure is 1.55 atm compared to earth, meaning the air pressure on Kista is 1.55 times greater than the air pressure on earth. The effective temperature is 249 degrees kelvin, however with the greenhouse effect (certain elements capture sunlight and trap it inside the atmosphere retaining it's energy and heat), which is strong, the temperature is about 349 K, making it habitable and quite warm. That converts to about 170 degrees farenheit, which is far too hot for humans liking.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>It has been discovered that there is a habitable planet orbiting the star Glunnayl. The star is 18 light years away and has a luminosity (.718 LS) that is slightly less than our sun’s (1 LS). It however has a very short life span of 1.265 years. The planet is about 1.29 AU from the sun. To put it into perspective, the earth is 1 AU from our sun. Compared to the mass of the earth, it is about 1.29 Me and has a radius of 1.28 Re. It also has a very similar density to that of the earth (5.51 g/cm3) at 4.19 g/cm3.  As we can see, this planet has very similar measurements to the earth. It is slightly bigger and less dense meaning that it probably has more gaseous elements than the earth. The temperature of this planet is 210.6 K which is about 45K cooler than the earth. But this is still in the temperature range for liquid water to be present. The greenhouse effect of the planet is very strong, however. This means that, if there is life, it is not very healthy and ‘human-type’ life would not be able to survive there. As for the biosignatures, I would look for the essential elements needed to sustain life. These include:  Sulfur, Oxygen, Carbon, Hydrogen and Nitrogen. If we can find presence of these elements, the chances of there being life on this planet become much more plausible. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I found a handfull of planets that could host life. Kathlat is a terrestrial planet that is about four times the size of earth. It lies almost exactly twice as far from its host star as the earth is from the sun. The star in question is slightly less luminous than our own, putting out about 85% of the energy the sun produces. Even though Kathlat is quite a bit further from its sun than earth it is but still remains habitable due to its size and greenhouse effect. The surface temperature is around 112 degrees fahrenheit making it hot but suitable for life. The greenhouse effect could make the planet unbearably hot for humans but other lifeforms would thrive in it. I would look for microbial life in wet environments first if life is not immediatly recognizable.</string>

      <string>The Best Candidate for a habitable world is Fyoddlana it's distance is 4.4 light years away. Now as for the planet that orbits this star it is habitable because liquid water exists here. This happens thanks to its distance from it's star which is 0.22 AU along with a mass of 1.39 when compared to the earth in other words is 1.39 times as big as our Earth. And its distance around or radius is 1.30 times as large as our Earth. With that comes its density of 3.50 g/cm^3 this means it would fall into the rock category of planets which would give it a great earth like surface. So with this planet just think that it would sink because water has a density of 1. tThe greenhouse effect on this planet is strong which helps make the surface temperture fall into the area where liquid water can be sustained. So overall this planet has many qualities that are close to our Earth athough the star it orbits is smaller than our star, life is sure to thrive on the planet. With this information as well we can conclude the biosignatures, or signs of life are available on this planet. We know this because of the distance and luminosity. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We are pleased to announce that a student at Arizona State University has identified a habitable world candidate. Patrick Keefe, a sophomore Electrical Engineering student, and a student in Professor Raymond’s SES 106: Habitable Worlds class, made the discovery.

	The host star, named Dekeegwyn, for Mr. Keefe’s pet gopher, is only 18 light years from earth. A light year is the distance light travels in 1 year. The Luminosity (the total amount of energy emitted by an object at a given time) is about 72% of the Luminosity of our Sun. 

	The planet, which has yet to be named, is about 1.3 times from its star as the distance Earth is from the Sun. The planet is a little larger than Earth and is comprised mostly of rock. The atmosphere is about the same as here on Earth. The average temperature is about 177 Kelvin which is a brisk 40 F. 

	We are very excited about this discovery and are anxiously awaiting a call from NASA to begin planning an exploratory mission to the planet to begin colonization. 

</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We interrupt your regularly scheduled programing to bring you this very important announcement!
A new world has been discovered! This world, unfortunately, is light years away, 62.7 to be exact, which means we will all be long dead before we ever reach it. 
Besestan
The planet Besestan is still very interesting to compare with our very own Earth. Besestan is quite a bit closer to its star and that would mean everyone should be sure to wear their sunblock as Besestan's sun is a lot closer than ours is. Besestan also has half the surface pressure of earth which means many things would practically float in comparison to us. Besestan is like Earth on weight watchers as the mass radius and density are all smaller than our home planet. Biosignatures to look out for to see if there was already life would be the smallest ratios of hydrogen and methane which could be indicative of present life. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>In order to have a start-planet system I had to find a planet that is similar to our Earth. The star in my planet system has a temperature of 8086K. Its mass is 1.980Ms and a radius of 1.700Rs. Its lifetime in years is 1.813Ga. I have classified this star in the main sequence.
It is also a host star to a planet that is 4.322 Astronomical units or approximately 85 years away from its star. The mass of the planet is 5.605in relation to Earth, and a radius of 2.113 in relation to Earth. It is classified as a terrestrial planet and has been deemed habitable due to its surface temperature, trace gasses and water phase. This planet has 7 trace gases (CH4, CO2, H2O, H2S, N2O, NH3, and O3) with and absorption of 98.19%. This means the gases absorb 98.19% of light being transmitted from the sun. When these gases are emitted back out they remain longer in our atmosphere thus increasing the effective temperature of 231.8. The rate of 98.19% absorption increases the effective temperature by 100 due to the greenhouse effect. Having a surface temperature of 331.8 allows for the planet temperature to remain at a state of habitability. This planet is also at a liquid water state and is able to host water. 
I discovered this planet by trial and error. I started with 300 stars and began my calculations. Once I had 45 stars that were possible host stars I removed the remaining stars on the list. Once the stars were selected I did more calculations to determine if it was in fact the host star to a planet. Once the host stars were found to have planets I sought to determine which of those planets were habitable. I did this by detecting trace gases, effective temperature and determining the effect of greenhouse gas. I compared my results to that of earth to determine if the surface temperature was within habitable range and that the planet was able to host water. 
I would search for bio signatures that are produced by bacteria, which would indicate the possible existence of life. In order to gather this data I would use the spectra of light radiated and reflected from the planet that would allow me to see peaks which would indicate molecules such as carbon dioxide, water, nitrous oxide and other molecules that indicate habitability.
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Here is my best habitable world candidate, star-planet Arimraldil.  This planet is quite far being that it is at 60.4 light years away that translates to it being somewhere around 355,061,388,524,000 miles away from us.  It's host star has a luminosity of 21.1 Ls, so in comparison to the Sun who's luminosity is 1 Ls, this star is giving off a ton of energy!  Luminosity is usually compared to a star's brightness though they are two different characteristics.  A star's brightness changes depending on how close or how far you are to it.  A star's luminosity on the other hand is simply the amount of energy radiating off of it outwards.  So regardless of if you are far or close up to the star it's luminosity never changes.  The host star also isn't very old.  If we were to compare its projected lifetime of 1,132,414,046 years to Earth's 4,600,000,000 years it is apparent that it would be about 3.5 billion years younger than Earth, but it has still been around for awhile!  Now as of the planet itself, it is about 91,083,024 miles away from it's host star.  It has a mass of 6.1 and a radius of 2.1 making it a decently large planet compared to Earth's 1 Me (mass) and 1 Re (radius).  It has a density of 3.4 which pushes it right into the rock category for planetary materials; any lesser and the planet may have been composed of ice, water, or gas and any bigger the planet could have been made up of metals, either which would have made the planet not habitable.  It has an effective temperature of 340 which is just within the boundaries of a habitable temperature between 270 and 370 degrees Kelvin.  Being that the planet's greenhouse effect is strong, that means that 60-100% of the host star's energy is being absorbed by the planet adding 100 K to it's effective temperature.  This would make the planet's overall surface temperature be 440 K. (surface temperature= effective temperature + greenhouse effects)</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>In recent discoveries an 'earth-like' plant was discovered in a galaxy much like our own, but 34 light years away. An 'earth-like' planet is classified by the planets ability to support liquid water, thus possibly supporting life. The world know known as Himasyash, rotates around a star with a luminosity much like our sun. The planet rotates close to the star at .4AU, where earth rotates the sun at 1AU. The density of the planet is just over 3 g/cm to the third, which tells us that the planet is composed of mostly rock, which classifies the planet as terrestrial, again like the planet we inhabit. The surface pressure is quite high in relation to Earth but combined with the temperature and high green house effect works to support liquid water. An essentual biosignature, or molecules, that provide specific evidence of human life, such as liquid water, oxygen, and ozone, were key pieces when searching for a habitable world. All of these biosignatures and more were found on Himasyash. There has been no confirmation of life on the planet, but as of now the planet has the possibility to support life, making it in fact habitable.</string>
    </entry>

      <string>Ayistash is a planet that could potientally be a habitable world. This means that life has a strong chance of existing on this planet and even potientally intelligent life. The planets host star (its version of our sun) has a luminosity condusive to supporting life. Its distance, mass, radius and denisty also support this theory. The planets surface temperature is similar to that of earth. It has a lower effective temperature than earth but an extremly strong greenhouse effect makign its surface temperature a comfortable and habitable one. Moving ahead in exploration of this planet I would look for fossil evidence and rock formation to give a significant look into the planets history. Now of course if upon landing a probe on this planet a creature of some kind walks up and says hello I do not think that the search for life will take to much time. Weathering is also another thing to look out for as it aids in the process of life. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Consider the star-planet system of Arli, a newly discovered planet within the habitable zone of its host star. While orbiting its host star at a distance not unlike Earth from the Sun, the similarities soon end there, yet its potential to harbour life still remains.  Any life discovered there may not look like us, or any of the complex organisms we have on Earth due to high atmospheric pressure, however, the planet's surface temperature makes it able to support water in a liquid state.This is one of the most important factors in determining the ability to sustain life. One orbit around Arli takes three times as long as it does Earth to orbit the sun and because of the high pressure and gases on the planet, a strong greehouse effect exists, yet not enough to hamper any potential life, as on Venus. The ability for the planet to sustain liguid water along with the trace gases found lead us to believe that life could possibly exist on this planet. The mixture of gasses present including:  methane, liquid water, and carbon dioxide provides a possible biosignature that there is or may have been life present on this planet. 
</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Located about 4.4 light years away is a planet that is causing a lot of buzz in the world of astronomy. Astronomers are intrigued by the habitability of this planet. Studies of Kirzihael show characteristics that indicate it is indeed a habitable world. This Earth-like planet first gained attention by some collegiate star watchers out of Tempe, Arizona, when studying its host star, which has a luminosity comparable to that of the Sun. With continued research, the planet is found to be 40% more massive than Earth, and has a radius 30% larger. Analysts determine the planet to have a very earth-like temperature, and a strong atmosphere. With these indications, one can determine that life is possible on this planet. As we continue to learn about our own planet earth, we strive for deeper understanding of our universe. With this latest discovery, our interest in life beyond earth can only increase without bound. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Outta this world.  A new habitable world has been discovered, which shares many similarities to earth.  The new planet, Cath, which is 60.4 light years away.  At 21.11 Ls (total amount of energy emitted by the star at any given time), Cath is 21.11 times as luminous as our sun.  Cath’s suns projected lifetime is 1157229928.25 years.  

In order to be deemed habitable, it must be a terrestrial planet, which is the closest to the sun.  They are made mostly of rock and metal, and have densities (between 3 and 8 g/cm3) yet they are small in size.  Cath has a density of 3.6 g/m3 which means that it is made mostly of rock.  Cath has a luminosity of 21.1, or amount of energy emitted by the star at any given time, so this means that it is 21.1 times as luminous  as our sun.

In order to be classified as a habitable world, the effective temperature must fall between 273 degrees and 373 degrees K.  Cath meets the temperature requirements at 339.644 K to host life with its moderate level of greenhouse gas affect from things like water, oxygen, nitrogen, and other greenhouse gasses.

</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Ingrindry is 96 light years or about 564 trillion miles away from our system. The host star is a little over half as luminous as our own, which means it releases about half as much energy. It will also live a few billion years longer than our own sun.
The planet is about 148 million miles from its' star which is about 1.6 times as far as Earth is from our sun. The planet has a bit more mass than Earth, almost twice as much, and its' radius is fairly similar which means it should be about the same size as Earth. Its' density, or the average of all material in the planet, is 3.5 g/cm^3, which is a bit less than Earth's density of 5.5 g/cm^3. The planet also has a strong greenhouse effect which raises its' temperatures much higher than its' cold effective temperature of 183 K, or about -90 degrees celsius, and allows for liquid water to exist.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Igja'are is a habitable world found about 37.5 light years away, which is approximately 217.5 trillion miles. In order to reach this planet, it would take man about 750,000 years traveling at approximately 18,000 miles per hour! Igja'are's sun is much closer than our own, sitting at 41,965,331 miles away, compared to Earth's sun at 92,960,000 miles. This explains why Igja'are has a higher effective temperature than Earth - about 112 degrees Farenheit. This habitable world is also much larger than Earth, totaling around 7,930 miles around, while Earth's raidus is only around 3,958 miles.

This planet was found by discovering a star that has an orbiting planet. By calculating the orbiting planet's density, I was able to determine whether or not the planet was terrestrial. After calculating the surface temperature, Igja'are's stable water state could be determined, and was found to be liquid - the same as Earth.

The type of biosignatures needed in this planet would be one that is very similar to our own planet. Habitable worlds are compromised of similar gases in order to manipulate the atmospheric pressure of the planet to a desireable and liveable level.
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The host star is a red dwarf, with a very long and stable lifespan, perfect for habitability. The planet itself is not far from the star, only 22% of the distance from the Earth to the Sun. Physically speaking, the planet has about 70% more surface area than the Earth, and it is mostly made up of rock. Surface pressure and temperature are both greater than those of Earth, but still within reasonable bounds to allow for life. Looking for certain life-supporting gasses allowed me to find an approximate surface temperature, and thus evaluate the potential for life.

In summary, this planet has a stable host star, a size and mass relatively comparable to those of Earth, and a surface temperature, thanks to a strong greenhouse effect, that allows for the presence of liquid water, essential to life as we know it.</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Astronomers announced the discovery of a habitable planet candidate orbiting a red dwarf star 83.6 light years away from Earth. The rocky terrestrial planet named Jinjin is 60% larger in radius and 3.6 times the mass of Earth. Jinjin is located in its stars habitable zone. The habitable zone is the zone or region around a star where planets are at the right orbital distance from the star for liquid water to be present on the planets surface. Liquid water is the most important compound in supporting life as we know it. 
Jinjins distance from its host star is 17.8 million miles away, which by comparison is less than half the distance Mercury is from the Sun at nearly 36 million miles. Because red dwarfs are low mass stars, they emit energy at a much slower rate and are visibly less bright. The slower the rate of emitted solar energy the longer the lifespan of the star. Jinjins star emits just 3% of the total energy our Sun emits and has a projected lifetime of 120 billion years or 12 times greater than that of our sun. 
The predicted or effective temperature of Jinjins surface is -55 degrees Fahrenheit and is determined by the total amount of starlight that reaches the planets surface, and the amount of starlight the planet absorbs or reflects. As the planet absorbs energy and warms up, it emits infrared light to restore temperature balance between in-coming starlight and out-going planet energy. The high surface pressure of this planet indicates a lot of gasses are present in its atmosphere. These gasses temporarily absorb the out-going planet radiation creating a strong greenhouse effect. The greenhouse effect increases the temperature of the planet to 124 degrees Fahrenheit providing a stable environment for liquid water at its surface. 
In our exploration of Jinjin, we'll look for scientific evidence of past or present life in its geology and atmosphere known as biosignatures. Scientists will use techniques such as age dating and absolute dating to determine the geologic sequence of events of an area and to date the estimated age of the rocks. By understanding the sequence of past geological events, scientists can also hypothesize about the atmospheric conditions of the planet during that time and the type of life that may have been present. All living organisms are made of cells. For organisms to grow and reproduce, biochemical processes occur at the cellular level to create energy. Metabolism or the ability to create energy is key to all life and occurs through a series of chemical reactions (called redox reactions) whereby electrons are exchanged. The basic building blocks of life are composed of six bio-essential elements abundant throughout the universe; carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur. If liquid water exists on Jinjin and traces of these building blocks are present or were in the past, we may discover life on this planet. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>A great discovery has been made recently here at the Katelyn Astronomy Lab for Other Earths! We have found planet 4.4 lightyears away that potentially harbors life!

This planet is orbiting a star that is less luminous than our own-- about 3.38% the luminosity of our own sun-- but the planet is about 5 times closer to the star than our own planet is to the sun. As a result, this new planet has a surface temperature of around 350 K-- much hotter than earth. Earth’s surface temperature is usually around 288 K or 59 degrees F. 

Though this planet may be too hot for us Earthlings, the planet is able to sustain liquid water, and therefore possibly life. The planet also has a slightly thicker atmosphere than Earth does-- about 1.5 times what we’re used to. Its radius and mass are only slightly larger than those of Earth’s, but its density 1.5 times less than Earth’s density, meaning that it is mostly made up of rocks, and very little metal, unlike earth which has a large metal core.

In order to know if there is life on the planet, we here at Katelyn Astronomy Lab for Other Earths need to look for what gasses are present in the atmosphere. We know that this planet has a strong greenhouse effect, which means it probably has water, methane, carbon dioxide, among other essential gasses present in its atmosphere. These gasses are essential to our own atmosphere, and we must explore further to see if life on the newfound planet is sustainable.</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Possible habitable world found
Recently, we have discovered a planet orbiting the star Keegolak that has the hypothetically accurate characteristics to sustain life. Keegolak is 37.5 light years away and has a projected lifetime of 11 billion years. It's luminosity is 0.87 Ls. The orbiting planet is half as close to the star as we are to our sun. You might be shocked to hear the surface temperature comes in at around 400 K or about 260 degrees F... so how could it possibly hold life? Well the atmosphere, coming in at 63.4 atm, is strong enough to make liquid water possible, and if liquid water is possible, so is life! The atmosphere is similar to ours with some of the same elements (water, methane, N2O, etc) and the greenhouse effect is very strong. 
Now all we have to do it get there</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Ignath is the planet I chose that is habitable. This means that it is possible for life to exist on it. Habitable characteristics would be that the planet is a liquid (water zone) and its surface temperatue is between 273-373 degress Kelvin. It is not too cold or hot to contain life. Ignath is 31.4 light years away from earth. Its host stars luminosity, it's intrinsic light and total energy released, is 16.04622797 Ls. Ls is a measurement formed through an equation using the starts brightness (amount of that energy that hits our eyes) and the logarithm of the parallax angle. (the distance from the earth and star over different times of the year like 6 months and 12 months). The projected life time of this star is 1.377270723206843e9 years. The planet circulated this star is 1.041587725037869 AU away from the star. AU is the astronomical unit of 149597871 kilometers. For example, the earth is 1 AU away from the sun. The mass of the planet is 2.806... Me. Which is calculated by a formula using the startsm velocity, orbital radius and the stars mass. The radius of the star (distance from the center of the planet to the edge) is 1.5633.. Re which is calculated by using the brightness drop percentage and star radius and the density of the planet is calculated by dividing its mass by its volum. The surface pressure of the planet is 12.57 atm and has an effective temperature of 355.8 degrees kelvin. The effective temp is the surface temperature plus the amount produced by green house effect which is how much radiation is absorbed by the planet through greenhouse gasses and the re-radiated. This planets green house effect is moderate meaning 40 to 60 percent of its energy is absorbed and 30 degrees kelvin is added to the surface temperature. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>I have recently discovered a habitable planet 18 light years away, which is equivalent to 105,812,997,000,000 miles thats approximately 4,035,775,800,000 marathons, thats a lot of running. This planet is called Jena, and since this planet is habitable its characteristics are very similar to those of Earth. It has an approximate lifetime of 12,658,916,032 years which is slightly longer than Earths estimated life of 1,750,000,000 years. When seeking out a habitable world there are many factors that we need to observe. These factors include, the host star and the energy released by the star, the distance from that star, the surface pressure, and the surface temperature, the density, and the greenhouse effect. Quite a mouthful, but all of these observations are necessary to discovering a habitable world.  Jena has a Sun (host star), which has a luminosity of approximately .71886 which is the energy that the star releases. Our Sun has a luminosity of 1, which means it releases more energy than Jena's host star. Jena also has a strong greenhouse effect, which means it has a large quantity of gasses that are neccessary for life, such as CO2, CH4, O3, and H2O. This greenhouse effect allows the surface temperature to increase to approximately 278.4058 K which is approximately 41 degrees farenheit. Jena is slightly cooler than the earth due to its distance of 1.291 AU which is equivalent to 120,005,947 miles, which is 4,615,613 marathons. The greenhouse effect also signifies that Jena has an atmosphere which is necessary for life as well. With the combination of the surface pressure and the surface temperature it allows the planet to exhibit liquid water which as most people are aware of that is an absolute necesscity for life. We can also observe that it is a rocky terrestial planet from its density of 4.1946g/cm^3. This means that although there is water and gas within the atmosphere there is more rock and metal, which means there would be land for a species to develop and evolve on. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The solar system I located with the most habitable planet is caled the Cedstilmo system. It is located over 1,700,000,000,000,000 lightyears away (that's a Quadrillion!),  from us which is roughly 680 million times further than Pluto is from our sun, thats far! The sun in the system is not quite as bright as our sun, only about 70% as bright actually. That means that the temperature on this planet is also lower, on average about 40* F. The "year"  on this planet is over one and a half times our 365 day year, at 569 days to orbit it's sun. The year is so much longer because the planet is further away from its sun than earth is, Earth to sun is 1 au, this planet is 1.3 au from it's sun. You might be asking how does a planet that is so much further from it's sun with a colder sun to begin with, how does it stay at a livable temperature? This unique planet is equipt with a stron greenhouse gas atmosphere containing CH4, CO2,H2S,N2O,NH3, and O3. 
The gasses above are considered bioessentials. Bioessentials are any gasses that are produced as waste by a metabolism. Plants take in sunlight, and c02, and release Oxygen into the atmosphere. In this case Oxygen wold be the bioessential. Speaking of Oxygen, this planet seems to be lacking the ever important gas. However earth was also once an oxygen lacking planet, but through some major event it began accumulating in our atmosphere. There is hope that the same can be occurring on the planet in the Cedstilmo system. </string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Very excited to annouce the discovery of my habiltible planet. The best candidate from the habitabile worlds that I found is the star-planet system Araviv. Araviv has a perfect lumnosity or, energy given off, and distance from the planet that it provides a perfect temperature for habitibility and liquid water. It is 62.7 light years away which is 3.68581938 × 1014 miles which is 1.41762E+13 marathons if thought about that way. That's a lot of marathons! With that, the greenhouse effect warms the planet even more creating a stable environment for the planet. Strong greenhouse effects are important in habitibility because there is not as much heat being lost into space, it is instead being absorbed by the gases present in the atmosphere. The temperature is important because if it is too hot it's like Venus which has a lot of water vapor, and if it's too cold it's covered in solid ice with no liquid water. Liquid water is one of the most important aspects of a habitible world.The density of the planet was also very important in it's habitibility, without the right density the planet would not have been the right one for life to survive. This planet has a density of 3.6 g/cm3 making it perfect for the terrestrial category which are between densitiies of 3 and 8. Terrestrial means that it is rocky and metal which gives a species land to develope on. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>A potential habitable world has been discovered!

It is a whopping 18 light years away. To put that in perspective, light travels at around 670 million miles per hour throughout the universe. Traveling at that speed, a person would go around the globe eight times in one second. That's nuts. 

The luminosity of the host sun of the planet has a luminosity of .71886 Ls. This means it is about 71.88% as luminous as our sun! 
Luminosity is defined as the amount of light it emits from its surface. This is different than apparant brightness. The difference lies with distance. Apparant brightness is not an intrinsic property of a star, but is based on perspective. It is similar to seeing a lightbulb close up and a light bulb at about 100 feet away. the brightness changes, but luminosity does not. 

The lifetime of the host star is 12,658,916,033 years or about 13 billion years. Our sun's lifetime is about 10 billion years! The bigger the luminosity and mass of the star, the quicker it burns out. This results in a shorter lifetime. 

The distance of the planet from the sun is about 1.2906 AU. 1 AU is distance from the center of the Earth to the sun. 1 AU is about 149,597,871 kilometers. In essence, Dolnitilya is a little bit farther from it's sun than Earth is from our sun. 

The mass of Dolnitilya is 1.6001457 Me. This means that Dolnitilya has 1.6 times the mass of our Earth. 1 Me = the mass of our Earth. 

The radius of the potential habitable world is 1.28128 Re, meaning that Dolnitilya has a radius 1.28 times bigger than Earth's. 

The density is 4.1946 g/cm^3. this means that the density per cubic centimeter of the planet is 4.19, classifying it as a terrestrial planet. Had the density been significantly under 1 and close to ~.5 g/cm^3, then it would be classified as a gas planet because it is below the density of water which is 1 g/cm^3. the density of a water or ice planet is ~1 g/cm^3, the density of a rock planet is ~3 g/cm^3, and the density of a metal planet is ~8 g/cm^3. A terrestrial planet is in between rock and metal, and is the only type of habitable planet. 

The effective temperature is 178.408 K which in fahrenheit is about -138.5 degrees. That's originally way to cold for life! This is the temperature prior to taking into other variables like Greenhouse Effect into account. 

The greenhouse effect is strong, meaning that there are a lot of greenhouse gases present in the atmosphere of Dolnitilya.

I looked for biosignatures that resembled Earth's to see if it is habitable. In this case, the greenhouse effect is strong and many trace gasses were found, such as methane and carbon dioxide. Due to the large amount of greenhouse gases present in Dolnitilya's atmosphere, the temperature of the planet raises100 Kelvin, changing it  from 178.4 Kelvin to 278.4 Kelvin. in other terms, the greenhouse gases alone raises the temperature from -138.5 degrees fahrenheit to 41.46 degrees fahrenheit. I made sure the potential greenhouse gasses correlated with what Dolnitilya portrayed graphically. 

Finding a planet with all of the required characteristics is very rare, so this quite the find!</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Scientists today have found a habitable world -- which means there is a recent discovery that is able to hold life. The new world is called "Belebron." The planet is a little less dense than planet Earth, but only by 1 g/cm^3.  Its radius, however, is closer to our familiar planet. 

The biosignatures of Belebron resemble Earth, and therefore, Belebron is habitable. No two things are exactly alike, and while these worlds may be different, they do share something in common - being able to sustain life. 

Belebron, of course, does share a very important trait with Earth - water! H2O is found on this new world. One can swim, wash their face, and most importantly, have access to an essential part of life. Because of water, other organisms can thrive on this newly discovered planet as well!

Because the world has not been lived on yet, there is no major greenhouse effect. However, with human actviity, that will increase. That is not a bad thing. The natural greenhouse effect on Earth is not harmful, and there needs to be a balance. Zero greenhouse effect paired with human activity will let those who live on the planet thrive.</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>My planet falls under the star system of Durio and it is a unique habitable world. Durio is a very small star that is not very luminous. At a whopping 138 Ga, Durio is still just a baby for the star of its size, but for its age, it is in a stable age to have a stable planet orbiting it. Because Durio is so small, its planet must orbit it at a very close distance to receive the warmth necessary to be within the habitable and water zones. It orbits its star at a distance that is about a fifth of the distance we are to our sun. Since this planet is so close to Durio, its year only lasts sixty Earth days! Although Durio is small, its planet is a different story. This planet is the size of about one and a half Earths, and has more than double its mass! Durio’s planet is considered a terrestrial planet, which means that it is comprised of a mixture of metal and rock instead of gas or ice giants like Neptune and Jupiter. Durio’s planet has a unique cocktail for an atmosphere. There are seven greenhouse gasses present, including two of Earth’s most well-known: carbon dioxide and water vapor. This planet’s atmosphere is also a little more than half of Earth’s, which is a unique find! At a surface temp of 330 K or 135 degrees Fahrenheit, it would be quite a toasty place for a vacation. However, due to its temperature and atmospheric pressure, liquid water is found stable on the planet’s surface! With this unique planet housing a variety of greenhouse gasses, a metal and rocky core, and being a part of a system over 100 billion years old, the ingredients for life are present.</string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Berralera, a star 18 light years away with a slightly dimer surface (about a third) and a host planet of incredible potenial for life. With a surface pressure hardly a tenth more than earth's (1 atm), this quite habitable world would almost feel like home on the surface. The major diference between earth and this new planet is greenhouse effect. On earth, greenhouse gases (such as CO2) warm the planet around 30 degrees, yet, on this new planet such gases warm the planet over 100 Kelvin (K)! This is not an issue since the temperature before this warming effect is approximately 178 degrees K (significantly less than earth's). The result is a simalar temperature where water (or a water substitute) can exist at liquid fom on the surface! Opening the possibility for life previously unimaginable. The planet is slightly bigger than earth (about a third) and has a terrestrial compisistion much like earth. All of this bodes well for the chance of alien life in space. 



</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The class has definitely given me a better understanding of how astronomers are able to calculate which stars have planets and which planets may be habitable. The spectrum of a star shows what elements the present in a star. Depending on the brightness, it shows how far away a star is from us. The luminosity helps us determine how much energy the star gives off. Depending on the luminosity and the surface temperature, we can determine the size of the star: main sequence, white, dwarfs, giants and super giants. The planet needs to be at the right distance of the star, depending on the size and energy that it releases, to make sure that its not too hot nor an ice ball. Now, these stars, even if they are large, have the potential of having a planet. We can identify if they have a planet by looking at the star's spectrum. If there are 2 brightness drop consistent then there is a plant. Depending on the planets density, they can be a gas, water/ice or rock/metal planet. The most likely planet that will be habitable is the rock/metal planets. The next thing to check is if the planet have and atmosphere. These will determine what gases are present and if there is enough to create a green house effect on the planet surface. This can help warm and stabalize a planet to make it between 273-340K at a certain atmospheric pressure. If the necessary bioessential elements (C, H, N, O, P and S) are present then the planet may be habitable.  </string>
    </entry>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>This star-planet system has a possible habitable planet that someday earthlife can life on. The planet orbiting Hist is closer to the host star than Mercury is to the sun in our own solar system. Which might not make sense because Mercury is a dried up world with no signs of life. But because Hist is less luminous than our own sun, the planet will get heated up as much as Mercury did by our own Sun. There is also liquid water on this planet, and we know that water is an essential building block to ultimately find "intelligent life." Rather thats a life form that can fly and communicate like a human being, or life that bark at you like a dog, it all began somewhere. And there is liquid water, that also means that there is oxygen, which is something that might be needed in the evolutionary process to develop intelligent life. So that means in the water, in the air, in the atmosphere, we should detect oxygen. Along with some greenhouse gases such as Nitrogen and Carbon dioxide. Just like on planet Earth.  </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The star-planet system that was discovered contains similar characteristics to that of the Earth and our sun.  The group in question is located about 14.4 light years from us here on Earth.  This group features a star that gives off about three times as much energy compared to our sun and has a total lifetime of 4,150,000,000.  Now some might say that being on a planet with a star has three times as much energy might not sound like a good plan however this issue has been thought through.  The planet  that the sun hosts is about three times farther from its star than Earth is to our sun so the planet is not burning up like one might initially think.  

Data retrieved from the planet also shows that it has about six times more total material than the Earth.  This material is also made up of rock and metal much like the Earth.  One difference that should be noted is that the pressure on this planet is about five times more than than on Earth however it is not outrageous to say that it can still host life.  The temperature however is very similar.  Our mystery planet seems to be undergoing a strong greenhouse effect which is also seen here on Earth, with that factored in, the average temperature is about 10 degrees Celsius of 50 degrees Fahrenheit.  

This discovery is in its infancy and is still in the process of being monitored for life.  Liquid water is believed to be present which combined with an Earth like atmosphere, is a good basis for life.  Further monitoring of gasses such as water vapor, oxygen, and nitrogen will be monitored.  Why theses gases you ask?  Simply put, these three are the main gases that make up Earth's atmosphere.  Simply put, having these three in combination in an atmosphere is rare and a good sign a planet can support life.  
</string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>We have discovered the planet, Audesh, about 1411.8 light years away from Earth. The livability  quite a bit different from Earth, with an average surface temperatue of about -52 degrees Celcius, or -72 degreen fahrenheit. However, the planet's star is brighter than our sun, so there will be plenty of light available despite the cold. It is a frozen tundra in many places, but still capable of maintaining liquid water and, therfore, the potential for life.  It could be that this planet is in it's "snowball" phase; a time where the conditions seem bleak, but great potential for life takes place. After Earth's "snowball" period, high concentrations of oxygen were produced by single-celled organisms, which eventually gave rise to the plants and animals that are familiar to us now.  The star that the newly discovered planet orbits is about 8.8 billion years old, about 4 billion years older than our sun. 

The planet is about 1.8 AU from its star. If it were part of our solar system, it would be just past Mars. The planet is small compared to Earth, at about one third of our home planet's mass, and three fourths of Earth's radius. It has a similar density to Earth. Because of this, we believe the ground to be similarly terrestrial, and may have some familiar looking rocks and metals. 

The pressure on the planet's surface is much higher than on Earth, at about eight times higher. Any forms of life on this planet may look very different from what we are familiar with, due to the adaptations required to withstand that difference in pressure. The greenhouse effect on this planet is also very strong, which adds to the buildup of heat in the atmosphere. If this greenhouse effect continues with nothing to counteract it, the temperatures may rise, and become more appealing to those of us here on Earth.

Though there are potential biosignatures to look for on this planet, such at the presence of methane, their presence alone oes not conclusively indicate life. The sources of biosignatures, such as methane, would first have to produce the chemical before they could be re-absorbed. Secondly, they would have to be produced by living beings, and not naturally occuring. It it impossible to tell the difference unless we can know that there are organisms giving off these biosignatures. Just seeing the chemicals alone does not give much information. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Well to start off with, the planet is relativly close to us by being only 4.4 light years away. This is still extremely far, but in comparison it is right around the block. The host star is not that similar to our own sun, this one is a lot smaller and less luminous, which refers to its heat production. For a planet to be in the  habitable zone for this sun it would have to be a lot closer than we are to our sun. Luckily this was the case with Cyrsin, which is only .2198 Astronomical units (the distance between our earth and the sun). This would be closer than mercury is to our sun, but with the lessend luminosity or heat from the sun the planet doesn't dry up. The planet itself is similar to our earth in size and mass, just a little bit larger though. On this planet the sun alone is not enough to heat this planet, so a heavy greenhouse effect, like the one we have on earth, helps the planet retain its heat and stay habitable. </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>The Audriani star-planet system is 141.8 light years away from us, meaning it would take 141.8 years travelling at the speed of light to reach this star. The terrestrial planet is made mostly of rock and lies withing the habitable zone of the solar system. The strong effect from the Greenhouse gases creates a thick atmosphere that retains a lot more heat irradiated from the planet. This heats up the planet almost 100 degrees Kelvin and creates surface temperatures warm enough to hold liquid water. This allows for water to easily switch forms between ice and vapor. Also, liquid water allows for erosion and weather patters due to the solubility and very reactive nature of water with rock and ice.  When water reacts with rocks, it breaks it down into soils which hold other materials like Carbonate materials or calcium. These materials are what is needed to naturally fertilize plant life. Also the dissolution of carbonate materials by water reactions lubricate plate tectonics in the planet which is a huge biosignature to show that the planet is still alive!</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Life outside our solar system, is it possible? 
   A recently discovered star-planet system, Gwin, suggest yes. With the multitude of stars in the Universe, the possibilities of another star harboring life like our star, the Sun, does is very possible. Orbiting a star not as luminous as our sun, a planet found in the “habitable zone”, the region where liquid water could exits on a planet’s surface, may be home to life. The planet is slightly larger than our Earth; the planet measured to have a mass of approximately 1.4 times the size of Earth and a radius of about 1.3 times the Earth. In addition, this planet has a density of about 3.5 g/cm3, where our Earth is about 5.5 g/cm3. This makes the planet a terrestrial planet, like the Earth, giving a possibility to life on it. The planets proposed surface pressure of 1.55 atm suggest the presence of an atmosphere that could have a strong greenhouse effect on the planet. This would raise the low effective Temperature of 250 Kelvin, about -10 F, to a surface temperature that could support life. The planet is orbiting much closer to its star, but because of the stars lower luminosity, this places the planet in a state that could support liquid water. One of the basic stepping block needed to support life, as we know it. We will need to look for biosignatures that match our Earth. Life as we know it require things like oxygen and ozone, therefor finding the signs of these may indicate life. In addition finding signs of carbon would suggest life because it is produced as waste by life as we know it. We will need to look deeper in to this unknown system to see if it in fact does have life within it.


</string>

      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>When looking at my star-planet system we found a Star called Efin. This is a star that is very far away from us. It would take us 37.5 years to be exact. This Star has a Luminosity, or what we could call brightnes of .86686073 Ls or dulling it down a little, this star is almost as bright as our sun which has an Ls of 1. This star hosts a planet, which in theory, can support life. With the Surface Pressure at 63.4atm and an effictive temperacture of 318.1 K is capable of allowing H2O to be in a liquid state at its stable phase, which is curtial to habitability. When we found this planet we looked for biosignatures or what elements that this planet posseses, and if it has the ability to retain some of the stars energy by creating an atmosphere. This planet has a very strong greenhouse effect which means it is capeable of retaining a lot of energy from the star. Without this greenhouse effect the planet would be much colder and unable to host life. That being said after discovering this star and planet all of the characteristics that we looked at do provide support that this planet may in fact have life on it. </string>

      <string>The planet Beri was discovered to be the best canidate in the universe to hold life other then our earth. the planet is 52.6 light years away, making it relitivly close to us and keeping it in our own glaxy. The planet is hosted by a star that is the goldilocks of suns, not to hot, not to cold, this allows the planet to sit in both the haibitable zone, and the water zone.
this is very key as to have life (as we know it) we need to have liquid water and a sutable atmosphere. being far enough away from the sun that the atmoshpere is still present and that it keeps the planet insulated enough to hold water is the KEY factor in finding this habitable world. 

This planet has the potential for testerial life, however the extent to which is unknown at this time. the planet is going to have a rocky surface and likely has a multan metal core. this planet is much like our own eath planet hoever it is 6x the size of earth with 65x the mass, this leads experts to belive it has a higher metalic content then earth. </string>
