    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>It is very rare to come across a habitable planet in space other than our own. Out of 105 stars that I analyzed, only two of them had a habitable planet. Aedd was the best habitable world candidate that I discovered because it relates well to Earth. Similiar to our sun, Aedd's host star has a luminosity of 0.867Ls. We use 1Ls to describe the luminosity of our sun. The luminosity is the rate of  emission of radiation that the star releases. 

Along with this similarity come many others. The similarity that grabs my attention is the relationship between Aedd's Effective Temperature (Surface Temperature) in relationship to its Greenhouse Effect. Aedd's Effective temperature is about 318K. Earth's is actually lower (288K). But both planets have strong Greenhouse Effects. This means that there are a lot of gases in the atmosphere that affect their temperature by blocking in some heat for a set amount of time. Planets with lower Greenhouse Effects can lose energy almost as fast as they gain energy, keeping them cool. Because Earth and Aedd temporarily trap some heat with their thicker atmosphere's these planets gain energy at a faster rate than they are losing energy, resulting in a higher surface temperature. Believe it or not, but this is the reason why Earth and Aedd are habitable planets. Without their strong Greenhouse Effects, they could both be too cold to support life.  

Detecting Aedd comes from gathering a lot of information about the planet's host star and about the planet itself. First you want to make sure Aedd's host star has a Lumiosity around 1Ls. You also want to make sure the planet is in a reasonable distance from the star. In some cases the host star does not need a Luminosity around 1Ls. It could be higher if the planet was farther away or lower if the planet is closer. Once you discover the perfect balance you than begin to look at your planet's characteristics. You calculate the mass and radius of the planet in order to find the density of the planet. To find a habitable planet, you will want the density to be at least 3.00g/cm^3 because if it is lower the planet will be made up of too much ice and gas to support life. Although you want a higher density, you do not want too high of a density because than it will have too much metal  and may not be able to support water, which is essential for life. Using the previous information you can calculate the surface pressure, effective temperature and greenhouse effect which all lead you to determine if the planet with be a snowball, a burning planet like Venus, or a habitable world like Earth. </string>
    </entry>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>When looking for a habital planet, I was mainly looking for carbon dioxide (CO2)and water (H2O). These two gasses are what make up a good percentage of the greenhouse effect and without a good percentage of a greenhouse effect you wouldn't be able to produce more water or oxygen. The planet that was selected most habitable had almost the same units and measurements that Earth has. Anything that was close to 1.0 Me and Re (mass of Earth and Radius of Earth) was good to take a look at and put up as most Earth like. Also the distance from the star had to be taken in consideration. 1.0 AU is the distance that Earth is from the sun, so anything close to 1.0 is the same distance as Earth. I do think 0.85589 is a close enough distance from the sun. You would have to make sure that your planet is not too close to the sun or too far from the sun. If you have a planet too close to the sun, the planet would be too hot for any life. A planet too far can become too cold and no life would be able to live on that as well.  The density of the planet plays a big role as well, density for a terristrial planet is ~3 (around 3.0 and up) and ~0.3 and under is considered a gas planet, ~0.4 to 3.0 is considered an ice planet. Density is something that you measure per square feet of a planet (quantity of mass per unit volume). The temperture shown is way to hot and liquid water is anywhere from 233 kelvin to 337 Kelvin (-40F to 146F). That is the ideal temperature for an Earth like planet. Since this is the same temperature as Earth and we have liquid water that can stay in liquid form at these temperatures. The luminosity of a star would always be compared to the sun in our solar system (Ls) and the measurement of our star in our solar system is 1.0 Ls. Anything above 1.0 Ls is bigger than our sun and anything lower is smaller that our sun. Also you to make sure that your sun's lifetime can live over millions or billions of years. Because if you want to live on an Earth like planet, you would want to make sure that your sun has a long life and not die out to quick. If you were to check my projected lifetime of my sun you would see that the star will last for about a trillion years.  </string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>In this project a total of 52 stars were analyzed after looking in the far edges of the universe only a couple habitable planets were found. These planets have the characteristics and have the correct features to potentially sustain life. The planets which have been discovered contain liquid water the surface temperature were adequate to sustain life. Having the following characteristics allowed for a habitable planet
 Distance from Star:  1 AU
Mass:  1 ME
Radius:  1 RE
Density:  1 g/cm
Proposed Surface Pressure:  0 atm
Effective Temperature:  0 K
Greenhouse Effect:  Moderate
The purpose of this exploration was to potentially find a second home for the human race. As a species on earth we are consuming more resources than needed therefore ensuring that we will eventually have to find a new home due to lack of resources, this project helped us ensure that there are other habitable planets to which we may relocate to if needed. The biosignatures that are expected on these planets are single cell organisms, the conditions which would allow for such scenarios would be if the planet is in the exact condition in which we have predicted. With advancements in technology we would be able to identify these biosignatures, with our current techonology it would be very difficult and almost impossible to identify them. 

</string>

    <entry>
      <string>stage.pressrelease.text</string>
      <string>Recently, scientists and I have discovered a planet known as Aryssa, that has been chosen as the best canditate among over 70 stars that had been researched.  This planet isn't too far, it's only about 31.1 light years away, however new forms of transportation would have to become readily available in order to travel there any time soon.  Its host star is much less luminous than ours, meaning the energy emitted from it is much less, but Aryssa orbits it at only .07 AU, relative to Earth's distance from the sun which is equal to 1 AU.  The mass of the planet is higher and also the radius is over twice ours!  This gives the planet a density of 3.149g/cm^3.  The pressure of the planet is less than ours, at only .28 atm, so we'd probably be able to jump pretty high.  Since the star is much less luminous, the planet's effective temperature is only 208 K, not quite warm enough for liquid water, but because of a strong greenhouse effect, its boosted up to over 300 K.  The planet is full of gases necessary for life, including water, ozone, carbon dioxide, etc. and we can find these using gases with easily observable absorption spectra.</string>
